<HEAD>Precede: CARACAS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Cardinal Drops Out of Mediation Effort Between Nicaragua and U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with cardinal unable to arrange
US-Sandinista talks; opposition asking cardinal for help. No pickup. Changes
byline. ^By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cardinal <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> y <PERSON> Bravo </PERSON> said Thursday he was unable to set up conciliation talks between <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, as requested by President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>. Also Thursday, Foreign Minister <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Escoto </PERSON> accused the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government of spreading `` systematic lies'' to discredit <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and its preparations for free elections in 1990. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> publicly asked <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> y Bravo, the Roman Catholic Archbishop of <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>, on Monday to act as a go-between in setting up the talks with the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration resolve its differences with <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s leftist Sandinista regime. The cardinal said he would think about it, but <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Rudi </PERSON> <PERSON> Boone </PERSON> on Tuesday rejected the offer. He said an improvement in relations would depend on a number of factors, including `` an end to Nicaraguan support'' for leftist guerrillas in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Boone </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, also said <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> should hold free and fair elections under international supervision and enter into of a genuine dialogue with opposition groups before the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> agrees to sit down and talk. Referring to <PERSON> Boone </PERSON>'s statement, <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> <PERSON> y </PERSON> <PERSON> Bravo </PERSON> wrote <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> saying that `` for the time being it is not possible to enter into a process of mediation ... because one of the parties has officially set conditions for the dialogue.'' <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> read the <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> y <PERSON> Bravo </PERSON>'s letter at a news conference, expressed thanks to the cardinal, and said he will `` insist through other venues with the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government and President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to accept a dialogue with <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>.'' The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> cut off all aid to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> in 1980, started supporting Contra rebels the next year and slapped an economic embargo on this nation in 1985 to pressure the Sandinistas to hold free and fair elections and sever military ties with Soviet bloc nations. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> administrations have argued that Soviet and <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> military aid to the <LOCATION> Sandinistas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s help to the Salvadoran guerrillas is threatening security in <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. The Sandinistas claim they have been providing only moral support to the Salvadoran rebels. An attempt by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> to hold talks in <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> in 1984 ended in deadlock, with the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration accusing the Sandinistas of failing to negotiate in good faith. The 14-party <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opposition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday asked <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> y Bravo to try and set up talks with the Sandinista government to try and resolve these differences. But the cardinal, himself a sharp critic of the Sandinistas, did not respond immediately. Earlier Thursday, Foreign Minister <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Escoto </PERSON> accused the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration of spreading `` systematic lies'' to discredit <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and denied allegations by Vice President <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> that <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> is allying itself with <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> to form a three way anti-U.S. alliance. Speaking in <LOCATION> Caracas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, where he was attending a Third World meeting, <PERSON> D'Escoto </PERSON> said: `` I would take anything a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government official says with a ton of salt. Systematic lying is an instrument of their foreign policy. The only thing he -LRB- <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> -RRB- needs for his opinions is his mouth.'' <PERSON> D'Escoto </PERSON> also denied recent allegations by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> about <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s election procedures and said the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> were `` strictly complying with the agenda for the elections in February 1990. Critics have said the government stacked a national election board, which will supervise the balloting process, in favor of the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION>. Also, as of June 1 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citizens were required for the first time to get visas to enter <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, making it difficult for American observers to be there.
