<HEAD>Indian Authorities Interrogating U.S., German Pilots</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Authorities are interrogating two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and two West German pilots after Indian air force fighters forced down their small planes near the Pakistani border, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> identified the Americans as <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Haile </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, 57, of <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Carson </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Rocksprings </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. The two, making an around-the-world trip in a Beechcraft Bonanza, were intercepted by the Indian jets on June 16 and forced to land at <LOCATION> Bhuj </LOCATION> airfield in western <LOCATION> Gujarat </LOCATION> state, a <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said. The spokesman, who can not be identified under briefing rules, said the two men were traveling with two West Germans, whose Beechcraft also was ordered to land at <LOCATION> Bhuj </LOCATION>, about 500 miles southwest of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION>. A West German Embassy official, speaking on condition of anonymity, identified the Germans pilots with only their last names as <PERSON> Kuhlmann </PERSON> and <PERSON> Kuffner </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said the planes had strayed about 310 miles off the assigned course and intruded into restricted airspace over <LOCATION> Bhuj </LOCATION>, a marshy wasteland near the border with <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>. Civil aviation authorities cleared the planes to fly from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Delhi </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Bahrain </LOCATION> via <LOCATION> Bombay </LOCATION>, he said. The pilots were first questioned by air force officers and later handed over to federal intelligence officers, he said. A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> offical said a consular officer attended the interrogation. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Privacy Act prevented disclosing more information about the pilots, said the official who can not be identified under briefing rules. Haile and <PERSON> Gilmore </PERSON> departed from the suburban <PERSON> Addison </PERSON> airport in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> three weeks ago. Haile, the owner and president of a Dallas-based engineering firm, has flown around the world twice and is an experienced long-distance pilot, according to his wife, <PERSON> Joan </PERSON>.
