<HEAD>HUD Looking Into Apparent Diversions in Austin Project</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 5 grafs after 6th graf, `Lee refused...,' to UPDATE
with developments in Indianapolis. Picks up 7th graf, `Last week...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal investigators are looking into the apparent diversion of up to $ 90,000 in housing funds intended for poor families living in federally subsidized apartments here, it was reported Thursday. The money was supposed to cover rent and utility bills in 1986 to early 1988 for five families who lived in the housing complexes known as <ORGANIZATION> Interregional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Apartments </ORGANIZATION>, the Austin American-Statesman said. The 99 apartments were shut down by the city in September because of building code violations. `` It may be a while before we can get to it, but it is scheduled for investigation,'' said <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, the Housing and Urban Development regional inspector general in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>. `` Right now, it's waiting in line with a lot of other cases,'' <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> said. `` It's a question of time and manpower.'' <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> refused to say who might have diverted the funds, saying it's their policy not to comment on ongoing investigations In another development, <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> officials in <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> said Thursday that almost a third of the $ 257,012 that federal auditors said might be missing from the agency's office here has been found. Payments have been received or documentation found for $ 80,046.95 from the sale of five foreclosed homes during a 4 -LCB- - year period, said <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Shelley </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Indianapolis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> office In a June 13 report, federal auditors identified 16 <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> transactions for which the agency had n't received payment. Auditors said the proceeds, plus $ 30,486 in damages, should be paid to the government. Authorities and <ORGANIZATION> Indianapolis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realty </ORGANIZATION>, which handled closings on the sales, are looking for documentation of the remaining 11 transactions, which brought $ 176,965.50, officials said. If the transfer of the money ca n't be documented, <PERSON> Shelley </PERSON> said, the government stands to get its money either from <ORGANIZATION> Indianapolis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Realty </ORGANIZATION> or its bonding company. Last week, a private escrow agent from <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> nicknamed `` <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> HUD'' told <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> she diverted millions of dollars from government housing programs. The agent, <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrell </PERSON>, admitted to investigators that she did not forward at least $ 5.5 million to the federal housing agency, saying she donated much of the money to charitable projects to provide housing for the poor. In <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, the principal owner of the <ORGANIZATION> Interregional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Apartments </ORGANIZATION> is <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION> investor <PERSON> Benard </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lifshutz </PERSON>, who said he was aware that some subsidies were taken but he was not involved. Another partner in the project, listed in city records as <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> McGinnis </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, could not be located, the newspaper said. <PERSON> Lifshutz </PERSON> said he and <PERSON> McGinnis </PERSON> are no longer business partners and he had not spoken to <PERSON> McGinnis </PERSON> in months. According to a letter from the city to the <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> inspector general, the apparent diversion of federal utility subsidies took place between August 1986 and February 1988. Former acting City Manager <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Ware </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> members in a memo last year that the exact amount of money taken was hard to determine because the owners' records for those years `` are virtually non-existent.'' City staff at the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, which administers the federally subsidized housing program, said they believe the amount was $ 80,000 to $ 90,000. The department staff first learned of the problem when Interregional tenants complained that their electric, gas, and water services were being disconnected. City records show that dozens of the apartments were overrun with rats and cockroaches; contained exposed and damaged plumbing and wiring; had holes in some of the floors and ceilings; and could not meet minimal city building and safety codes. Police records also show that by 1986 the apartment complexes had become a center of criminal activity, including prostitution and drug dealing. At one point, police records show, one tenant at <ORGANIZATION> Interregional </ORGANIZATION> offered `` drive-up curb service,'' making drug deals through an apartment window.
