<HEAD>Monument Dedicated to War Ace `Pappy' Boyington</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YUMA, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Military officials and former comrades of Col. <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> `` Pappy'' <PERSON> Boyington </PERSON> dedicated a life-size bust Thursday at the <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Station </ORGANIZATION> here to honor the late World War II ace. <PERSON> Boyington </PERSON>'s widow, <PERSON> Josephine </PERSON>, of <LOCATION> Fresno </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, and son, <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, attended the ceremonies at the base, the home of VMA-214, the <ORGANIZATION> Black </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sheep </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Squadron </ORGANIZATION>. The nickname for the group originated around the idea that members of the squadron, formed in the <LOCATION> Solomon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Islands </LOCATION> in 1942, were misfits. <PERSON> Boyington </PERSON> shot down 28 aircraft while fighting in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Theater </LOCATION>, and his squadron accounted for a total of 197 Japanese planes. Shot down Jan. 3, 1944, over <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Boyington </PERSON> spent the rest of the war in a prisoner-of-war camp in <LOCATION> Omori </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. He was mistakenly presumed dead during the war and awarded the Medal of Honor _ the nation's highest decoration for military valor _ posthumously. <PERSON> Boyington </PERSON> died Jan. 11, 1988. The bust was the idea of his longtime friend, <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> `` Hap'' <PERSON> Halloran </PERSON>, who said attending <PERSON> Boyington </PERSON>'s funeral at <ORGANIZATION> Arlington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cemetery </ORGANIZATION> gave him the desire to do something special to commemorate his friend. <PERSON> Halloran </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corps </ORGANIZATION> fighter pilot, was shot down over the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> in January 1945 and met <PERSON> Boyington </PERSON> in a prisoner-of-war camp. `` To see him in real life was a comforting thing. I know probably nothing would happen to us'' because <PERSON> Boyington </PERSON> was there, <PERSON> Halloran </PERSON> said at the ceremonies.
