<HEAD>California Plane Crash Kills Three</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARITA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A single-engine plane that snagged a wire above a 500,000-volt power line crashed Thursday afternoon, killing three people and injuring a fourth. The pilot of the French-made TB-21 <LOCATION> Trinidad </LOCATION> reported engine trouble shortly before the 2:13 p.m. crash near <LOCATION> Placerita </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canyon </LOCATION> about 30 miles northwest of downtown <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> said. The survivor, a teen-age girl, was in critical condition at <ORGANIZATION> Henry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mayo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newhall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Memorial </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Valencia </LOCATION>, said hospital spokeswoman <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Ingram </PERSON>. The pilot and two other passengers were killed. None of the victims' names was immediately released. The four-seat plane hit a static wire, which protects the power line from lightning, said <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Fraudenburg </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION>. The plane missed the power line itself, which carries enough electricity for the needs of 3 million people, <PERSON> Fraudenburg </PERSON> said. DWP crews were assessing the damage to determine if the cable needs to be replaced, <PERSON> Fraudenburg </PERSON> said.
