<HEAD>Utility Votes to Take Private Bids to Restart Nuke Power Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The operator of the <LOCATION> Rancho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seco </LOCATION> nuclear power plant has decided to accept bids for a private takeover of the facility, despite a referendum that called for its shutdown. The 3-2 vote by directors of the <ORGANIZATION> Sacramento </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utility </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday angered many of the activists who have fought for years to shut down the plant, which has nearly a continuous history of operating problems. On March 2, the directors had voted unanimously to abide by the results of the June 6 referendum, in which voters turned down an advisory measure endorsing the <ORGANIZATION> Sacramento </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Municipal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utility </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION>'s plans to keep the plant running. The plant was taken off line June 7 and so far about 400 contract workers have lost their jobs. Utility directors voting with the majority argued that voters merely had forbidden <ORGANIZATION> SMUD </ORGANIZATION> from operating the plant. Divestiture of Rancho Seco `` remains a viable option ... that could free this community from the staggering costs of decommissioning,'' said <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Buonaiuto </PERSON>, president of the utility's board of directors The utility estimates it will cost about $ 200 million to close the plant. Sacramentans for Safe Energy, an anti-Rancho Seco group, has said it will sue to stop efforts to transfer <LOCATION> Rancho </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Seco </LOCATION> to private businesses that might continue to operate it. `` We will wait and see what happens in the 10-day period'' that the utility set to accept bids, said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Remy </PERSON>, an environmental attorney affiliated with the group. `` Our position still is that enough is enough.''
