<SECOND>AM-Massachusetts Deportation,0281</SECOND>
<HEAD>Massachusetts, Federal Officials Agree on Plan to Deport 1,000 Illegal
Aliens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A policy reversal by Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has led state and federal officials to agree on a plan to deport about 1,000 illegal aliens held in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> prisons. In 1985, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> issued an executive order forbidding state investigators from working on deportation cases unless ordered to do so by a court. That order was portrayed as gesture of good will toward illegals at a time when the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration was cracking down. Under the new policy agreed to Tuesday, the state will work with <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> officials to identify and deport inmates of the crowded state and county prison system who are in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> illegally. When possible, the state will work `` aggressively to get these people out on the next plane,'' said Human Services Secretary <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>, who oversees <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>' correction system. Regional <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> director <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Cobb </PERSON>, who met Tuesday with <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> to work out the plan's details and has criticized <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' order, called the agreement `` a step in the right direction.'' About 1,300, or 10 percent, of the approximately 13,000 inmates in state prisons are illegal aliens, according to <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>. Of the 1,300, about 1,000 are eligible for immediate deportation. Most of the inmates involved have been involved in drug dealing, and come from <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Dominican </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, according to <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON>. Some convicted of particularly violent crimes, including four men serving sentences for the rape at <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dan </ORGANIZATION>'s tavern in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bedford </LOCATION> in 1984, will remain in prison, <PERSON> Johnston </PERSON> said.
