<FIRST>r a PM-Timber-Economics     06-22 1491</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Timber-Economics,1525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Northwest's Timber Jobs Declining In Changing Economy</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Thursday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARNARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRANTS PASS, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When GIs came home after World War II, the nation looked to the great forests of the <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> for lumber to build their houses. <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> mills responded, and still supply more than a third of the lumber and plywood used in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` There was always that one more shining hill covered with trees to the west,'' said <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> budget officer <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>. `` Now we find there's a <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ocean </LOCATION> and we fell into it.'' From the western slope of the Cascade Range to the shore of the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>, this is the home of the Douglas fir, the towering king of the ancient forests whose structural strength tops all other lumber. It is also home to the Northern spotted owl, a 14-inch bird that could face extinction because, with rare exceptions, it wo n't nest or hunt anywhere but the dwindling virgin forests that are most prized for timber. While logs are tied up in the legal battle over how much of the national forests can be cut without killing off the spotted owl, record amounts of raw timber grown on private and state land are being shipped for premium prices to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION> without ever seeing the inside of an American mill. `` If a log is of export quality, and is available to be exported, it will be exported,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Mayr </PERSON>, owner of the <ORGANIZATION> Mayr </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> mill in <LOCATION> Hoquiam </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mayr </PERSON> has been reduced to counting his supply in months instead of years while watching a stream of logs being loaded onto ships in <LOCATION> Grays </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION> `` We want to put out logs to the highest value market In recent years the highest value has been offshore,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON>, operations manager for <ORGANIZATION> Weyerhaeuser </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Coos </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION>, where the region's leading exporter of raw logs has started a new mill to produce metric-dimension lumber for the Japanese home-building market Companies can generally get 25 percent more for export logs than they can in the domestic market, said <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> economist <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Flora </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. Boom-and-bust cycles were known to the timber industry before the spotted owl entered the spotlight, but for the first time the pinch is from a shortage of logs rather than rising mortgage rates and dips in the housing market. Eighteen years ago, <PERSON> Brad </PERSON> <PERSON> Wentworth </PERSON> stopped off in the coastal town of <LOCATION> Gold </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> to see some friends on his way to college to study forest management. Now he's 37, a husband and father, and one of the 300 workers at Gold Beach Plywood who will be out of a job this summer when the mill shuts down. `` I got sucked into the mill because it was such good wages,'' <PERSON> Wentworth </PERSON> said. `` I kick myself in the butt now.'' Thirteen other wood products mills in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> have closed this year, putting nearly 2,000 people out of work as the industry enters a new era of high-priced timber in short supply. A referendum Tuesday in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> calls for a ban on exporting state-grown logs and asks <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to make permanent an annually renewed ban on exporting logs grown on federal land. `` The mill is old and inefficient,'' said <LOCATION> Gold </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> mill manager <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Saunders </PERSON>. `` It would take about $ 3 million to bring it up. Why should we put in that kind of investment without knowing there is a stable supply of timber?'' The shortage of timber does n't come as a surprise, but its magnitude does. In 1976, <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> forestry professor <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Beuter </PERSON> reported that little mature timber was left on private land and that the industry would have to depend on national forests, home to most of the old-growth timber, to make it to the next century, when second-growth trees planted before World War II would be ready for harvest. <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>, director of resource services for <ORGANIZATION> Seattle </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Simpson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Timber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, had expected harvests in national forests to decline about 20 percent in <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> this year as the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> revised its long-range management plans He now fears it could drop 50 percent because old-growth forests have been ruled off-limits because of the spotted owl. `` Historically, a lot of the impetus for the management of federal lands in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> was to settle the West and develop it,'' said <PERSON> Beuter </PERSON>, now a consultant in <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>. `` We are sort of at the end of that era now. We are at the point of recognizing that cutting more timber is n't going to create new cities and new economic opportunity in the West. In fact, we are coming around to where saving the forests may create new economic opportunity.'' <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitelaw </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> economics professor, has been a leading proponent of the idea that the Northwest has more to gain from preserving its blue skies, green forests and clear water than from exploiting its resources. `` Most Oregonians receive two paychecks,'' he said. `` One is in dollars. The other comes from the environment. By accounting for all other amenities, I estimate that the environmental paycheck is worth $ 1.3 billion. The paycheck from the timber industry is $ 1.5 billion.'' In 1988, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> national forests supplied 5.4 billion board feet of timber, a third of the region's total harvest from all lands. Where the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> management plans used in the 1980s allowed the annual harvest of 5.5 billion board feet, the limit in the 1990s will be closer to 4.7 billion. Unlike owners of private forests, the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> by law may cut no more timber than it can grow back. It also has to provide for the needs of fish, wildlife, campers, hikers and water quality. Where it once had to answer only to the timber industry, the service now has a crowd of watchdogs panting over its shoulder. The governors of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> want to be sure there is enough timber to sustain the rural economy. Environmental groups demand preservation of old-growth forests. Academics have started offering new management techniques that follow the lead of nature. And there is new unrest inside the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Jeff </PERSON> <PERSON> DeBonis </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Willamette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> timber sale planner, has organized the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ethics </ORGANIZATION>, with a mailing list of about 200. <PERSON> DeBonis </PERSON> wrote in February to <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> claiming the agency is in bed with the industry. `` The question we need to ask concerned citizens is, ` Why should the national forests be sacrificed to an overzealous and greedy industry that liquidated their own lands to make a fast cut?''' he said. <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>'s staff is preparing a detailed response to <PERSON> DeBonis </PERSON>' letter, said spokeswoman <PERSON> Rose </PERSON> <PERSON> Narlock </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> `` Maybe we need some of these things talked about It was a gutsy move on his part.'' <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> has acknowledged that the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> has taken a beating in the courts under the National Environmental Policy Act, evidence <PERSON> DeBonis </PERSON> cites for his argument that too many trees are being cut. While loggers tie yellow ribbons to their trucks and demand more timber, the grim truth is jobs are disappearing, spotted owl or no spotted owl. `` The biggest source of change in employment has been the modernization and automation of the forest products industry,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Wilderness </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> economist <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Olson </PERSON>, who produced a study concluding the decline in timber jobs in the <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> has little to do with cutting old growth in national forests. <LOCATION> Flora </LOCATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> economist, said in the 1970s he figured each 1 million board feet of timber translated into eight timber jobs. That's now down to 1.5 jobs in the high-tech mills and four to five jobs overall. Timber is virtually extinct as a factor in the economies of <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, but still vital in small cities and towns that grew up with it. <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>'s 68,700 wood-products jobs _ almost all of them outside the <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION> area _ account for 5.2 percent of the state's employment <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s 41,800 timber jobs account for 2.1 percent of its employment. In 1986, the most recent figures available, timber accounted for just 6 percent of <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>'s gross state product at $ 2.5 billion and 2.2 percent of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s, at $ 1.6 billion. But <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> economist <PERSON> Con </PERSON> <PERSON> Schallau </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Corvallis </LOCATION> argues timber has a greater impact than that, because it accounts for 38 percent of <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>'s basic economy _ bringing in outside dollars _ and 18 percent of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>'s. While economists may differ over timber's importance, they agree the places that will be hurt worst are towns like <LOCATION> Gold </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, population 1,500, with a payroll of $ 6 million from Gold Beach Plywood. `` If you live in a big city you've got a lot of choices,'' <PERSON> Wentworth </PERSON> said, `` but if you live here you've got to work in the brush or the mill.''
