<HEAD>Massachusetts Town Celebrates 250th Anniversary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>STOCKBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Alice </PERSON> does n't cook here anymore, but this sleepy western <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> town, captured in paint by <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Rockwell </PERSON> and in song by <PERSON> Arlo </PERSON> <PERSON> Guthrie </PERSON>, celebrates its 250th birthday this weekend. Some things have changed since the days when <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> made <LOCATION> Stockbridge </LOCATION> famous to Saturday Evening Post readers. Police Chief <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Obanhein </PERSON>, whose visage <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> used as the model of the `` perfect <ORGANIZATION> Secret </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> man'' and whose enforcement of the litter laws inspired <PERSON> Arlo </PERSON> <PERSON> Guthrie </PERSON>'s ballad `` <PERSON> Alice </PERSON>'s Restaurant,'' has retired. <PERSON> Alice </PERSON> <PERSON> Brock </PERSON> herself no longer has a restaurant. Dr. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Campbell </PERSON>, captured by <ORGANIZATION> Rockwell </ORGANIZATION> while aiming a hypodermic needle at a bare-bottomed youngster scrutinizing his medical degrees, made his last house call in February on his 83rd birthday. But the cat and dog fountain still stands. So does the horse trough proclaiming `` utility is preferable to glamor'' and the line of cane rockers on the veranda of the Red Lion Inn. <LOCATION> Stockbridge </LOCATION>'s charm has proved irresistible to thousands of tourists, who sometimes turn Main Street into a bumper-to-bumper traffic jam. But for about two hours Saturday, <LOCATION> Stockbridge </LOCATION> will reclaim the thoroughfare for a gala parade of brass bands, Boy Scouts, floats, and more than 500 marchers. An old-fashioned picnic and fireworks also are planned. Asked to explain <LOCATION> Stockbridge </LOCATION>'s appeal, Selectman <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Charbonneau </PERSON> responded: `` The people. And the uniqueness of the area.'' <PERSON> Guthrie </PERSON> agreed. `` I grew up in <LOCATION> Stockbridge </LOCATION> and have spent most of my life near there,'' <PERSON> Guthrie </PERSON> said in a telephone interview from his nearby <LOCATION> Berkshire </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION> home. `` Most of the people in town are wonderful and fabulous ... `` It's a place that has retained its turn-of-the-century beauty and sense of history. It's always accommodated a wide variety of people _ artists, wealthy ambassadors, mobsters running booze during Prohibition _ but it does so very reluctantly. `` And in some ways that's just fine. When I was young I did n't understand that kind of small-town politics, but I've learned to actually like it. <PERSON> Guthrie </PERSON>, now the father of teenagers, said <LOCATION> Stockbridge </LOCATION> is `` more a town for older folks,'' adding: `` I do n't recall there being a whole lot to do for a young person and there probably still is n't. I do n't think my kids ever go to <LOCATION> Stockbridge </LOCATION>.'' But <PERSON> Guthrie </PERSON>, who will sing `` Alice's Restaurant'' at a July 4 concert in nearby <LOCATION> Tanglewood </LOCATION>, can still cackle gleefully in anticipation of the town's reaction to his summer plans to market T-shirts emblazoned `` with the Trail of the Garbage'' that will lead tourists on the path of his crime. `` It will be sort of our own version of the Freedom Trail -LRB- in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> -RRB-,'' he said.
