<HEAD>US Skeptical of Soviet Proposal to Consult UN Council on Palestinian
Vote</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is skeptical of a Soviet proposal to seek advice from the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>'s permanent members on proposed elections among Palestinian Arabs on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION>, administration sources say `` We said we were n't interested,'' an official said late Wednesday. The official, who spoke on condition that he not be identified, did not reject the idea outright but said it would not get anywhere `` as far as we're concerned.'' The official said the proposal could complicate efforts to hold elections to choose <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> representatives to negotiate self-rule with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. `` It would only muddy the waters and distract from the -LRB- elections -RRB- idea itself,'' the official said. Participation by the council members would guarantee the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> a role that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> fears would be used to the advantage of the Arabs. The five members of the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> are the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The Soviets, without committing themselves on Palestinian elections, made their proposal during a two-day meeting in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> last week on the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. It was one in a series of conferences on various global problems arranged by the two superpowers. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegation was headed by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>, assistant secretary of state for the <LOCATION> Near </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>, head of the department's policy planning staff. <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Polyakov </PERSON>, senior expert on the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> in the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, led his government's delegation. The Soviet idea was first disclosed in Thursday editions of The Star Tribune of <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION>. The elections were proposed by <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> as a way of breaking the stalemate between the Arabs and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. The idea has qualified <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> support, provided arrangements are satisfactory to the Palestinians and the Arab countries. The <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> has rejected <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s offer as a subterfuge to block the creation of a <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> state. But the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is operating on the assumption that the <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> proposal still has a chance and in any event is the only known vehicle for starting negotiations. For this reason, the official said, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> proposal to consult the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> members on a proper framework received a skeptical <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> response. The official said the Soviets did not endorse or reject <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON>'s proposition As in the past, the Soviets said only that it was `` worthy of consideration.'' In the past, as an inducement to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, the Soviets have said they would be prepared to resume diplomatic relations once negotiations began. But the official said the Soviets did not repeat this offer in the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> sessions. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> broke relations with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> in 1967 when <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> defeated a combination of <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> countries in a six-day war.
