<HEAD>Sandinistas Confiscate Opposition Leaders' Coffee Plantations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cracking down on its critics, the leftist <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> government says it has confiscated coffee plantations and other property belonging to three opposition business leaders. The three _ <PERSON> Nicolas </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolanos </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jaime </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuadra </PERSON> and <PERSON> Arnoldo </PERSON> <PERSON> Aleman </PERSON> _ were linked to the <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Private </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprise </ORGANIZATION>, an opposition group, and have been sharply critical of government regulation of the coffee industry. The confiscation announcement Wednesday came three days after coffee growers from all over the country decided to pull out of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coffee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, calling the regulatory and development-oriented panel useless. An order signed by Agriculture Development Minister <PERSON> Jaime </PERSON> <PERSON> Wheelock </PERSON> and read on state-run <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nicaragua </ORGANIZATION> radio declared the properties of the three men of `` public utility and social interest.'' It did not mention compensation. At a meeting Sunday in <LOCATION> Matagalpa </LOCATION>, 80 miles north of the capital, coffee growers unanimously decided to withdraw from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coffee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. They said the panel, made up of government and private representatives, had ruined the industry. At the meeting, <PERSON> Bolanos </PERSON> accused the government of causing a severe economic crisis through mismanagement, adding that only a `` government of national salvation'' replacing the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> could bring <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> out of recession. Coffee is one of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s main export items and a principal dollar-earner. Commenting on the confiscation order, the Voice of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> accused leaders of the coffee growers of `` urging chaos, disorder, price gouging, smuggling and speculation'' in the industry. The properties were ordered confiscated because these leadaers `` adopted irresponsible attitude that was fomenting anarchy in the coffee industry at a time when the country is going through an economic crisis.'' In a speech Tuesday, President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said `` all anti-patriotic coffee growers will not receive a single cent'' in credit from the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> accused the growers of trying to sabotage an economic austerity plan to reduce inflation, which last year topped 10,000 percent. As part of the plan, the Sandinista government earlier this week ordered a 110 percent devaluation of the cordoba currency, which sent prices of consumer goods and services skyrocketing. <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolanos </PERSON>, the brother of <PERSON> Nicolas </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolanos </PERSON>, called the confiscations `` an act of vengeance by the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> over what happened at the assembly in <LOCATION> Matagalpa </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolanos </PERSON>, a former chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Private </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprise </ORGANIZATION>, had some of his properties in the eastern province of <PERSON> Masaya </PERSON> confiscated by the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> some years ago. In June 1988, the Sandinista government confiscated the <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION> sugar plantation and mills, one of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s largest industries. Sugar is also an important export item.
