<HEAD>Antique Dealer Sees Nothing Wrong with Trying to Sell Mummy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Harlan </PERSON> <PERSON> Berk </PERSON> does n't like to think of the dusty, diminutive Egyptian mummy for sale at his downtown coin and antique shop as a body. `` It's wrapped, and I try to think of it as a piece of antiquity,'' said <PERSON> Berk </PERSON>, standing near the Plexiglas table that for a month has been the resting place for the ancient remains of a woman. `` I try to look at the artwork on the outer wrappings and not focus on the more macabre aspects.'' He's asking $ 50,000 for it, adding, `` The market will tell me if I'm right or wrong.'' He hopes to sell the mummy to a museum or university. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Larson </PERSON>, archivist and Egyptologist at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oriental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION>, said it is illegal to export mummies from <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> without <LOCATION> Egyptian </LOCATION> government permission. But until well into this century, more `` laissez faire'' rules applied. <PERSON> Berk </PERSON>, an antique dealer, said he bought the mummy from an <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> family a month ago, and considers himself free to sell it at his shop. He said he was told that a family member brought the mummy back from <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> about 60 years ago. The mummy, at 4-feet, 1-inch, looks smaller than lifesize as it rests on the table in a temperature-controlled room. On the front are remnants of the pinkish paint and gold leaf used for decoration, with some pictures of Egyptian gods including Horus, the god of heaven; and <PERSON> Osiris </PERSON>, the god of vegetation and later of death. The pictures tell a story of life, death and rebirth _ paths the long-dead woman's loved ones likely envisioned for her, <PERSON> Berk </PERSON> said. `` We do have respect for the individual, even though she's been deceased for several thousand years.'' <PERSON> Larson </PERSON> said he understands why some are disturbed by the sale of human remains, particulary those of American Indians only a couple generations old. `` I do n't think any of us would want to see our grandparents' bodies on display in a museum,'' he said But the time and distance involved for the mysterious Egyptians seem to make viewing them less distasteful. `` Letting the rest of the world study and enjoy these things only creates greater appreciation of the Egyptian culture,'' <PERSON> Berk </PERSON> said.
