 <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> lawmakers have endorsed the notion that while men and women may have been created equal, one definitely takes longer in the bathroom. The state <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> gave final approval Wednesday to a `` potty parity'' bill that would require new buildings to have as many toilets for women as for men. `` It's been suggested that if we ca n't find equity here, can we find it anyplace?'' asked Assemblywoman <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, the bill's sponsor The bill, dubbed a `` squatters' bill of rights'' and a `` back-stall method to enact an equal rights amendment,'' was approved 140-1. The dissenter, <PERSON> Assemblyman </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> <PERSON> Hannon </PERSON>, the No. 2 man in the Assembly's <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> minority, said women should have more toilets than men because they need more time in the bathroom. He cited a <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> undergraduate study that called for women to have six toilets for every four that men have, including urinals. <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> drew laughs when she noted that the same <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> study found that `` a man's biological needs are cared for within 45 seconds, as compared to a woman, who takes 79 seconds.'' Nonetheless, <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> said the law would be a firm step toward equity. The bill has already passed the state <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. There was no indication from Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> whether he'll sign the bill into law.
