<HEAD>Vets' Programs Threatened as Emergency Bill Locked in Limbo</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An emergency spending bill <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has been debating since April has run into new trouble that threatens to cause cuts in some veterans' programs as lawmakers prepare to leave for their Fourth of July holiday. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, in a surprise 218-201 vote, sent the bill back to committee Wednesday. House leaders immediately asked the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to hold new talks in search of a compromise acceptable to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Democrats. With warnings of service cuts at veterans' hospitals and with the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> scheduled to begin a two-week recess on Friday, there was increasing pressure on <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to complete the task and leaders searched for another way to keep veterans programs running while other subjects continued in dispute. The key dispute is over an $ 821 million drug law enforcement amendment which <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Democrats were trying to push past the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who has threatened a veto. By beating the $ 3.5 billion emergency spending bill in an early procedural vote, Republicans were able to avoid voting on the anti-drug spending, which is opposed by the president as wasteful despite its political popularity. All but five Republicans voted against the bill and 52 Democrats joined the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> lawmakers, partly because of a <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> memo highlighting pork barrel spending in the measure. The tally was a surprise defeat for the newly installed <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> leadership. Speaker <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> had confidently predicted they would prevail. `` There are going to be times when the unexpected occurs. We will have our ups and downs,'' said <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Majority Whip <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, D-Pa., who said leaders had not pressured Democrats to keep in line The bill, under congressional budget rules, is supposed to provide money only for `` dire emergencies'' which the government must attend to before Sept. 30, the end of the current fiscal year. There is no disagreement over the largest single item, $ 1.2 billion for the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> to cover a shortfall in money for medical care, compensation and pensions, and in other areas. Congressional leaders Wednesday night began exploring a short-term bill for only veterans' programs to prevent major disruptions, according to Democratic and <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> aides who spoke on condition they not be identified. Final details were still being worked out, but such a bill would carry the Veterans programs through July 22, giving <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> extra time to iron out the drug and other disputes, the aides said. Nearly $ 900 million would be added to the federal guaranteed student loan program, $ 342 million to cover the cost of fighting last year's widespread forest fires, and $ 423 million for foster care and adoption. The food stamp program would be increased $ 225 million, aid to the unemployed $ 90 million, and refugee assistance 100 million. However, influential lawmakers also used the must-pass legislation as a vehicle for cherished spending projects for their constituents. For example, <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, included $ 75 million to rebuild a radiotelescope in his The White House said Wednesday that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would sign the bill, even with most of those constituent projects, if the drug money were left out and some budget gimmicks which threatened future excess spending were deleted. The gimmicks included moving the dates on paychecks for some federal workers up one day, so the money would count against this fiscal year instead of fiscal 1990. Another accounting change would allow <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to dodge agreed-upon spending limits for housing and related agencies.
