<HEAD>Dollar Plunges, Stocks Slip</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar continued its slide against the Japanese yen on Thursday while the key index on the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> inched down. The dollar ended the day's trading at 141.40 yen, down 3.55 yen from Wednesday's 144.95-yen finish. The currency opened at 141.75 yen and fell further while fluctuating between 140.35 yen and 141.75 yen. The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which gained 111.81 points Wednesday, lost 20.31 points, or 0.06 percent, finishing at 33,324.97. The index, which moved higher during the morning session, suffered a setback in the afternoon. Dealers said the index fell as profit-takers sold issues, while others stepped off to the sidelines in the absence of market-affecting incentives. A trader said the market, which suffered consecutive losses last week, has not fully recovered its strength. In currency dealings, traders said the dollar's decline followed sharp overnight retreats on overseas markets. <PERSON> Minori </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeuchi </PERSON>, a dealer with <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, said the majority of investors have lost confidence in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> unit after recent market movements. `` Some trust investment companies and foreign investors bought the dollar when it approached 140.25 yen, but many participants sold it to reduce the amount of the currency at hand,'' she said. Ms. <PERSON> Takeuchi </PERSON> said the market sold the dollar to avoid losing profits, while watching how far the currency can fall to determine the market direction. `` Nothing has changed in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy, so the dollar would eventually return to its previous level, somewhere around 130 yen,'' she said, `` The market thinks this is what the central bank also intends.'' <ORGANIZATION> Kyodo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> quoted a central bank official as saying it is `` desirable'' for the yen to be a bit higher against the dollar to forestall inflation. Attributing the yen's surge to dollar-selling by speculative investors in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, the official said the yen's further rise will help correct the trade imbalance between <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> reportedly intervened in the market Thursday to sell the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency to keep it lower against the yen. Neither the action nor the amount were confirmed because the central bank does not comment on its monetary activities.
