<HEAD>Ruling Unlikely to Change Policies Against Using Rape Victims' Names</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Scotus Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling allowing newspapers to identify rape victims in some instances is unlikely to change voluntary policies against doing so, a newspaper executive said. The court ruled 6-3 that The <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Jacksonville </LOCATION> weekly newspaper, does n't have to pay $ 97,500 to a rape victim whose name was published in 1983. Wednesday's ruling limits states' power to punish the reporting of truthful information that is lawfully obtained. Many news organizations, including <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION>, voluntarily withhold names of victims of sex crimes. The newspaper's lawyers said the woman's name was published inadvertently. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Weitzel </PERSON>, managing editor of The <ORGANIZATION> Miami </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION>, said he did n't think the decision will change what newspapers do He pointed out that the American press has become more sensitive to privacy issues in recent years. `` I think all this really does is say you've got to make the judgment yourselves,'' said <PERSON> Weitzel </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Newspaper </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Editors </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. The committee filed a court brief on the side of the Star. `` It was a pretty straightforward win,'' <PERSON> Weitzel </PERSON> said. `` It bascially says, yes, you can go after a newspaper based on privacy, but it must be on very narrow grounds.'' The justices ruled that a state can punish the publication of lawfully obtained information `` only when narrowly tailored to a state interest of the highest order.'' That interest was not present in the Star's case, the court found. Allowing censorship for an interest of `` the highest order'' will have little practical application because that terminology previously has been used only for national security matters, said attorney <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Rahdert </PERSON>, who represented the Star. `` It raises the fundamental question of whether a privacy issue could ever be an interest of the highest order,'' <PERSON> Rahdert </PERSON> said. He said the ruling could have a wide ranging effect against attempts at censorship. The victim's lawsuit was based on a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> law that outlaws printing, publishing or broadcasting the names of sex crime victims. <PERSON> Weitzel </PERSON> said the editors' group has long questioned the constitutionality of the law. <PERSON> Mitch </PERSON> <PERSON> Franks </PERSON>, assistant deputy state attorney general, said he was uncertain what impact the court's decision would have on the law. `` We would urge, in the interest of protecting the victims of crime, that the news media continue to adhere to their policy of not publishing the names of rape victims,'' <PERSON> Franks </PERSON> said. Star publisher <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> said he was pleased with the ruling but regretted the award was n't reversed by state courts. `` We were being denied -LRB- the right -RRB- to publish the truth,'' <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> said. `` It constituted prior restraint.'' The rape victim's name had been obtained from a report posted, apparently by mistake, in the press room of the <ORGANIZATION> Duval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sheriff </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. Had the court allowed the award to stand it could have lead to passage of laws to prevent the publication of victim's names in other types of crimes, <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON> said. `` A person being raped is no worse than a person being killed,'' he said.
