<SECOND>PM-Mayors,0672</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayors Conference Ends on Discordant Note</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The new leader of the nation's mayors is confident the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration will pay attention to urban needs. But her optimism was n't shared by all her colleagues at the end of their annual conference. <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Kathryn </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitmire </PERSON>, a Democrat who is mayor of the city President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> calls home, assumed the presidency of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mayors </ORGANIZATION> as the group ended its five-day annual meeting Wednesday. The mayors adjourned on a discordant note with an unprecedented floor fight over future leadership of the conference. The contest was decided along party lines with the selection of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s Mayor <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON>, a Democrat and outspoken critic of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration, as a future president of the conference. <PERSON> Whitmire </PERSON> maintained an optimistic and conciliatory tone toward the administration following the meeting and praised Cabinet members and other administration officials who spoke to the mayors. `` After hearing from them, we are optimistic that our issues will be on their agenda,'' she said. But mayors called on the White House to provide support for increased federal aid to cities and for urban problems of drugs, crime, homelessness and poverty. The mayors asked <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for an immediate $ 822 million increase in the fight against drugs. `` Urban America has been neglected over the last eight years, and the need is even greater than before,'' said Mayor <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Holland </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Trenton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, outgoing president of the group. <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON>'s election capped a partisan fight for the job that puts him in line to be president of the organization _ and leading spokesman for the nation's mayors _ in 1991. <PERSON> Whitmire </PERSON> voted against <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> and in favor of a Republican <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Althaus </PERSON>, mayor of <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, in a vote that was otherwise decided largely along party lines. <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> said that at issue in the dispute was whether mayors were willing to `` have an aggressive voice'' against <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s urban policies. `` I do n't think this is the time for mayors to sit back and just go along, to say everything's all right in our cities,'' <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> said. `` Everything is not all right in our cities. ... The Federal government has walked away from our cities.'' The mayors devoted scant attention during their meetings to the unfolding scandals at the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> _ the agency that handles most federal aid to cities. The scandals include evidence of massive embezzlement and the steering of millions of dollars in grants to projects based on political favoritism during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. `` Frankly, our efforts with <ORGANIZATION> HUD </ORGANIZATION> will be primarily aimed at the future rather than the past,'' <PERSON> Whitmire </PERSON> said. `` We do believe it is the duty of Mr. <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> -LRB- Secretary <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON> -RRB- to address the scandals. ... Our goal will not be to chastise someone now gone from the agency about what was done or not done last year.'' The conference approved unanimously a policy statement calling on the administration and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to raise federal taxes to reduce the deficit and to finance greater spending on urban problems. The mayors also called for an outright ban on possession, as well as manufacture and sale, of `` military-type'' semiautomatic assault weapons. That goes far beyond <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s ban on the importation of foreign-made assault weapons and would, if it became law, render illegal thousands of such weapons now owned by Americans. The mayors' resolutions become the new policies that will guide conference lobbying in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. They approved a resolution saying mayors `` deplore'' recent <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decisions that are weakening affirmative action programs and `` making it more difficult to ensure equal opportunities in employment for all Americans.'' Other resolutions called for tougher action against drugs, poverty, homelessness and AIDS. But in an earlier committee, mayors deleted a proposal by <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON> to encourage free distribution of needles to drug addicts as a way to reduce spread of AIDS.
