<FIRST>r a PM-AIDS-Newborns     06-22 0608</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS-Newborns,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>Test May Speed AIDS Treatment of Newborns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With a new test, doctors may be able to begin treating AIDS-infected babies soon after birth rather than waiting more than a year to make sure they truly carry the virus, doctors reported today. Babies of infected women have about a one in three chance of picking up the AIDS virus from their mothers. But until about age 16 months, there is no foolproof way of sorting out which infants are infected and which are not. Therefore, doctors have been unable to try early treatment with the AIDS medicine AZT. The drug has been shown to help _ though not cure _ youngsters with more advanced disease. Doctors caution, however, that the test may miss some infected babies, and it is still too difficult to be used routinely. The technique, known as polymerase chain reaction, or PCR, can spot the genes of viruses that have invaded blood cells. `` It's something of a breakthrough. We have been very hindered by the fact that we do n't have diagnostic tests in infants,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Martha </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. `` We need that critically,'' she added, `` because people would like to start treatment with AZT very early on. But you are stuck with treating every child born to a -LRB- virus -RRB- positive mother with a fairly toxic drug, and you'll be treating some kids who do n't have the infection and do n't need it.'' Ordinarily, doctors check for AIDS infections by testing the blood for antibodies to the virus. Those who carry antibodies are presumed to be infected. This method is worthless for newborns. Babies whose mothers were infected will carry their mothers' AIDS antibodies for months, even if the babies themselves are not infected. `` This will be the key role of PCR,'' commented Dr. <PERSON> Cody </PERSON> <PERSON> Meissner </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>. `` We will be able to do a test on the baby's blood in the first weeks of life, and hopefully this will differentiate between kids who are truly infected and those who are simply born to women who are infected.'' Doctors have been reluctant to treat all newborns of infected mothers with AZT until they can find out which ones are truly infected. Otherwise they would be giving the toxic drug to twice as many uninfected babies as infected ones. <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> and colleagues at six <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> hospitals tried out the test on newborns of women infected with the AIDS virus. They report their results in the New England Journal of Medicine. In the study, the test revealed AIDS infections in five of seven newborns who later went on to develop AIDS. It also showed infection in one of eight newborns who later had non-specific symptoms, such as swollen lymph glands, that could have been caused by the AIDS virus. The test results were negative in nine infants who remained well. While childhood AIDS infections are rare in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, they are becoming a major health hazard in parts of <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. Another study in the journal describes the results of a study on 475 infants who were born to infected mothers at two hospitals in <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION>. The research, directed by Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryder </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Kinshasa </LOCATION>, concludes that AIDS may already have increased infant mortality there by 15 percent. The study found that women with more advanced AIDS infections are more likely to pass the virus to their babies during pregnancy. Infected women are also more apt to deliver babies who are premature or unusually small.
</TEXT>
