 Rain continued to soak much of the East today, worsening flooding in several states, while a summer chill brought record low temperatures and snow to the <LOCATION> Rockies </LOCATION>. Showers and thunderstorms reached from <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and western <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state across western <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Carolinas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> W. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, got a soaking as 1 -RCB- inches of rain fell in 25 minutes Showers also covered eastern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> state, eastern <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>. Flood watches were posted in <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Carolinas </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Virginias </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Overnight temperatures tied or set record lows in <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>. It was 44 degrees in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Springs </LOCATION> on Wednesday evening, 2 degrees below the record for the date set in 1982. Early today, Casper, <LOCATION> Wyo. </LOCATION>, tied its record low for the date of 40 degrees set in 1957. Light snow was falling by midnight over parts of the <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> mountains, with 8 inches of new snow at <LOCATION> Echo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION>. Roads were icy in come moutain areas. Rain also was scattered across parts of <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATI