<HEAD>Author's Admirers Gain Victory in Fight to Save Haunt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALINAS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Preservationists and admirers of author <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinbeck </PERSON> have won a temporary victory in their battle to save a hotel he once frequented. <ORGANIZATION> Monterey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> ruled Wednesday the city failed to obtain an adequate environmental impact report before ordering the Cominos Hotel torn down. The building, built in 1874 and remodeled in 1919, was visited often and mentioned in several works by <PERSON> Steinbeck </PERSON>, famous for such books as `` The Grapes of Wrath'', `` East of Eden'' and `` Of Mice and Men.'' The city decided in April to raze the hotel for a parking lot, office building and museum. But the <ORGANIZATION> Monterey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Historical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> sued, saying the environmental analysis was deficient. The group actively promotes <PERSON> Steinbeck </PERSON>'s connections to the agricultural region. Preliminary studies indicate it would cost $ 4.5 million to refurbish the hotel. <PERSON> Steinbeck </PERSON>, who won the Nobel and Pulitzer prizes, died in 1968.
