<TEXT>
 The Who _ the guitar - and drum-smashing rock band that once sneered, `` Hope I die before I get old'' _ launched its 25th anniversary tour, and nothing more than a tambourine got broken The graying rockers performed `` My Generation'' and 39 other songs at a small arena here for an audience of about 5,000 people, some of whom were not even born when the anthem of youthful bravado was recorded in 1966. The Who is just one of a spate of old rock bands hitting the road this year to coax Baby Boomers back into stadiums and concert halls. <PERSON> Ringo </PERSON> <PERSON> Starr </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Doobie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Allman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> will tour this summer, with the <ORGANIZATION> Rolling </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stones </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> McCartney </PERSON> following this fall. The Who splintered after a `` farewell tour'' in 1982-83 but regrouped for its 25th anniversary. Dressed in a baggy gray suit with his hair in a ponytail, <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Townshend </PERSON> leaped in the air and banged power chords on his guitar with his trademark windmill motion. But in a concession to age and hearing damage caused by years of loud music, <PERSON> Townshend </PERSON> strummed an acoustic guitar for most of the show. Singer <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Daltrey </PERSON> spun his microphone in the air and banged two tambourines together until one shattered and he had to toss it aside. The Who performed a series of their hits during the more than three-hour show, including `` Wo n't Get Fooled Again,'' `` Who Are You,'' `` <PERSON> Baba </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Reilly </PERSON>,'' `` Substitute'' and `` Ca n't Explain.'' <PERSON> Townshend </PERSON> played three songs from his upcoming album, `` The Iron Man.'' Bassist <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Entwistle </PERSON> also performed solo. The three surviving band members were supplemented by 11 musicians, including a five-piece horn section. The Who's original drummer, <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> <PERSON> Moon </PERSON>, died in 1978. Except for two indoor performances of `` Tommy'' in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, the summertime tour is set for outdoor stadiums. The band made a last-minute exception in <LOCATION> Glens </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Falls </LOCATION>, an upstate <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> city of 20,000 where The Who rented the civic center for nearly two weeks of rehearsal. The tour has been criticized by many in the music community, who note that <PERSON> Townshend </PERSON>, <PERSON> Entwistle </PERSON> and <PERSON> Daltrey </PERSON> have n't enjoyed the same financial success with individual tours and records as they did with The Who. The cover of the current Musician magazine features a drawing of the band members as the centerpiece of a dollar bill. The tour moves to <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION>, the city that hosted the last performance of The Who before their breakup.
