<HEAD>Official Media Carry Faculty Statement on Katyn Blame</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government-run media today published a university resolution blaming the Soviet secret police for the massacre of Polish soldiers at <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> in World War II. It was the most direct statement of blame reported by the official press. The <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> faculty condemned what it called efforts to obscure `` the basic fact known in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and the world for nearly half a century. Namely: the <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> crime committed on thousands of Polish officers interned by the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in 1939 was committed by <ORGANIZATION> NKVD </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> secret police -RRB- bodies.'' The resolution was carried by the official <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> news agency and was published in the daily pro-government <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Slowo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Poszechne </ORGANIZATION> newspaper. In recent months, the Polish government has moved toward rejecting the official version of the <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> massacre, which says the 4,200 officers were shot by the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> in 1941 after <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> invaded the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Although discussion of <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> was taboo in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> for four decades, most Poles and historians in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> believe the slayings were carried out by the Soviet secret police on <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>'s order in 1940 while the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> were allied. The officers, the cream of Polish society called up from the reserves and interned by the Soviets shortly after the outbreak of the war, were shot in the back of the head and dumped in mass graves in <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION>, near the Soviet city of <LOCATION> Smolensk </LOCATION>. The fate of another 10,000 officers, interned at two other Soviet camps, has never been revealed. They are also presumed to have been executed. The Polish side of a joint commission investigating `` blank spots'' in Polish-Soviet history has reported the tentative conclusion of Soviet responsibility for <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION>, and a government spokesman has said there is circumstantial evidence. But there has been no direct statement assigning blame and no response from the Soviet side of the joint commission. The resolution said, `` The maneuvers around the <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> crime consist in attempts to create a false appearance that despite obviousness, the <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> case is very unclear and calls for long-term research. `` Unfortunately, the Polish-Soviet commission of <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> historians is also being used as a tool in these maneuvers.'' The unanimous faculty statement critcized efforts to `` create a cover and an excuse for all those who for nearly half a century have tried to falsify the truth about <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION>, thus becoming the supporters of the terrible crime.'' The official media in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> have written about <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> this year, and in April, soil from the <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> graves was sent to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> by an official delegation. The official tablet on a <LOCATION> Katyn </LOCATION> monument in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> that blamed the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> has been removed.
