<FIRST>r a PM-Epilepsy-Defects 1stLd-Writethru a0466 06-22 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Epilepsy-Defects, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0466,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>Epilepsy Drug Linked to Birth Defects</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with two grafs to tighten, DELETE misspelled `principal.'
PICKS UP 3rd grav pvs, ``Physicians who ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A drug used to treat epilepsy during pregnancy to prevent birth defects may itself harm the unborn baby, scientists reported today. In the report, doctors linked the drug Tegretol, or carbamazepine, with minor facial abnormalities and retardation. Several other drugs to treat epilepsy, which afflicts an estimated 4.9 million Americans, also have been shown to be bad for the fetus. `` Physicians who treat women with seizures are in a very difficult position,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lacro </PERSON>, whose study appears in the New England Journal of Medicine. `` This is the drug of choice, because it seemed to be safe. We ca n't say that anymore.'' <ORGANIZATION> Ciba-Geigy </ORGANIZATION>, which makes Tegretol, said the study is a reminder that the risks and benefits of anticonvulsant drugs need to be weighed carefully, but the medicine should still be considered for epileptics who want to have children. `` We feel that our past data show that Tegretol is a good option for epileptic women. We still feel that way,'' said spokeswoman <PERSON> Cathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Kernen </PERSON>. <PERSON> Lacro </PERSON>, a pediatrician at <ORGANIZATION> Children </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, was a co-author of the study directed by Dr. <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyons </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California-San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diego </ORGANIZATION>. The report found evidence that women who took Tegretol during pregnancy were more likely to produce babies with delayed development and mental retardation. They also were more likely to have unusual facial formations _ including upward slanting eyes, long upper lips and short noses _ and incomplete development of finger nails. Studies have shown that severe epileptic seizures during pregnancy can temporarily interrupt the flow of blood to the fetus, causing brain damage. However, epileptic women have an increased risk of producing babies with minor birth defects, even if they do n't have seizures during their pregnancies. `` Counseling has to start before pregnancy for these women,'' said <PERSON> Lacro </PERSON>. `` If the woman has severe enough seizures and needs the medicine, then by all means you have to give it. But there is no completely safe therapy other than being off medications.'' The researchers first identified the pattern of birth defects in eight children who had been exposed to the drug before birth. They confirmed it by evaluating 48 other children whose mothers had taken the medicine. They found that 11 percent of those exposed had facial abnormalities, 26 percent had incomplete finger nails and 20 percent were slow to develop. Only one youngster with delayed development was old enough to take an intelligence test. That child, a 6 year old, had an IQ of 65. <ORGANIZATION> Ciba-Geigy </ORGANIZATION> criticized the study for `` serious methodological problems.'' It noted that the doctors used women who did not have epilepsy in a comparison group. The higher risk of birth defects among the children of the epileptic women might have resulted from the epilepsy, not the medications. <PERSON> Lacro </PERSON> said: `` I think that what we are seeing is due to the drug. If the changes that we saw were due to seizures alone, then we would see the same pattern of malformations for all kinds of seizure drugs. I think the defects are drug specific, but I ca n't prove that.''
</TEXT>
