<HEAD>Airline Passengers Suffer Food Poisoning After In-Flight Snack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A jet made an emergency landing when 98 of the 139 passengers suffered dizziness and nausea after eating a snack aboard the plane, and seven people remained hospitalized today, officials said. None of the airliner's eight crew members ate the food, said <PERSON> Dareen </PERSON> <PERSON> Khan </PERSON>, an Emirates Airline spokesman. The A-300 Airbus was en route Wednesday from <LOCATION> Dhaka </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bangladesh </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Dubai </LOCATION>, in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION>, when the people fell ill after eating a light meal consisting of chicken, <PERSON> Dareen </PERSON> said. The meal was catered in <LOCATION> Karachi </LOCATION> by the Midway Hotel run by <ORGANIZATION> Pakistan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, he said. Samples of the food on board were sent to laboratories to be examined. Medical officials said the seven passengers still hospitalized suffered from dehydration but none was seriously ill. Fifty-two passengers spent the night in hospitals but 45 were released today, <PERSON> Dareen </PERSON> said Most of the affected passengers were Bangladeshis, he said.
