<HEAD>Rebel Leader Says Summit Will Fail Without Govt-rebel</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with Angolan president leaving for summit;
reports he will meet Savimbi, list of countries expected at summit. No
pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOA ESPERANCA, Angola (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An African summit to resolve <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s 14-year-old civil war will fail without talks between the rebels and the government, guerrilla leader <PERSON> Jonas </PERSON> <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> said before today's meeting. Speaking at his bush camp Wednesday, <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> also said that `` never in 14 years of war have we come so close'' to peace. Angolan President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> dos </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON> left the capital, <LOCATION> Luanda </LOCATION>, early today for <LOCATION> Gbadolite </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION>, where leaders of 22 African nations were gathering for the conference. In an interview with <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> published today, Zairean President <PERSON> Mobutu </PERSON> <PERSON> Sese </PERSON> <PERSON> Seko </PERSON> said <PERSON> dos </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON> would meet <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> during the summit. But <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON>, head of the rebel <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> for the Total Independence of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, made no mention of talks with <PERSON> dos </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON> during his news conference Wednesday in <LOCATION> Boa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Esperanca </LOCATION>, in southern <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>. Before leaving for <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION>, <PERSON> dos </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON> commuted the death sentences of 50 <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> rebels condemned for high treason and terrorism between 1981 and 1987, the state news agency <ORGANIZATION> ANGOP </ORGANIZATION> reported. <ORGANIZATION> ANGOP </ORGANIZATION> reported Wednesday that the government released 700 rebel prisoners June 2. The prisoners reportedly renounced the rebel movement and accepted the government's offer of clemency, the dispatch said. The goal of the summit was to clear the way for peace talks between <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s Marxist government and the rebels. <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> said his delegation in <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION> was flexible about procedures leading to elections and formation of a national government. But the rebels do not want any amnesty or clemency that would imply they are criminals, <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> said. `` Our army, 75,000 men in the field, will not accept amnesty, clemency or integration,'' <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> said. `` That wording has a political context that means -LRB- the rebel army -RRB- is considered criminal. Our army was not defeated and is not going to be defeated.'' <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> said he had agreed to stay out of the negotiations and would not demand a role in any transitional government. He said, however, that he would continue to head his party and also wants to participate in free elections within two years of a formal cease-fire. The government has rejected elections, saying it wants to maintain one-party rule, with some rebels participating in the administration. Under a peace plan put forward by <PERSON> dos </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON>, <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> would go abroad and recognize the legitimacy of the government, and the rebel movement would then be integrated into the one-party state. <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> vetoed all these proposals. In six months, half the 50,000 Cuban soldiers who have supported the Angolan government will have left <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> under a U.S.-mediated peace agreement reached in December. <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON>'s U.S.-backed rebels have been fighting a guerrilla war to force the <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> - and Soviet-assisted government to share power since shortly after <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> gained independence from <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> in 1975 In addition to <PERSON> dos </PERSON>