<HEAD>Panel Wants to Meet With Ortega as it Monitors Nicaraguan Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 2nd graf to correct name to Curtin sted Curtis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A private panel formed to monitor the upcoming Nicaraguan elections says it plans to conduct polls in that country and seek a meeting with President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>. However, <PERSON> Curtin </PERSON> <PERSON> Winsor </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, co-chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Bipartisan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> and Fair Elections in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, expressed concern Wednesday about <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>'s recent announcement that it will require <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> visitors to have visas beginning July 1. Visas have not been required of Americans before. `` This has an element to it which suggests restriction, restriction for press and foreign observer presence, and we hope that will not be the case. It is a matter of some concern, however,'' <PERSON> Winsor </PERSON>, a former <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration ambassador to <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION>, told reporters. In a letter to <PERSON> Leonor </PERSON> <PERSON> Huper </PERSON>, charge d'affaires of the Nicaraguan embassy in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Winsor </PERSON> and co-chairman <PERSON> Gaylord </PERSON> <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> senator from <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION>, said the commission plans to send its six commissioners and several staff members to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> sometime this summer. The letter also asked for visa applications. <PERSON> Margarita </PERSON> <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON>, press officer for the <ORGANIZATION> Nicaraguan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>, said she assumes the visas will be granted, but `` the official position is that the only people who will be allowed to be observers are those that have been invited to be observers by the government.'' `` There is really no restriction on the visas, unless someone is really undesirable,'' Ms. <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> said. `` There is no new qualification that people must go through simply because they are Americans.'' <PERSON> Winsor </PERSON> spoke at a news conference at which the commission released a report saying international observers, press and broadcast media must be free to travel throughout <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> during the campaign to monitor the election process. The Nicaraguan elections are scheduled for February 1990. Ms. <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON> said the embassy had not yet received a copy of the report. <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> did not attend the news conference but said in a statement a number of delegation trips are planned to examine <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s political climate The first delegation plans to go to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> in late July or early August and will request a meeting with <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said. `` Another integral part of the commission's activities will include a series of polls,'' <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> said. `` The first poll will examine the political and economic climate in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and how the Nicaraguan people feel about the possibility of free elections.'' After that, he said, polls comparing support for opposition and government candidates are planned. The commission released letters seeking meetings with President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>. <PERSON> Winsor </PERSON> told reporters it was uncertain whether the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, whose members were chosen by <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, `` will operate fairly.'' Commission member <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Bendixen </PERSON>, a Democrat and international political consultant, said, `` Even though there are some questions about the composition of the council which may or may not be valid, it is by the actions of the electoral council that they should be judged.'' `` If we find that the decisions of the electoral council are being arrived at by consensus, I think that would be a very positive point,'' <PERSON> Bendixen </PERSON> said. `` If on the other hand most of the votes of the electoral council are 4-1 or 3-2, always in favor of the Sandinista position, then I think the entire electoral process in <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> should be questioned.'' The commission, which held three days of hearings in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> May 9-11, is sponsored by the conservative <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Freedom </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>.
