<HEAD>Giscard d'Estaing Calls for Joining of Main Opposition Parties</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former President <PERSON> Valery </PERSON> <PERSON> Giscard </PERSON> d'Estaing has called for unifying <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>'s conservative parties and said this is the only way to wrest power from the Socialists. Giscard d'Estaing made the comments in an interview published today in the newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Le </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Figaro </ORGANIZATION> and in comments on television Wednesday night. He is president of the <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> French </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION>, a federation of five small center-right parties. The other main opposition party is the neo-Gaullist Rally for the Republic. Giscard d'Estaing's comments came after his party and the Rally for the Republic joined forces in European <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> elections during the weekend. The list of candidates put forward by the parties finished first with 28.9 percent of the vote, leading <PERSON> Laurent </PERSON> <PERSON> Fabius </PERSON>' Socialist list which had 23.6 percent. <PERSON> Simone </PERSON> <PERSON> Veil </PERSON>'s separate centrist list won 8.4 percent of the vote `` It was division that caused the opposition to lose'' last year's presidential and legislative elections, Giscard d'Estaing said. `` It is union that will cause it to win.'' <PERSON> Jacques </PERSON> <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON>, the president of the Rally for the Republic who lost his bid last year to unseat Socialist President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, reacted coolly to Giscard d'Estaing's idea. He told today's opening session of the party's <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> there would be no `` fusion'' of the two parties. `` We have no intention of fusing with anybody, but reinforcing the links of solidarity'' between the opposition groups, he said. Giscard d'Estaing said a convention of the opposition parties should be held soon and a new, unified party created before the end of the year. Such a party, he said, would still be a place where ideas could be debated. The Socialists have the advantage of a single party, and while that party has its different wings, once decisions are made, or candidates designated, its leadership usually pulls together. It is the lack that cohesiveness that troubles the opposition. In last year's presidential elections, <PERSON> Chirac </PERSON> had to battle not only <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>, but the <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> French </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democracy </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Barre </PERSON> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Jean-Marie </PERSON> <PERSON> Le </PERSON> <PERSON> Pen </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON> calmly ran his own campaign, with only the small Communist thorn in his side.
