<HEAD>Southern African Officials Oppose International Ivory Ban</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> opposes an international effort to ban the ivory trade, a government spokesman said today. <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Botswana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Zimbabwe </LOCATION>, which must cull their elephants to keep the population under control, say such a ban could drive up the price of illegal ivory and does n't take into account legal ivory exports that generate income for conservation programs. `` Our basic position is that we do not support a total ban on the ivory trade worldwide,'' said <PERSON> Bosman </PERSON> <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON> said <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> wanted to make its position known but does not plan to campaign in support of ivory trade. `` In <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> we have a very healthy elephant population that must be culled or it will simply destroy its own environment,'' he said. `` The selling of the ivory in a legal manner makes good sense.'' <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> earns $ 2 million annually from the sale of elephant tusks at the culling program in Kruger National Park, <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON> said. The money is spent on animal research and maintaining the park, he added. <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Pitman </PERSON>, chairman of the Zimbabwean conservation group the <ORGANIZATION> Zambezi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, said there is a question whether bans `` really work or whether they merely raise prices and drive trade underground.'' Soaring ivory prices in the last decade have fueled a killing spree that has cut <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s elephant population from an estimated 1.5 million in the 1970s to less than 700,000 today, experts say. An average tusk weighs 11 pounds and can fetch $ 109 a pound on the international market. This month, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, the 12-nation <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> have imposed bans on ivory imports that make elephant poaching profitable. The <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> consume up to 75 percent of the ivory in world markets. The 102-member Convention In Trade Of Endangered Species will consider such a ban in an October meeting in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>, one country that supports a total ban on the trade, today announced plans to destroy 12 tons of ivory the government has seized from poachers, and it urged other nations to do the same. President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> arap </PERSON> <PERSON> Moi </PERSON> gave no specific date for the incineration.
