<HEAD>Court Makes It Easier for Communities to Turn Down Volume on Rock
Concerts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today made it easier for communities to turn down the volume on rock concerts, upholding <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s effort to avoid ear-splitting noise levels in Central Park. The justices, by a 6-3 vote, said officials may require sponsors of rock concerts in the park's <ORGANIZATION> Naumberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Acoustic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bandshell </ORGANIZATION> to use a sound system operated by a city-designated engineer. That requirement does not violate the freedom-of-expression guarantees of the Constitution's First Amendment, Justice <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> wrote for the court. The decision reversed a federal appeals court ruling that said city officials had to devise a `` less restrictive'' way to satisfy their concern over noise levels. `` This less-restrictive-alternative analysis has never been a part of the inquiry into the validity of a time, place and manner regulation'' on expression, <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said. He added: `` The city's sound amplification guideline is narrowly tailored to serve the substantial and content-neutral governmental interests of avoiding excessive sound volume and providing sufficient amplification within the bandshell concertground. `` Accordingly, it is valid under the First Amendment as a reasonable regulation of the place and manner of expression,'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said. In a dissenting opinion, Justice <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> said the court `` plays to our shared impatience with loud noise to obscure the damage that it does to our First Amendment rights.'' Calling <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s requirement for a city-run sound system at rock concerts `` an impermissible prior restraint,'' <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> said, `` Because judgments that sounds are too loud, noise-like, or discordant can mask disapproval of the music itself, government control of the sound-mixing equipment necessitates detailed and neutral standards.'' Quoting one music critic, the 80-year-old <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> added, `` New music always sounds loud to old ears.'' He was joined in dissent by Justices <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>. The city's noise-control campaign is aimed at protecting visitors to the park's neighborhing <ORGANIZATION> Sheep </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Meadow </ORGANIZATION>, a 13-acre area decreed a `` quiet zone'' by Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> in 1985, and residents of a fashionable neighborhood called Central Park West. The city policy was challenged by Rock Against Racism, which sponsors an annual bandshell program of speakers and musical groups. The case is <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> vs. Rock Against Racism, 88-226.
