nited </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> did not reject the idea outright. But, the official said it was unlikely to get anywhere `` as far as we're concerned. The official said the proposal could complicate efforts to hold elections to choose <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> representatives to negotiate self-rule with <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. `` It would only muddy the waters and distract from the -LRB- elections -RRB- idea itself,'' the official said. Participation by the council members would guarantee the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> a role that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> fears would be used to the advantage of the Arabs. The five members of the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> are the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. The Soviets, without committing themselves on Palestinian elections, made their proposal during a two-day meeting in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> last week on the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. It was one in a series of conferences on various global problems arranged by the two superpowers. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> delegation was headed by <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>, assistant secretary of state for the <LOCATION> Near </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>, head of the department's policy planning staff. <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Polyakov </PERSON>, senior expert on the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> in the <ORGANIZATION> Soviet </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, led his government's delegation. The Soviet idea was first disclosed in Thursday editions of The