<TEXT>
 A Roman Catholic priest appeared in court Thursday on charges he sold papal souvenir blankets for more than 10 times the legal price. The state alleged the Rev. <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Musonda </PERSON>, secretary general of the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Secretariat </ORGANIZATION>, and church fund-raiser <PERSON> Valentine </PERSON> <PERSON> Musakanya </PERSON> engaged in profiteering by selling 220 blankets for about $ 120 apiece after Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>'s May 2-4 visit. It was also alleged the Catholic Secretariat did not obtain statutory approval from the trade and commerce ministry to import the blankets. Under government pricing laws, the top price of a blanket was fixed at about $ 9. <LOCATION> Lusaka </LOCATION> magistrate <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Mukubesa </PERSON>, who recessed the hearing to June 26, did not ask <PERSON> Musonda </PERSON> to enter a plea on the charges, which carry the penalty of a fine related to the alleged pricing infringement. Roman Catholic churches in <LOCATION> Zambia </LOCATION> have said they raised an undisclosed sum from donations and souvenir sales to finance the pope's visit. Earlier this month, the government's Prices and <ORGANIZATION> Incomes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said it was investigating sales of mugs and T-shirts emblazoned with <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>'s portrait at inflated prices.
