<SECOND>AM-Housing Report,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Finds Home Ownership Among Young Declining</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Home ownership is declining among young Americans but increasing among those 65 and older, according to a <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> study released Thursday. <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Housing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> said in its annual report on the state of housing in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> that the home ownership rate for those in the 25-34 age group was 45 percent in 1988, down from 52.3 percent in 1980. Among households headed by people 65 and older, however, the rate increased from 72.3 percent in 1980 to 75 percent in 1988. The report said that many of those people already owned homes before housing costs increased in the 1970s and early 1980s. Young people, the study found, are increasingly unable to accumulate the down payment and other costs involved in buying a house. `` This trend is not easily reversed,'' the report said. `` Left unchecked, it threatens to produce a permanent underclass of disadvantaged renters and to jeopardize the long-term financial security of future generations.'' The study was co-authored by <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> professors <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Apgar </PERSON> and <PERSON> Denise </PERSON> <PERSON> DiPasquale </PERSON>. `` The situation is likely to worsen,'' Ms. <PERSON> DiPasquale </PERSON> said at a news conference. `` Federal budget cutbacks and expiring use restrictions threaten the subsidized housing stock.'' The report said inflation-adjusted rents for poor people living in unsubsidized units increased 34 percent from 1974 to 1985. `` As long as these trends persist, the gap between those who can afford decent shelter and those who ca n't will continue to widen,'' <PERSON> Apgar </PERSON> said. Single-parent households, which account for an increasing share of the nation's total population of children, are living in some of the worst housing, the report said. The median income of a single parent under 25 was $ 6,223 in 1988, down 15 percent in inflation-adjusted terms from 1974, the report said. At the same time, 71 percent of all single-parent households pay more than 50 percent of their incomes for rent.
</TEXT>
