<HEAD>Soldier-Spy Had No Plan When He Entered East Germany</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FULDA, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soldier who pleaded guilty to espionage charges says he did n't know what he was going to do when he crossed the border to communist <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, a military newspaper reported today. Spec. 4 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Peri </PERSON>, 22, of <LOCATION> Laguna </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Niguel </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, pleaded guilty to charges he gave defense secrets to <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> when his court martial opened Wednesday. <PERSON> Peri </PERSON> could be sentenced to life in prison on the espionage charges. <PERSON> Peri </PERSON> disappeared from his unit, the 11th Armored Cavalry Regiment in <LOCATION> Fulda </LOCATION>, on Feb. 21. He returned voluntarily 11 days later. `` I was never really sure what I was going to do at all,'' <PERSON> Peri </PERSON> told the courtoom after changing his plea from not guilty to guilty, according to an account in the Stars and Stripes, the Armed Forces unofficial newspapers. `` I really did n't have a plan. My primary reason was to leave behind all the frustrations and problems at work,'' the newspaper quoted him as saying about his decision to leave his unit. `` Everything had been wrong. I was n't enjoying myself. I wanted to start over somewhere else,'' the Stars and Stripes quoted his as telling the court in response to a question from Col. <PERSON> Craig </PERSON>. <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobsen </PERSON>, the presiding judge. <PERSON> Peri </PERSON> disappeared with a lap-top computer from his unit, where he worked in the military intelligence section as an electronic signal interceptor. `` I was looking at Soviet forces on paper -LRB- at work -RRB- and I wanted to see it firsthand,'' the newspaper quoted his as saying. `` I took the computer to run the software because I did n't think the Soviets would have one. It was a bargaining chip to keep them from doing something to me. It would show them that I was n't an American plant,'' the paper quoted him as telling the court. <PERSON> Peri </PERSON> said he used a multipurpose military vehicle to drive to the East German border because it was a headquarters vehicle and would not arouse suspicion inside the half-mile zone along the border, which <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> soldiers can not enter without authorization. After abandoning the vehicle near the border, <PERSON> Peri </PERSON> said he climbed over the border fence, using angled support posts as a ladder, according to Stars and Stripes. <PERSON> Peri </PERSON> said he walked to an East German border command tower and was spotted by soldiers who took him to a nearby barracks. `` They were surprised when I told them how I came over and got so far before being seen,'' the Stars and Stripes quoted him as saying. He was then taken by unidentified civilians to a house in East Belrin, where he was questioned about the secret documents he brought on the computer software, <PERSON> Peri </PERSON> told the court, according to the paper. <PERSON> Peri </PERSON> told the judge he did n't realize how extensive the information was until he returned to <LOCATION> Fulda </LOCATION> and was questioned by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intelligence officials, the newspaper said. On March 3, <PERSON> Peri </PERSON> told the East Germans he wanted to leave and was allowed to go back with the computer and the software, the Stars and Stripes said. He was charged with espionage on March 16. <PERSON> Peri </PERSON>'s parents, <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> and <PERSON> Winnie </PERSON>, and sister, <PERSON> Desiree </PERSON>, from <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, were at Wednesday' court session, Stars and Stripes said.
