<HEAD>Tourists for Bicentennial Find There's No Room at the Auberge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFFREY ULBRICH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tourists coming for the bicentennial of the French Revolution next month may find out that they picked the worst of times. They will have to stay in a hotel far from the capital. A parking space in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> might be just as tough to get. Motorcades for the 30 or so presidents and prime ministers will whiz through streets, and authorities will deploy 30,000 police _ two-thirds from out of town _ during the July 11-17 peak of festivities. Tourists flock to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> every summer, but officials say the number of visitors already is considerably larger than last year. During the bicentennial period, about 3 million tourists are expected to flood this city of 2.3 million people. With a bit of luck, a tourist can still find a room this month. Next month _ forget it. `` Impossible,'' says a woman at the hotel reservations counter of the Tourist Office on the Champs-Elysees. `` You'll have to go at least 100 kilometers -LRB- 60 miles -RRB- outside of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> is booked solid.'' Many VIPs will be attending a July 14-16 summit of the seven major industrial nations, and their entourages will fill hundreds of hotel rooms. <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> is coming to town July 4-6, followed by <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>. Also attending celebrations are 10 African presidents, six <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> presidents, six <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> presidents, and six prime ministers or presidents from <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, with baggage. Among those attending is President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. The elaborate preparations for the foreign leaders have left many people grumbling. `` Allowing a few dozen privileged people to be lodged and to move about tranquilly must not in any way be done to the detriment of hundreds of thousands of other people,'' elected officials from the <ORGANIZATION> Greens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> wrote to President <PERSON> Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitterrand </PERSON>. Police have put together a security and traffic strategy worthy of the Joint Chiefs of Staff. For the crucial week of July 10-17, parts of central <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> will be off - limits to all motor vehicle traffic and no cars allowed to park on the streets All vehicles must be removed from those areas. Permits must be sought for delivery trucks and residents heading for garages. Taxis may carry passengers into the areas. Special parking lots are being set up in the <LOCATION> Bois </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vincennes </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Bois </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Boulogne </PERSON>, forests on the east and west extremities of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. That could seriously upset the thriving transvestite prostitution business in the woods. Officials have played down the inconvenience. `` At least once in our lifetime, we will have seen the heart of <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> without cars, without trucks, without exhaust fumes, without backfiring motors,'' said Premier <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Rocard </PERSON>. The Louvre will be shut down July 13-15 for security reasons while delegations gather at the art museum for sessions. And the `` bateaux mouches,'' the tourist boats that ply the <LOCATION> Seine </LOCATION>, will drop anchor those three days because they will not be allowed to use their Alma bridge terminal. July 14 is Bastille Day, the 200th anniversary of the storming of Bastille Prison that started the revolution. The Tourist Office said about 100 families have responded so far to calls for private citizens to rent rooms to visitors. `` And we certainly will have more,'' says <PERSON> Florence </PERSON> <PERSON> Quercia </PERSON>, director of the Champs-Elysees office. `` If you have any problems, come and see us.''
