<HEAD>Routine Cholesterol Screening Recommended for Children</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MALCOLM RITTER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A private research and education organization urged routine cholesterol testing in children Thursday, saying high levels go undetected in many youngsters. Cholesterol should be checked at some point from ages 2 to 10 `` and the sooner the better,'' said <PERSON> Ernst </PERSON> <PERSON> Wynder </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. High cholesterol can lead to disease in the arteries that feed the heart muscle. That sets the stage for a heart attack in adult life. The American <ORGANIZATION> Heart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> recommends childhood cholesterol testing only if a child's family history suggests he is at risk. But that strategy overlooks many children with high cholesterol, <PERSON> Wynder </PERSON> said in a recent interview. Children are considered at risk if their fathers have had a heart attack, for example, but a young father may not have had his heart attack while the child is still young, <PERSON> Wynder </PERSON> said. The health foundation said research shows that some 5 percent to 15 percent of children in industrialized countries have excessive cholesterol levels, using the adult standard of 200 milligrams per deciliter or more. Almost a third are above 175 milligrams per deciliter, which may be a more appropriate marker for children, the foundation said. <PERSON> Wynder </PERSON> said screening all children would be cost-effective because it would reduce such later costs as those of coronary bypass operations and time off work from heart attacks. The heart association's recommendation was published in 1986. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Weidman </PERSON>, a member of the committee that developed it, said it was based on the state of cholesterol-testing technology and knowledge about childhood cholesterol at that time. `` We felt we were n't ready'' for universal childhood screening, he said in a recent interview. Now such screening is being studied by a committee organized by the National Heart, Lung and <ORGANIZATION> Blood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Weidman </PERSON> said. The heart association is awaiting the committee's conclusions before deciding on any change in its recommendation, said association spokesman <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>. The health foundation said a feasible target for children's cholesterol is 140 milligrams per deciliter <PERSON> Weidman </PERSON> agreed that is `` a goal to shoot for'' but said diet and exercise will not be enough to reach it in all children. So medications may be needed, he said.
