<SECOND>AM-Submarine Races, Bjt,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Human-Powered Submarine Racers Ready To Take A Dive</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RIVIERA BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 With the minds of engineers and the spirits of pioneers, 18 teams are gambling their reputations and their survival in the first human-powered submarine races. `` There's both a fun and serious side to the races,'' said <PERSON> Maggie </PERSON> <PERSON> Linskey </PERSON> <PERSON> Merrill </PERSON>, director of The H.A. <ORGANIZATION> Perry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Hingham </LOCATION>, Mass.-based undersea research group that, along with <ORGANIZATION> Florida </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boca </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Raton </ORGANIZATION>, organized the three-day event starting Friday. `` We want to see the type of materials used and what shape performs the best,'' Ms. <PERSON> Merrill </PERSON> said. `` There could be a commercial and recreational application for human-powered subs.'' And for the competitors, who will race their two-person craft 1,000 feet offshore in about 20 feet of water, there's the spice of a $ 5,000 overall performance prize and several smaller cash awards for design and efficiency. The lightweight subs _ with one person steering and the other in the `` crankman'' seat providing the pedal power _ will race head-to-head over a one-kilometer course. The eight winners of Friday's first rounds will move on to elimination rounds over the weekend. The subs will tow surface floats to mark their progress, about the pace of a brisk walk. All the subs are `` wet'' designs that fill up with water and require the crews to wear scuba gear. For most entrants, the nearly 18 months of design and construction was plotted on computers and bankrolled by universities or corporate sponsors. A few, however, pulled the car out of the family garage for their work space. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Leibolt </PERSON> and two co-workers at the <ORGANIZATION> David </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Taylor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Bethesda </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, combed junk yards for parts. The crew seats are old plastic cafeteria chairs, and an old 10-speed bike was converted into the sub's gear system. They dubbed the 600-pound fiberglass sub `` The Turtle'' after the first human-powered sub, built in 1775 but abandoned after its first unsuccessful mission to sink British ships in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION>. `` Hope we have better luck,'' said <PERSON> Leibolt </PERSON>. `` We literally funded this by passing around a hat in the office.'' In <LOCATION> Concord </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, an auto shop donated a pink-and-green paint job for the independent `` Sub-Human.'' `` We sort of winged it,'' said crankman <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Reno </PERSON>, who still shivers when he recalls the first test run in <LOCATION> 46-degree </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lake </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tahoe </LOCATION>. While most of the subs resemble sleek torpedos, many teams boasted of subtle differences. `` Ours may look like some of the others, but there's one difference: Ours is fastest,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Friedman </PERSON>, a back-up navigator for the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Icarus,'' which uses a cable-and-pulley propulsion system rather than the more common chain-and-gear `` We designed ours in a perfect hydrodynamic shape,'' said <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> mechanical engineering graduate <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Poor </PERSON>. `` It should slice right through the water.'' The `` Gossamer Albacor,'' built by <ORGANIZATION> Lockheed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advanced </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Marine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>, was one of two entries using a waving fish-tail propulsion device rather than propellers. `` We're looking at all things: the cleverness of design and the materials used,'' said engineer <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, one of six judges assigned to award $ 500 prizes for cost effectiveness and innovation. `` Anyone can build something with a blank check. I'll be looking for some real imagination.'' Surely, 73-year-old <PERSON> Calvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Gongwer </PERSON>'s `` Knuckle Ball'' will not go unnoticed. <PERSON> Gongwer </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Innerspace </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION> Covina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, will be the navigator inside his 60-inch-diameter plastic sphere. `` There are some ideas I want to test out with spheres underwater,'' said <PERSON> Gongwer </PERSON>. `` Looks are n't everything.'' On the beach, <ORGANIZATION> Perry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> President H.A. <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> watched all the preparations. `` The response has been four of five times what we imagined,'' said <PERSON> Perry </PERSON>. `` At first we thought we'd have a few subs, a few races and a keg of beer. We did n't expect this.''
