<HEAD>Bush Touts New Foundation to Boost Volunteerism</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds; New material, editing throughout with Bush speech.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> today called upon all American citizens and institutions to join a voluntary crusade to fight poverty, drugs and other societal ills by extending national service `` into every corner of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' Bringing a campaign metaphor to life, he unveiled his blueprint for a foundation called the `` Points of Light Initiative'' that would get $ 25 million a year in taxpayers' funds to spur Americans to volunteer for social service. He made the pitch in a speech for the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Partnership </LOCATION>, a civic group, after touring a shelter for runaway youth called Covenant House. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also named <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Kean </PERSON> to head an advisory committee that will recommend legislation to achieve the foundation's goals and propose a structure for the organization. `` I ask all Americans and all American institutions, large and small, to make service central to your life and work,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` We know that during the past two decades we have spent more money, on more social programs, than at any time in our history. And some problems are n't better. In fact, they're worse.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said `` too many Americans still endure a living nightmare of want and isolation. That must stop.'' `` The key to constructive change is building relationships, not bureaucracies,' he said. `` Today, more than ever, we need community service to help drop-outs, pregnant teens and drug abusers; the homeless and AIDS victim; the hungry and illiterate.'' Invoking again the guiding metaphor of his campaign, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he wanted to unleash the energy of every citizen, school, business, church and synagogue and civic group. `` This is what I mean when I talk of ` a thousand points of light' _ that vast galaxy of people and institutions working together to solve problems in their own back yard,'' he said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he was asking both the public and private sector, including all branches of government, to `` join this great movement to extend national service into every corner of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' He urged every church and synagogue to `` become an around-the-clock community center,'' every restaurant and grocery to distribute surplus food to soup kitchens and shelters, every corporation to teach illiterate employees to read, and every college to start a Big Brother or Big Sister program. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said that in addition to the Youth Engaged in Service to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> program -LRB- YES -RRB- announced Wednesday, the new foundation will include a `` ServNet Project'' that will encourage corporations, professional firms and other groups to donate the services of their top talent. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said the YES program will select annually two college-age youth from each state to serve as roving service ambassadors and salespeople. `` We know that volunteerism can help those free-falling through society,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. At <ORGANIZATION> Covenant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, a shelter near Times Square, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and his wife <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> heard 11 young residents tell of their lives on the streets. Mrs. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> cradled a three-week-old baby of one of the youths as they spoke. <PERSON> Monique </PERSON>, 20, said of her life on the streets, `` You do n't want to be there.'' She said as a child she was beaten at home, `` tied up and hung over a spiral staircase.'' <PERSON> Walter </PERSON>, 18, told the president that kids wound up on the streets because `` It's hard to get good jobs. Working in McDonald's at the minimum wage _ it just does n't pay.'' He said that he could make $ 100 `` in 15 minutes'' selling drugs. He said his father was an alcoholic and his mother was dead. The White House billed the new community service drive as a potential panacea for a welter of social problems, from drug abuse to homelessness, and said it could be ` the most comprehensive and inclusive movement of our time.'' During his acceptance speech at the Republican convention last Aug. 18 <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> first spoke of what he called the `` brilliant diversity'' of volunteerism in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, shining `` like a thousand points of light'' across society. The metaphor drew guffaws from Democratic rival <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, but <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> returned to the theme repeatedly and promised to help spur volunteerism with a <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Entering </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> initiative.
