<HEAD>Smithsonian Says Happy Birthday to `Sesame Street' TV Show</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT M. ANDREWS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The horde of squealing youngsters knew how to get to Sesame Street on Thursday: Follow the yellow bird, just as millions of kids have done watching television for the last two decades. The <ORGANIZATION> Smithsonian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institution </ORGANIZATION> saluted the 20th anniversary of the popular public television show with lavish oratory at the ceremonial opening of a `` Sesame Street'' exhibition at the <ORGANIZATION> Smithsonian </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Museum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> History </ORGANIZATION> Visiting preschoolers swarmed past grown-up dignitaries and TV cameramen to jostle happily around Mr. <PERSON> Hooper </PERSON>'s storefront. At the window ledge was Elmo, their old Muppet friend. The friendly, red-faced animal, operated by puppeteer <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Clash </PERSON>, waved back and spoke to the youngsters who reached out to grasp his paws. The children giggled at Oscar the Grouch, scowling from his trash can, and peered up at the 8-foot-2-inch yellow majesty of Big Bird. Along the lower walls of the museum, they twirled clear plastic wheels to form funny faces and searched a train picture to count the hidden letter T's. `` The one thing kids wo n't learn on ` Sesame Street' is the difference between education and fun,'' said <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> Roney </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON>, the exhibition curator. `` Sesame Street,'' created by <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ganz </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooney </PERSON>'s non-profit Children's Television Workshop to help disadvantaged children age 3 to 5 make the transition from home to school, made its public television debut Nov. 10, 1969. In the last two decades, the hour-long show has won 36 Emmys and is seen regularly in more than 11 million households each week. The English-language version is seen in more than 80 countries. Producer <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> V.B </PERSON>. <PERSON> Britt </PERSON> estimated the show has 40 million `` graduates,'' not counting tens of millions of parents who also watch. <PERSON> Britt </PERSON> was accompanied by <PERSON> Loretta </PERSON> <PERSON> Long </PERSON>, the actress who has played <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> the nurse on `` Sesame Street'' since it began. Long is a professional educator with a Ph.D. in urban education. Museum director <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said the show's creators had prevailed against `` the greed, heedlessness and irresponsibility of much of network television'' to produce a program that has `` made an immense difference in the tone of our culture.'' `` It is not only a TV program, it's a proclamation that there are people, even in the TV industry, who are n't going to give up on it, they're staying with it and producing something that is good,'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said. `` That's heroism.'' The exhibition includes more than 50 photographs recalling two decades of `` Sesame Street'' programming. Besides the show's familiar Muppet characters, objects on display include the Sesame Street lamp post and sign, original story boards and a production slate used in filming. When the exhibition closes at summer's end, <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> will join the museum's permanent history of American entertainment collection, alongside <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Garland </PERSON>'s ruby slippers from `` The Wizard of Oz,'' <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hagman </PERSON>'s cowboy hat from TV's `` <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>'' and <PERSON> Archie </PERSON> <PERSON> Bunker </PERSON>'s wing chair from `` All In The Family. For the record, Big Bird likes birdseed sandwiches, while <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON>'s favorite treat is an ice cream sundae topped with pickles and sardines
