<HEAD>Dog Lost On Mount McKinley Wanders Into Camp 18 Days Later</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A sled dog lost in poor weather during a climbing expedition on <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> McKinley </LOCATION> has turned up, weak but alive, after 18 days on the ice-covered mountain. <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jean-Francois </PERSON> <PERSON> Tuveri </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Chamonix </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, assumed the dog had fallen in a crevasse and died after it disappeared May 31. The Tuveris had four dogs in harness when they started mushing up <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s tallest peak. On the sixth day of the journey, while descending to their camp at the 11,000-foot level after ferrying supplies higher, they unhitched the dogs because of treacherous ice conditions. By the time they got around Windy Corner at 13,200 feet, only three dogs were with them. A 15-month-old Siberian husky named <PERSON> Oukiok </PERSON> was gone. A snowstorm forced the Tuveris to hole up for the next four days. When they climbed to a medical research camp at 14,200 feet, they asked other climbers if they had seen the dog. None had and they assumed he had fallen to his death. With only three dogs left, the Tuveris abandoned their sled and simply climbed to the 20,320-foot summit with the dogs. It was only the second expedition to reach the top with dogs. The Tuveris left the mountain for some sightseeing around <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, then returned to <LOCATION> Talkeetna </LOCATION>, near the mountain, to pick up the remaining dogs for the trip back to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. That's where they learned that, 18 days after he disappeared, <PERSON> Oukiok </PERSON> had walked into the high basin where the medical camp is located. Denali National Park rangers said the dog did n't have any broken bones, but was exhausted. `` It would seem pretty spectacular but it's not impossible,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Leach </PERSON>, chief veterinarian for the Iditarod Trail Sled Dog Race. Snow and ice could provide enough liquid to prevent death through dehydration, he said. The dog was being nursed back to health by staff members at the research camp. <ORGANIZATION> Rangers </ORGANIZATION> said he should soon have enough strength to make the trip to the <LOCATION> Kahiltna </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Glacier </LOCATION> base camp at 7,200 feet. From there he will be flown to <LOCATION> Talkeetna </LOCATION>, hopefully in time to accompany the Tuveris and the other three dogs back to <LOCATION> France </LOCATION> on Monday.
