<HEAD>Man Sues for $20.35 Because Discount Tokens Unavailable</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In at least one respect, <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Schlichtman </PERSON>'s lawsuit is just a token gesture He'll be happy if it nets him $ 20.35. The commuter is suing the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jersey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> because its discount toll-booth tokens were always sold out, and when he did manage to buy some, they sold him a slug. That's what the 35 cents in the suit is for. By the same token, he'll also seek the $ 11.70 court filing fee. `` If you've got a mule, the only way you can get it to do something is to get its attention first,'' he said Wednesday. `` I'm filing the suit to get their attention, then I'm going to get them to do something _ give me the money they owe me. <PERSON> Schlichtman </PERSON> said he tried five times without success to buy rolls of tokens for the Garden State Parkway. It costs $ 10 to buy 40 tokens, a savings of $ 4 over the cash toll. `` I spend about $ 1,000 a year on tolls, counting going into <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Schlichtman </PERSON>, a South Orange resident who works in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> giving driving lessons to cabbies. `` I spend more time sitting at toll booths than I do with any other part of my day. They're ridiculous and obnoxious.'' <PERSON> Schlichtman </PERSON> said a toll collector refused to reimburse him for the slug. <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jersey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Authority </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Ingoglia </PERSON> would not comment on the case but said if motorists are sold slugs, they can contact the agency for reimbursement.
