<FIRST>u w AM-Economy     06-22 0847</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Economy,830</SECOND>
<HEAD>Economy Expanded at 4.4 Percent Annual Rate in First Quarter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economy expanded at a 4.4 percent annual rate in the first three months of the year, but the overall growth rate masked a significant slowdown in business activity, the government reported Thursday. The <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said the gross national product, the country's total output of goods and services, rose at the fastest rate in more than a year during the first quarter. However, more than half of the increase resulted from a statistical rebound from last year's drought, a one-time accounting change necessary to return expected farm production this year to its pre-drought levels. Discounting this change, the non-farm economy grew at a lackluster annual rate of 1.9 percent in the first quarter, down from a non-farm growth rate of 3.5 percent in the final three months of 1988. Economists have been predicting for some time that economic growth will slow markedly this year under the impact of high interest rates engineered by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> in an effort to cool off inflationary pressures. On the inflation front, a price index tied to the GNP rose at an annual rate of 4.6 percent in the first three months of the year, a less worrisome figure than a 5 percent increase estimated a month ago. The improvement came from slower price increases for farm products and industrial supplies. The effect of the economic slowdown was evident in a companion report that showed the after-tax profits of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> corporations fell by 1.1 percent in the first three months of 1989. The decline, which was revised from an even larger 1.7 percent estimated drop a month ago, was the first setback for corporate profits since a 2.5 percent fall in the first quarter of 1987. Economists said the new GNP report was a generally favorable sign that the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> can engineer a soft-landing with slower growth and less inflation without pushing the country into a recession. `` The Federal Reserve seems to be getting precisely what it asked for,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Dederick </PERSON>, chief economist of <ORGANIZATION> Northern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` We have an economy that is continuing to expand but at a subdued rate.'' Many analysts believe that the country has now entered what is termed a growth recession, a period when the economy keeps growing but at such a sluggish pace that unemployment rises. <PERSON> Cynthia </PERSON> <PERSON> Latta </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, predicted that the unemployment rate, now at 5.2 percent, would climb to 5.9 percent early next year. She forecast GNP growth in the second quarter of around 1.8 percent, very much like the non-farm increase in the first three months of the year. In the second half of 1989, she predicted growth would slow to around 1 percent, but without a recession. `` It is still our bet that we can avoid a recession,'' she said. `` The new GNP report provides further ammunition for those arguing for a soft landing.'' The primary reason for the slight upward revision in the overall 4.4 percent GNP figure, up from a 4.3 percent estimate a month ago, was a better performance in trade than previously believed. The country's huge trade deficit, which had been getting worse since last spring, narrowed significantly in the first quarter and business investment shot up substantially. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit, as measured by the GNP, narrowed by $ 19.5 billion in the first quarter as exports shot up by 15 percent and imports fell by 0.5 percent while business investment advanced by 7.6 percent, rebounding from a 2.9 percent decline in the fourth quarter. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration is counting on both trade and business investment to be strong this year to keep the economy moving forward while consumer spending slackens. Consumer spending, which accounts for two-thirds of all economic activity, rose at a sluggish annual rate of 1.3 percent in the first quarter, reflecting in part weak auto sales. Housing construction, which also has been hard hit by the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION>'s anti-inflation campaign, dropped by 4.6 percent in the first quarter, the poorest performance in a year. The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> signaled last week that it had begun lowering interest rates slightly amid signs that inflationary pressures are abating somewhat. That move is expected to revive the fortunes of interest-rate sensitive sectors of the economy such as housing. The various changes left the GNP, after adjusting for inflation, at an annual level of $ 4.077 trillion in the first quarter. The latest monthly survey of 51 top economists conducted by the <ORGANIZATION> Blue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chip </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Indicators </ORGANIZATION> newsletter put the consensus growth forecast this year at 2.7 percent, down significantly from GNP growth of 3.9 percent in 1988, the best performance in four years. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration, which needs significant growth to lower the budget deficit without the need to resort to a tax increase, is more optimistically forecasting growth this year of 3.2 percent. That estimate will be revised by mid-July and administration officials have indicated that they expect to lower their growth figure somewhat.
</TEXT>
