<HEAD>Proposals Sought to Search for Water on Moon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A private space research organization said Thursday it has asked for proposals from satellite manufacturers to build a probe to look for water on parts of the moon that have never seen daylight. <PERSON> Gregg </PERSON> <PERSON> Maryniak </PERSON>, executive vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, said the probe can be built for $ 5 million, and sent to the <LOCATION> moon </LOCATION> in 1992 with a little bit f help from the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. For example, he told a news conference, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> has in storage an Apollo-era gamma ray spectrometer that could be dusted off and used to map the moon's surface and search for water at the poles, areas of which never face the sun. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> or rocket-launching firms could also carry the probe into orbit as non-paying cargo, either on the space shuttle or as a hitchhiker on a rocket taking a satellite to an orbit 22,300 miles above <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Maryniak </PERSON> said. He said SSI, a 12-year-old organization supported by 4,000 private members, is looking for financing from aerospace corporations and organizations. The six teams of astronauts who visited the moon in the 1969-1972 period all landed closer to the equator of the moon than to the poles and the question of whether there is water to be found in the shadowed area never was answered. Finding water, which is composed of hydrogen and oxygen _ the fuel for chemical rockets _ would be of enormous value to future space exploration. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Space recommended such a search as its first priority. It takes less than one-twentieth the energy to lift materials form the moon as it does from <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>.
