<HEAD>Court Turns Down the Volume</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday made it easier for communities to turn down the volume at rock concerts, a decision free-speech advocates found disquieting. The court, by a 6-3 vote, upheld <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s effort to avoid ear-splitting noise levels in Central Park by requiring sponsors of rock concerts to use a sound system operated by a city-designated engineer. Such requirements do n't violate the freedom-of-expression guarantees of the Constitution's First Amendment, the court said. But <PERSON> Dana </PERSON> <PERSON> Beal </PERSON>, political coordinator for a concert-sponsoring organization called Rock Against Racism, said the ruling strikes at the heart of rock. `` Bit by bit, each municipality in the country will be able to turn rock' n' roll into easy listening music,'' <PERSON> Beal </PERSON> said. The decision reversed a federal appeals court ruling that would have forced city officials to devise a less restrictive way to deal with what they deem excessively loud entertainment. `` This less-restrictive-alternative analysis has never been a part of the inquiry into the validity of a time, place and manner regulation'' on expression, Justice <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> wrote for the court. `` The city's sound amplification guideline is narrowly tailored to serve ... substantial and content-neutral governmental interests,'' he wrote `` Accordingly, it is valid under the First Amendment as a reasonable regulation of the place and manner of expression.'' In a dissenting opinion, Justice <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> said the court `` plays to our shared impatience with loud noise to obscure the damage that it does to our First Amendment rights.'' <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> called <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s requirement for a city-run sound system `` an impermissible prior restraint,'' and said such government actions should be subjected to the same scrutiny as regulations based on an expression's content. `` Judgments that sounds are too loud, noise-like or discordant can mask disapproval of the music itself,'' he said. Quoting one music critic, the 80-year-old <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> said, `` New music always sounds loud to old ears.'' He was joined in dissent by Justices <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>. The city's noise-control campaign is aimed at protecting visitors to Central Park's Sheep Meadow, a 13-acre area decreed a `` quiet zone'' by Mayor <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> in 1985, and residents of fashionable Central Park West. The city policy was challenged by Rock Against Racism, which sponsors an annual program of speakers and musical groups in the park's <ORGANIZATION> Naumberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Acoustic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bandshell </ORGANIZATION>. The losing lawyer in the case was <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Kunstler </PERSON>, who a day earlier found himself on the winning side when the justices ruled that burning the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flag is a form of constitutionally protected political protest. `` What the court gives with one hand it takes away with the other,'' <PERSON> Kunstler </PERSON> said. `` Now, art is subject to government control, something the framers of the Constitution certainly would not have countenanced.''
