<TEXT>
 A federal judge has ordered the Yahweh sect to pay $ 940,000 to tenants who lost their homes in a strong-arm eviction that ended in the deaths of two residents at a crime-ridden apartment complex. The tenants' attorney called Thursday for a police investigation of the sect, saying the civil trial testimony demonstrated that the white-robed <PERSON> Yahwehs </PERSON> engaged in a policy of violence against those who opposed them. `` They fire-bombed an entire block in <LOCATION> Delray </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, and they were involved in slayings in other cities,'' <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Equels </PERSON> said. `` I think the state and federal government need to carefully examine the judge's findings here.'' In <LOCATION> Delray </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, after some residents took offense at the Yahwehs' door-to-door proseletyzing, someone threw firebombs into apartments. No one was injured and the crime is unsolved. Witnesses also mentioned slayings, including the unsolved killing of a former sect member. The Yahwehs' attorney, <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON>, said he would appeal the ruling, saying the sect should not be blamed for what a few members did. `` We're appealing as a matter of religious freedom,'' <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON> said. `` If a <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> commits a crime, you do n't punish the pope or the priests because of his wrongdoing.'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Kehoe </PERSON> issued his decision Wednesday in the lawsuit filed by 27 former residents of an <LOCATION> Opa-locka </LOCATION> apartment complex against the Temple of Love, the Miami-based mother church run by the sect's leader <PERSON> Yahweh </PERSON> <PERSON> ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Yahweh </PERSON>. The church, which takes a strong stand against drugs, moved to buy the apartments in 1986 after the previous owner abandoned them, saying crack dealers and criminals had taken over the complex. `` They will go into a distressed area that is overrun by drug dealers and criminal element and they will clean them up, kick out all the wrong-doers, and then either sell or make housing available for poor people,'' <PERSON> Rubin </PERSON> said. The Yahwehs, who teach that blacks are the true chosen people of God, run businesses and property in predominantly black neighborhoods. The Opa-locka apartment building was eventually abandoned and now is empty. In the Opa-locka case, the Yahwehs, many carrying six-foot wooden staffs, evicted everyone in the complex, threatening residents and dumping their belongings on the street, according to the lawsuit, which called the tactics a `` terrorist occupation strategy.'' On Oct. 30, 1986, two tenants who publicly opposed the evictions were shot and killed. Sect member <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Rozier </PERSON> was later convicted of murder in the case, and testified in the tenants' lawsuit. He said <PERSON> Yahweh </PERSON> <PERSON> ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Yahweh </PERSON> had tortured sect members and taught them ritual murder techniques, but other witnesses disputed his account. He also recounted acts of violence allegedly committed by the sect in other communities. The judge did not rule on who was responsible for the deaths of the two tenants, citing conflicting testimony. But he found that the church had engaged in running a criminal enterprise, extortion and assault, and ordered it to pay $ 10,000 to each tenant for emotional distrress, as well as reimburse them for six times the value of the belongings they lost. An additional $ 500,000 in punitive damages also will be divided among the tenants. Former tenant <PERSON> Shadell </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON>, brother-in-law of one of those killed, said he was pleased by the verdict, recalling his initial sense of helplessness. `` I gave up. I said that there was n't any justice, that nothing would be done about it, because there were so many things they got away with before,'' <PERSON> Hamilton </PERSON> said.
