<FIRST>r a AM-SunDagger     06-22 0384</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sun Dagger,0394</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rock Shift Moves Solstice Phenomenon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHACO CANYON, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Natural erosion apparently has blunted a spike of light dubbed the `` sun dagger'' that ancient pueblo Indians are believed to have used to mark the summer solstice. The dagger was formed by light shining between 9-foot-tall sandstone slabs sitting just below the top of the 500-foot-tall <PERSON> Fajada </PERSON> <PERSON> Butte </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Chaco </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canyon </LOCATION> in northwestern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>. On the solstice, the longest day of the year, the light would shine on a spiral-shaped petroglyph etched on rock behind the slabs. But erosion apparently caused a rock to shift, and on Wednesday the dagger-shaped pattern of light missed its summer-solstice mark on the petroglyph for perhaps the first time in 1,000 years, researchers said. Instead, the light shined above and to the left of the Indian pattern. `` We're used to this thing acting like a clock,'' physicist <PERSON> Rolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinclair </PERSON> said Wednesday. The dagger widened and lengthened into `` an overgrown carrot,'' said <PERSON> Anna </PERSON> <PERSON> Sofaer </PERSON>, an artist and archaeo-astronomer who discovered the dagger in 1977 in Chaco Culture National Historical Park, which contains numerous ancient stone dwellings. The rock formation also cast distinctive light patterns at the winter solstice and the fall and spring equinoxes _ when day and night are of equal length. The petroglyph near the canyon's south entrance was believed to have been carved between A.D. 950 and 1150, at the peak of the Anasazi culture that once thrived in Chaco Canyon. <PERSON> Sinclair </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sofaer </PERSON> and others contend rocks originally might have been manipulated to cause the sunlight patterns. But on Sunday, a group that included <PERSON> Sinclair </PERSON> discovered that one of the rock slabs had shifted and had altered the phenomenon. `` It's very serious and sad,'' Ms. <PERSON> Sofaer </PERSON> said. `` We knew when we first saw the site that it had a fragility that was remarkable.'' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Zelik </PERSON>, a physics and astronomy professor at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mexico </ORGANIZATION>, said the alteration raises questions about how much or how often rocks have moved previously at the site and about just how old it really is. However, <PERSON> Sinclair </PERSON> said it's clear the rocks have not moved much, if at all, over the years. He said the erosion which caused the rock to slip might be due to 10 years of relatively wet weather at <LOCATION> Chaco </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
