eek on their way out of <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> with every piece of property they could take. Government officials at the news conference indicated the labor drain is already disrupting agriculture and many industries. <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Angelov </PERSON>, a government adviser, said those departing had withdrawn up to $ 260 million from banks, adding the sum might reach $ 1 billion if people keep leaving. To cope with the sudden loss of manpower, <PERSON> Ganev </PERSON> said the the government will order longer working hours, relocate workers, reschedule summer vacations and start a crash retraining program. In addition, manpower is to be moved from `` not critical'' to `` critical'' industries or areas, <PERSON> Ganev </PERSON> told the news conference without elaborating. <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> has been short of labor even before the current wave of emigration, and at least 30,000 Vietnamese are employed in Bulgarian factories. Throughout the news conference, <PERSON> Ganev </PERSON> and five other senior government officials blamed the huge outflow of Turks on Turkish propaganda and `` instigation.'' `` <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> has whipped up a psychosis among the Moslem population,'' <PERSON> Ganev </PERSON> said, accusing Turkish Premier <PERSON> Turgut </PERSON> <PERSON> Oezal </PERSON> of repeatedly issuing military threats against <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> <PERSON> Slavs </PERSON> and ethnic Turks have been deeply suspicious of one another since the five-century rule of <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION>'s Ottoman Empire Asked if <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION> would accept the assistance of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> High Commissioner for Refugees, he said, `` We have no refugees, so we do not need him.''
