<HEAD>The Short Life of a Mighty Battleship</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Bismarck Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A chronology compiled by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geographic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> of the fate of the German World War II battleship Bismarck: 1936 _ Construction starts in <LOCATION> Hamburg </LOCATION> of the 820-foot ship with a displacement, when fully loated, of more than 50,000 tons, carrying eight 15-inch guns, 12 5.9-inch guns and 16 4.1-inch guns and a crew of 2,200 and capable of a top speed of 30 knots. Feb. 14, 1939 _ On St. Valentine's Day, <PERSON> Adolf </PERSON> <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON> launches the ship. May 19, 1941 _ After more than two years in fitting and shakedown cruises, the <PERSON> Bismarck </PERSON> sets sail from <LOCATION> Gdynia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> with orders to sink Allied merchant ships in the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> while evading engagement with allied warships. May 20, 1941 _ A Swedish cruiser spots the Bismarck and its escort, the <PERSON> Prinz </PERSON> <PERSON> Eugen </PERSON>, off the coast of neutral <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>. Later they are sighted off the coast of <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>. May 21, 1941 _ British Spitfires over the <LOCATION> Bergen-Korsfjord </LOCATION> region of <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION> spot the two German ships. The British send the battle cruiser Hood to join other British ships on patrol in the <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION>. May 22, 1941 _ More British forces head for the search zone. May 23, 1941 _ In the <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> beteen <LOCATION> Greenland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION>, the British cruisers <LOCATION> Suffolk </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Norfolk </LOCATION> sight the German ship threading through a minefield. The Bismarck opens fire, but the British retire safely. The British follow the Germans despite rain and snow storms and dangerous ice floes. The Hood and the Prince of <LOCATION> Wales </LOCATION> are closing in from about 250 miles away. May 24 _ At 5:35 a.m., the Hood and Prince of <LOCATION> Wales </LOCATION> sight the Bismarck and open fire. The Germans return fire. At 6:01 a.m., a massive explosion sinks the Hood, leaving only three of its 1,419 crewmen alive. The <PERSON> Bismarck </PERSON> suffers a ruptured fuel tank. The Bismarck engages the British again in the evening. The <PERSON> Prinz </PERSON> <PERSON> Eugen </PERSON> escapes. The Bismarck's commander decides to make for a <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> port for repairs. A British force heads to the area from <LOCATION> Gibraltar </LOCATION>. Around midnight, nine British biplanes attack, causing little damage. May 25 _ About 3 a.m., the Bismarck evades its chasers and heads for the safety of U-boat patrols and <ORGANIZATION> Luftwaffe </ORGANIZATION> air cover, near the coast of <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>. May 26 _ A British plane spots the Bismarck. In a last-ditch effort to stop it before it reaches safety, planes from a British carrier score two torpedo hits that wreck the Bismarck's steering gear and jam her rudders, only hours from safety. The Bismarck's fate is sealed May 27 _ At 8:47 a.m., a British force opens up on the limping <LOCATION> Bismarck </LOCATION>, putting its main guns out of action. By 10 a.m., the <PERSON> Bismarck </PERSON> is a battered hulk. By 10:39 a.m. it has capsized and sunk, coming to rest upright on the ocean floor with only 115 of its crew of 2,200 rescued.
