<HEAD>Soviets Agree to Religious Contacts With Iran; Indicate Arms Sales</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOS3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> on Thursday strengthened its ties with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, agreeing to exchange delegations of Moslem religious leaders and indicating it would send weaponry to its Islamic neighbor. The agreement with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> came as the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> struggles with a resurgence of Islamic fundamentalism and conflicts between its Christians and 50 million Moslems. The agreement was part of a broad declaration signed by President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and Iranian Parliament Speaker <PERSON> Hashemi </PERSON> <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON>, whose visit to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has defrosted a decade of icy relations. It implies future Soviet weapons sales to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, by promising the superpower's cooperation in `` strengthening the defense capacity'' of its southern neighbor. At the same time, the document commits both nations to strive `` to rid the world of aggression.'' <PERSON> Rafsanjani </PERSON> later sidestepped questions about arms deals. He said only that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> was trying to be self-sufficient in arms but has some `` technical requirements that we would like to see met by various sources.'' In <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy toward <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> would be guided by developments in the country _ and not by its relationship with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> was <LOCATION> Iraq </L