<FIRST>r a AM-HospitalTreatment     06-22 0588</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hospital Treatment,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Uninsured Patients Who Are Hospitalized Get Less Treatment, Study
Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release at 5:30 p.m. EDT.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 People without medical insurance not only are less likely to get into hospitals than insured patients, they also get less treatment once they're there, a new study of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> hospital patients has found. But the finding does n't necessarily mean the uninsured get worse care, because doctors may keep insured patients in the hospital longer than necessary and may give them more treatment than they need, researchers said. Previous studies have revealed that the poor, minorities and people without health insurance have less chance of getting medical care than others. But `` there has been a feeling that once you get into the system, everybody is treated the same,'' said <PERSON> Joel </PERSON> <PERSON> Weissman </PERSON>, a health-policy specialist at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> and a co-author of the new study. `` What we're seeing is that even after you get into the hospital, these patterns persist.'' <PERSON> Weissman </PERSON> and Dr. <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Epstein </PERSON>, also of <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>, examined the treatment of more than 65,000 patients at 52 hospitals in the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> area during 1983. They found that uninsured patients, on average, underwent fewer procedures and were discharged earlier than patients covered by <ORGANIZATION> Blue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION>. The uninsured also were discharged earlier than Medicaid patients, the study said. Though the differences were not great, they should serve as a `` red flag'' to spur further investigation, <PERSON> Weissman </PERSON> said in a telephone interview Thursday. More studies will be necessary to determine if the Boston-area trends reflect those in the rest of the nation, said <PERSON> Weissman </PERSON>, who added that <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> is currently working to update the 1983 findings. The study also found that people with different types of medical problems tended to end up at different types of hospitals, with the major teaching hospitals and public hospitals taking the brunt of the tough cases among the uninsured. `` Although we lacked data on income and housing situation, the results are consistent with the popular view of the urban public hospital as the provider of last resort for persons with multiple problems at the bottom of the socioeconomic scale,'' the researchers said. After correcting statistically for differences in severity of illness and other factors, the researchers found that uninsured patients stayed in the hospital half a day less than <ORGANIZATION> Blue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> patients _ 5.36 compared with 5.79 days. The uninsured underwent about 7 percent fewer procedures _ operations or tests _ per stay than <ORGANIZATION> Blue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cross </ORGANIZATION> patients, 1.16 vs. 1.25, respectively, the researchers said. `` The effects we found occurred in all types of hospitals, including major teaching and public hospitals _ institutions commonly considered to be relatively blind to payment source,'' the researchers reported in Friday's Journal of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. Though the results suggest that hospitals or physicians tailor people's medical care according to ability to pay, or that patients do so themselves to avoid high bills, it does n't necessarily mean the uninsured are getting inferior care, the researchers said. `` We know, for example, that lengths of stay have been decreasing nationwide during the last decade, but so far there is little evidence that the quality of care has been reduced,'' they said. Longer stays and more procedures among insured patients in the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> area may represent overuse of medical resources, they said. `` Further research is warranted to clarify whether lower utilization represents inadequate care and whether alternative financial and organization arrangements can remedy the situation,'' the researchers said.
</TEXT>
