<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The crippled Soviet ocean liner Maxim Gorky reached a remote archipelago for repairs Thursday, two days after its bow was ripped open when it hit an iceberg while on a cruise. The ship reached <LOCATION> Coles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> on <LOCATION> Svalbard </LOCATION>, the largest of the <LOCATION> Spitzbergen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Archipelago </LOCATION>, said <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Klyver </PERSON>, an administrative official for the Norwegian islands. The secluded bay has no wharf or facilities but offers shelter from wind and waves, he said. The 630-foot <PERSON> Maxim </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorky </PERSON> was kept afloat with pumps after a 20-foot gash was ripped in its bow and it took on 18,000 tons of water during a midnight sun cruise in the <LOCATION> Norwegian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION>. All of the 575 passengers and 378 crew were rescued. The passengers and some crew were brought to shelter at <LOCATION> Spitzbergen </LOCATION> and flown home from there. Soviet spokesman <PERSON> Andrei </PERSON> <PERSON> Romanov </PERSON> told the Norwegian news agency <ORGANIZATION> NTB </ORGANIZATION> the <ORGANIZATION> Maxim </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gorky </ORGANIZATION> anchored in the bay with 184 crew aboard. Temporary repairs were being made there to allow the ship to sail to <LOCATION> Bremerhaven </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, its port of embarkation. He did not estimate how long repairs would take. Soviet news reports said the ship would be back in service in three weeks. The Soviet newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Sovietskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rossiya </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday the ship may have rammed a metal object frozen in the ice or that a large old piece of ice unexpectedly surfaced. Norwegian maritime experts said the <PERSON> Maxim </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorky </PERSON> was sailing too fast for conditions in an area clogged with drifting ice up to 20 feet thick. <PERSON> Sigurn </PERSON> <PERSON> Kleiven </PERSON>, commander of the Norwegian coast guard vessel Senja, which rescued passengers, dimissed claims the Soviet crew was drunk during the accident or rescue. A Norwegian doctor aboard the <PERSON> Senja </PERSON> said Wednesday that Soviet sailors were intoxicated. `` There was absolutely no drunkenness on the part of the Soviet crew involved in the rescue,'' <PERSON> Kleiven </PERSON> was quoted as saying in the daily newspaper Aftenposten. He did say, however, that some waiters, service personnel and passengers had been drinking. Some passengers spent seven hours in open boats among the ice floes waiting to be taken to safety and were given alcohol by the crew. `` Drinking alcohol during exposure to cold is a bad combination,'' said <PERSON> Mads </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON>, the Norwegian doctor.
