<FIRST>r a AM-SeabrookTest     06-22 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Seabrook Test,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Valve Problem Stops Low-Power Test</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEABROOK, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Low-power testing of the reactor at the <LOCATION> Seabrook </LOCATION> nuclear power plant was halted Thursday because of a problem with a steam valve, operators said. The reactor was running at 3 percent of maximum power at the engineers shut it down, said spokesman <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Sher </PERSON>. `` The valve remained open longer than it should have, drawing too much steam away from the plant's steam generators,'' <PERSON> Sher </PERSON> said. `` Under our strict operating procedures, control room operators manually shut down the reactor.'' He said the engineers went to work to correct the problem so the reactor could be re-started. He said the valve was on the non-nuclear side of the plant. Hot, pressurized, contaminated water from the reactor flows through a heat exchanger and back to the reactor. On the non-nuclear side, water flows into the heat exchanger, picks up heat from the nuclear side and becomes steam to drive the turbines that spin the plant's generators <PERSON> Sher </PERSON> said the valve directs steam that normally would drive the plant's turbines back to a steam condenser instead. He said the steam bypasses the turbines during low-power testing. Because it stayed open, more steam condensed to water, thus cooling the system too quickly. <PERSON> Sher </PERSON> said the problem was n't considered serious enough to warrant notifications to state and federal regulatory officials, but <ORGANIZATION> Nuclear </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> observers were in the control room at the time. <PERSON> Sher </PERSON> said the valve, one of about 6,000 in the plant, is not associated with three other valves that malfunctioned earlier this month, delaying the start of the tests. `` The reason we do tests is to ensure that all plant systems are working as designed. The low-power testing of the reactor in the past nine days has gone very well, and this is the first interruption we've had in the schedule,'' he said. <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> officials won regulatory permission to conduct the tests despite long opposition from <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> and anti-nuclear activists who argue nearby beaches and communities could never be safely evacuated in the event of an accident. The plant has not yet won a commercial operating license, but utility officials predict they will be selling <PERSON> Seabrook </PERSON> power by the end of the year.
