<HEAD>Congress Told Out-of-Staters Trashing Ohio, Buckeyes Are ``Truly
Engaged''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> was told Thursday that out-of-staters are trashing <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, leaving <ORGANIZATION> Buckeyes </ORGANIZATION> `` truly enraged'' about having tons of garbage heaped on them by their neighboring states. An <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> official, saying `` we could become the next <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> in just a few years,'' urged <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to slap a $ 40-a-ton fee on long-haul garbage to discourage interstate trafficking in trash. `` We simply do not have adequate disposal capacity to become the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>'s dumping ground,'' <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Sahli </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Solid </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Waste </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advisory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Deieso </PERSON>, assistant commissioner of the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jersey </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION>, said `` we understand completely'' the concerns of states gaining garbage, since <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> had been a dump for <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>. He suggested <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> order every state to become self-sufficient. <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> last year took in 2.4 million tons of out-of-state waste, double what came in the previous year. Nearly 20 percent of the waste disposed of in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> is generated elsewhere and the heap is growing, <PERSON> Sahli </PERSON> told the transportation and hazardous materials subcommittee. Landfills are filling up or being closed because of pollution problems, <PERSON> Sahli </PERSON> said. `` We in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> have a home-grown crisis on our hands,'' he said. `` The importing of wastes has truly enraged the citizens of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>.'' `` We're the dumping ground,'' agreed Rep. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Luken </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, chairman of the subcommittee. Witnesses said <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> is n't alone. The <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> said 15,000 landfills have closed over the past 10 years, leaving about 5,000 nationwide. All of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s landfills must close within 10 years because of threats to groundwater, the environmental group added. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Templet </PERSON>, secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Louisiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Quality </ORGANIZATION>, said that state is down to 40 landfills, compared with 800 in operation in 1980. `` Solid waste management in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> has reached crisis proportions,'' said <PERSON> Templet </PERSON>, who asked the subcommittee to consider a national recycling program and strict landfill guidelines. Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.M. </LOCATION>, said his state has been `` victimized by the lack of federal policy'' on solid waste. `` States like mine are virtually unprotected,'' he told the panel. <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> asked the panel to consider his bill giving states the right to reject the interstate transfer of solid waste. Rep. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Kanjorski </PERSON>, D-Pa., said he was introducing legislation to treat trash the same way the government treats low-level radioactive waste His bill would force states to develop regional compacts to deal with the garbage problem collectively. The <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> official asked the panel to tax garbage sent long distances and then use the money to encourage recycling and to increase <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> funding for developing better ways of handling solid waste. `` Such a tax would act as an incentive to states to take care of their own waste disposal needs and not create devastating economic dislocation and potential environmental problems in communities located hundreds of miles away,'' he said.
