<HEAD>Jury Finds Woman Guilty On All Counts In Murder Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DOVER, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A woman accused of `` shopping around'' at nurseries for a baby to steal was convicted Thursday of killing a couple she had stalked for days, snatching their 9-day-old son and trying to pass him off as her own. Jurors who found <PERSON> Joyce </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> guilty on all counts meet Friday to begin deciding whether she should be executed by lethal injection or sentenced to life in prison without probation or parole. Mrs. <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON>, 36, had accused her husband, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON>, of killing <PERSON> Beverly </PERSON> and <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> on Christmas Eve 1987, drugging her and duping her into believing that she had given birth. <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON>, 27, faces a trial in September. Both were charged with two counts of murder, two counts of felony murder, one count of conspiracy and one count each of possession of a deadly weapon during the commission of a felony, burglary and unlawful imprisonment. The state contends the Lynches shot the <ORGANIZATION> Gibsons </ORGANIZATION> and took 9-day-old <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON> because Mrs. <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> could no longer have children. Prosecutors accused them of `` shopping around'' at nurseries `` until they stumbled upon <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON>.'' `` They hunted the <ORGANIZATION> Gibsons </ORGANIZATION> down, stalked them for at least a week and murdered them to get that child,'' Deputy Attorney General <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> said during closing arguments Wednesday in <ORGANIZATION> Kent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>. During 16 days of testimony, the defense portrayed Mrs. <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> as a victim of her husband. She claimed <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON> controlled her by injecting her with overdoses of a prescription pain-killer she needed for a back ailment. Mrs. <PERSON> Lynch </PERSON>, who had two children from a previous marriage, also claimed her husband duped her into believing she was pregnant, and told her she had given birth to <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> while she was asleep. She said she was at the crime scene, but because she was heavily drugged, she thought it was a dream. When she awakened, there was a baby. The state contended she was the mastermind because she knew she had had a hysterectomy in 1978. <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON>, 32, was found in a pool of blood by his then-5-year-old daughter, <PERSON> Rebecca </PERSON>, and 1-year-old son, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON>. Mrs. <PERSON> Gibson </PERSON>, 27, was found slumped over the steering wheel of her car, clutching the cloth diaper she used when burping <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON>. The prosecution said one of the Lynches took <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> from her arms. <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> was with the Lynches when they were arrested Jan. 7, 1988. <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> and his brother and sister have been raised by their paternal grandparents.
