<HEAD>U.S. Pilot Claims World Record Flight Over North Pole</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELSINKI, Finland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A retired <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> colonel said Thursday he had made a solo flight over the North Pole in a single-engine plane. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Mack </PERSON> said he flew from <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Barrow </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> in 19 hours, 58 minutes, and claimed a world record for the solo 2,970-mile flight in his Beechcraft Bonanza BE-36. There was no independent verification. Officials at <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION>'s airport said <PERSON> Mack </PERSON> landed about 7 p.m., but they did not know were he came from. <PERSON> Mack </PERSON>, 68, of <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, said he planned the trip for midsummer so he could use the arctic's seasonal 24-hour sunlight to help him navigate. He said he had to make adjustments to his gyro-compass every 20 minutes to keep from straying off course. He also navigated by sun sightings, a sun dial and radio direction-finding equipment. `` I chose <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> from Point Barrow to <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> because it's a straight line over the North Pole,'' he said. `` If I went to <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION>, then somebody could say I went beside the North Pole.'' <PERSON> Mack </PERSON> said he flew over ice for most of the trip and said clouds often blocked his view, but he made some videotapes. He flew near the west end of <LOCATION> Spitzbergen </LOCATION> island and over <LOCATION> Finland </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Helsinki </LOCATION> in the Beechcraft. He had planned to fly at 160 mph at an altitude of 3,000 to 5,000 feet. <PERSON> Mack </PERSON>, a former fighter pilot, said he has more than 14,000 hours of flight time, including solo flights from <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and back. He left south <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> on June 13 and plans to return via <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Iceland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> next month.
