<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> on Thursday convened the first military review meeting since the Soviet withdrawal from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> and said the goverment needs `` a new tempo and dramatic steps'' to fight the guerrillas. `` It is too early to talk about final victory,'' <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> told members of the 22-member <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> and military commanders from <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s 28 provinces. `` We should think in terms of how to get rid of the imposed war and put an end to it.'' Western journalists were invited to attend the inauguration of the meeting, held a day after <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> announced it had a broken a 15-week rebel siege of the eastern city of <LOCATION> Jalalabad </LOCATION>. Guerrillas based in <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> denied the claim. The lifting of the siege would represent the biggest military victory for the government since the last Soviet troops withdrew in February, ending their nine-year involvement in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. The military review was the first since the Soviet withdrawal, and diplomats say it was called to plan a new strategy against the rebels. <PERSON> Najib </PERSON> used the occasion to renew attacks on <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, which supports the Moslem guerrillas fighting <PERSON> Najib </PERSON>'s Soviet-backed government. `` The grave dangers emanating from the satanic plans of <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> ... pose a serious threat to peace, security and stability in the region,'' he said. The president also said <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and other rebel supporters `` did not want to stop the war, they want to continue the bloodshed.''
