<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Too little is known about the spotted owl to justify closing off vast portions of the ancient forests of the <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> to logging, the head of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. `` I do n't think we ought to penalize the people of the <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION>, throw people out of work, close down towns, until a biological decision can be made properly,'' <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>, chief of the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said as two <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittees wrapped up two days of joint hearings. <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> said his agency has begun a five-year study of the owl, which is thought to nest only in the old-growth forests of <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and northern <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. He said there was insufficient scientific on the owl to justify a 50 percent reduction in the timber harvest from the national forests of the Northwest this year. A federal judge in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> has enjoined the agency from offering 162 timber sales planned during the current fiscal year in those forests involving 1.4 billion board feet. <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> said that represents roughly 25 percent of the timber sale program scheduled this year and said the injunction might be expanded so it would eventually affect sales involving 2.5 billion board feet or half of the sales planned in the region. The injunction was sought by environmentalists who want to have the owl protected as a threatened or endangered species as part of their campaign to halt logging in the old-growth forests of the Northwest. The timber industry has claimed such protection would create an economic catastrophe for dozens of one-mill towns in the region. The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> has proposed the owl for listing as a threatened species, but it will take between 18 months and two years before a final decision is made. The hearings were held by the national parks and public lands subcommittee of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and the forests, family farms and energy subcommittee of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> said that 60 percent of the timber available for harvest in western <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> was old-growth, much of it prime habitat for the spotted owl. <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON> faced harsh criticism from <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> Democratic Rep. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> DeFazio </PERSON>, who charged the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> had done little since the injunction was issued four months ago to soften its impact on the region. `` Are you trying to precipitate a crisis in the hope that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will bail you out?'' <PERSON> DeFazio </PERSON> asked, adding that the agency has yet to appeal the injunction and took two months before it responded to a letter he wrote asking if there were alternative sales that could be offered quickly.
