<HEAD>American, Delta Drop Reservations System Merger</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial circuits.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lines </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday dropped plans to merge their computer reservation systems because the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> threatened to sue to block the $ 2 billion joint venture. `` The likely result of this transaction would be higher fares and poorer service for airline passengers,'' Attorney General <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said in a statement announcing the department's intention to file a civil antitrust suit. <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Berry </PERSON> announced that the two carriers had given up trying to merge their computer then said, `` We decided it would take too much time to fight this in court. American operates <ORGANIZATION> Sabre </ORGANIZATION>, the leading system among the five used by practically all airlines and travel agents. <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION>'s system is Datas II, the smallest of the CRS _ for computer reservation system _ ventures. `` We feel that Justice is wrong,'' <PERSON> Berry </PERSON> said. `` We really were surprised. We felt that this partnership was giving the government what it wanted, in terms of taking the -LRB- reservation -RRB- systems out of the ownership of individual airlines, making it an autonomous company.'' Said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Crandall </PERSON>, chairman and president of American: `` While the decision clearly means that we can not create a joint venture with another domestic airline that sponsors a competing CRS, we will continue to offer partnership interests in Sabre to domestic airlines which do not sponsor a competing CRS, to foreign airlines and to other interested companies.'' The computer systems provide up-to-the minute information on video screens about schedules, fares, seat availability, hotels, car rentals and package vacations. They allow users to make reservations and issue tickets in seconds, and are the primary channel for the distribution of tickets. The systems give airlines the practically instantaneous data on seat sales that lets the carriers quickly change prices, blackout dates, advance purchase requirements and other conditions that form their `` yield management'' strategies. American's <ORGANIZATION> Sabre </ORGANIZATION> had $ 445 million in fee revenues and approximately 41 percent of the national market in 1988, the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said. <ORGANIZATION> Delta </ORGANIZATION>'s 7-year-old Datas II is the youngest system, with about $ 68 million in revenues and approximately 7 percent of the market. The three other systems are joint operations of <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> USAir </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION>, and <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>. In 1986, travel agents paid about $ 287 million in fees to the systems and airlines paid $ 600 million, the department said. <PERSON> Thornburgh </PERSON> said the lawsuit would allege that the joint venture would violate the <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> and the <PERSON> Sherman </PERSON> acts because it likely would substantially lessen competition both in the sale of services to travel agents and in the provision of scheduled airline passenger service. `` Travel agents using a particular <ORGANIZATION> CRS </ORGANIZATION> tend to sell a disproportionately high number of tickets on that <ORGANIZATION> CRS </ORGANIZATION> owner's airline,'' said <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Whalley </PERSON>, acting assistant attorney general in the antitrust division Since 1986, airlines have been forbidden to favor their own flights in the computer display listings. <PERSON> Berry </PERSON> said his company and American intended to sell up to 50 percent of the merged system to other airlines and already had received expressions of interest from <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Lufthansa </ORGANIZATION> and more than a dozen other carriers. `` Last week, we became aware that <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> felt it had a problem with this partnership,'' <PERSON> Berry </PERSON> said. `` We attempted to resolve it. There was really nothing we could do.''
