<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Coach,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Narrows Ability to Sue for Discrimination</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Scotus Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> added Thursday to a string of defeats for civil rights forces with a decision that gives cities new protection against certain lawsuits accusing them of racial bias and other violations. Voting 5-4, the justices used the case of a former <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> high school football coach to narrow the scope of a century-old civil rights law. The coach said he was transferred to another school because he is white. Justice <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, writing for the court, said the 1866 law can be used to sue a city only if it can be proved the alleged violation of civil rights was part of an official municipal policy. It is not enough to show that a city employee, acting in an official capacity, violated someone's rights, she said. `` Once those officials who have the power to make official policy on a particular issue have been identified, it is for the jury to determine whether their decisions have caused the deprivation of rights at issue by policies which affirmatively command that it occur,'' she said. The high court previously limited a civil rights law enacted in 1871 _ a statute also known as the <PERSON> Ku </PERSON> <PERSON> Klux </PERSON> Klan Act _ in the same way. Thursday's ruling is particularly significant because of the potential big-money damages the 1866 law provides for winners of such suits. The ruling is the latest in a series of defeats handed civil rights plaintiffs this year by a newly solidified conservative majority on the court. In a dissenting opinion, Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> said the latest decision is `` astonishing'' because the court did not allow pro-civil rights forces to present their side fully. `` It is not only unfair to decide the case on this basis,'' he said. `` It is unwise.'' The court ruled against <PERSON> Norman </PERSON> <PERSON> Jett </PERSON>, longtime coach and athletic director at <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cliff </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>. He sued the <ORGANIZATION> Dallas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> and others. A federal jury awarded <PERSON> Jett </PERSON> $ 850,000 in damages, reduced by a federal trial judge to about $ 563,000. A federal appeals court overturned the award. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday that <PERSON> Jett </PERSON> could get a new trial to determine whether he can recover any money from the school district. But the decision makes his case considerably more difficult to prove. <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said a federal appeals court could grant <PERSON> Jett </PERSON> a new trial against the city only if it determines that the school superintendent who ordered him transferred had policy-making authority granted by <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> law in the area of employee transfers. <PERSON> Jett </PERSON> had coached the <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cliff </ORGANIZATION> football team since 1962 when, in the spring of 1983, he was transferred to another city high school. <PERSON> Jett </PERSON> had been named head coach and athletic director at the school in 1970, the year the racial composition at <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Oak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cliff </LOCATION> changed from predominantly white to predominantly black. <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> Todd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Oak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cliff </LOCATION>'s black principal who held that job since 1975, was also sued by <PERSON> Jett </PERSON> for replacing him with a black coach. According to court records, the relationship between <PERSON> Todd </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jett </PERSON> grew more tense after <ORGANIZATION> South </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cliff </ORGANIZATION> lost to <LOCATION> Plano </LOCATION> in the state high school championship in November 1982. <PERSON> Jett </PERSON> said <PERSON> Todd </PERSON> believed that the only way for South Oak Cliff to compete was to hire a black coach who in turn would recruit black players. <PERSON> Jett </PERSON> said that school officials violated his due-process, free-speech and equal-protection rights. <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> was joined in dissent by Justices <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>. Joining <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> were Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> and Justices <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON> and <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>.
