<HEAD>Eds: Rachael is cq in 6th graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JUDY DAUBENMIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Women who once knocked on the doors of all-male clubs to try to crack the good old boys' network formed their own informal grapevine Thursday to boost members of their sex. Members of the Association of Good Old Girls, AGOG, promise never to make decisions in a locker room, in a bar or on the golf course. `` It's fun and it's serious at the same time,'' said <PERSON> Denise </PERSON> <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON>, who helped found the group. Fifteen women gathered amidst exhibits on feminist history at the <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> Women's Historical Center and Hall of Fame for the first AGOG meeting. They raised their right hands and, shouting `` AGOG,'' they pledged to function as an informal network of women helping other women climb to the top in their business or profession, just as men have done by swapping information over drinks or lunch. <PERSON> Rachael </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON>, a co-founder of the association, said the women are trying to copy the good old boy network, rather than dismantle it, because they know it works. Boys begin training to join the network when they are youngsters by taking part in sports that teach cooperation and teamwork, she said. As adults, men holding top positions socialize with each other and learn about job openings, business opportunities and promotion possibilities, she said. `` That's the topic of their social interaction and because there are so few women in similar positions it's very difficult for women to have access to those same pieces of information,'' she said. Any man or woman who is willing to help women get ahead is a member in good standing of AGOG, said <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON>, who dreamed up the name because she liked the meaning of `` agog'' _ intense excitement. <PERSON> Moreno </PERSON>, an associate superintendent of <ORGANIZATION> Genesee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION>, said women already are giving each other a helping hand up the corporate level. `` From whatever position I hold or whatever organization I belong to, I make sure women have the opportunity to participate, to be promoted, to have some visibility and most of all to learn from real experiences, learn about leadership,'' she said. But she said the good old girls network needs the extra visibility that a semi-serious organization like AGOG can give it. `` I do n't believe that we have the numbers yet because it takes women in almost every organization, agency and industry in order to establish that kind of comprehensive network,'' she said. The group, which includes women in real estate, higher education and politics, has a copyright on its name and a logo, three female stick figures with hands joined. They plan to offer information to women around the country who want to form their own chapters.
