<HEAD>With AM-Bush</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY31</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A young man who lives in a homeless shelter told President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Thursday that it's more profitable to sell drugs than work for the minimum wage. `` $ 100 a week, that's no money,'' said 18-year-old <PERSON> Walter </PERSON>. `` I can make $ 100 in 15 minutes'' selling drugs. Another resident agreed. `` Working in McDonald's _ at the minimum wage _ it just does n't pay,'' <PERSON> Monique </PERSON>, 20, told <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> after he asked why young people ended up on the street <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> recently vetoed an increase in the minimum wage from $ 3.35 an hour to $ 4.55, saying he'll support an increase to $ 4.25 an hour with the stipulation of a lower training wage for new employees. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON>, met for about 30 minutes with 11 residents of <ORGANIZATION> Covenant </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, a shelter for homeless youths located three blocks from Times Square. Covenant House asked that the residents be identified only by their first names. `` You do n't want to be there,'' <PERSON> Monique </PERSON> told <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> when he asked about the problems of living on the street. She said she had no home and had been abused as a child. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON>, who said his mother was dead and his father an alcoholic, also said he had no home. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> asked <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> what he wanted to do with his life. <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> said he hoped to learn electronics, carpentry or plumbing. `` I want a good job _ so I can get a house, a dog, a rabbit and babies,'' <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> said. Mrs. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> cradled a 3-week-old baby, <ORGANIZATION> Crystal </ORGANIZATION>, whose mother was a resident of the shelter, as <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spoke with the youths.
