<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Sidney </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yates </PERSON>, a 20-term Democratic congressman from <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, received emergency medical attention Thursday after bumping his knee in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> chamber. He later said he `` almost fainted because the pain was so intense.'' Six white-coated members of the congressional medical staff rushed to the aid of the 79-year-old lawmaker from <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> at about 12:30 p.m. EDT when he fell forward in a seat after voting on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor. They put a blood-pressure cuff on his left arm and what appeared to be a heart monitor on his chest, and talked to him for about 15 minutes before taking him out of the chamber in a wheelchair. He said he felt fine, though he was pale, when he left for more examination at the attending physician's office in the Capitol. `` I'm feeling very well,'' he said later by telephone from his office. `` I voted and I was on my way back, turning up the aisle and bumped my knee. I almost fainted because the pain was so intense.'' He said there was no permanent damage to his knee, but he was keeping an ice pack on it to ease the pain. <PERSON> Yates </PERSON> had just participated in a parliamentary vote approving Wednesday's <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> work. The vote was followed by brief speeches, which continued while the emergency crew worked on <PERSON> Yates </PERSON> in a chair toward the rear of the chamber.
