<HEAD>Drought Had Little Impact on Quality of Corn</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Drought a year ago bit deeply into the 1988 corn crop but did n't do much damage to the grain that was harvested, an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report said Thursday. <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, administrator of the department's <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inspection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said the drought had little impact on the `` quality characteristics'' of last year's corn, including test weights, moisture and kernel damage. The annual report did not include statistics for aflatoxin content of the 1988 corn harvest. Aflatoxin is a cancer-causing substance that can result from certain kinds of fungus under drought stress conditions. Some corn harvested last fall had been reported as having high levels of aflatoxin, prompting fears that the tainted grain could cause harm in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> food chain.
