<HEAD>Pentagon Official Confident Bomber Will Perform as Anticipated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> official in charge of testing new weapons said Thursday he is confident the B-2 bomber, set to be flown in a few weeks, will perform as anticipated. `` I do n't see any indications the B-2 ca n't do what it intends to do,'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Krings </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s Operational Test and Evaluation office, told reporters However, <PERSON> Krings </PERSON>, who is leaving at the end of the month, refused to discuss whether he thought the B-2, the so-called Stealth, was worth the money, a question raised by some members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Krings </PERSON> said politicians and defense analysts will have to decide if they're willing to pay for the bomber. Each B-2 bomber is expected to cost over $ 500 million and there are plans to build 132 of them. <ORGANIZATION> Northrop </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> is building the plane at its <LOCATION> Palmdale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, plant. The plane, described as resembling a `` flying wing'' without conventional fuselage, is designed to penetrate Soviet borders without being detected by radar. The plane has no sharp angles and relies on the use of radar-absorbing coatings on its surface, officials have said. <PERSON> Krings </PERSON> said the B-2 has not been operationally tested in the field yet, but individual systems were tried out along the way. The <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> says the B-2 will not be deployed before 1991. Meantime, <PERSON> Krings </PERSON> defended the record of his office, which has been criticized by some lawmakers who say it has failed to test weapons adequately and is too cozy with defense contracting firms. <PERSON> Krings </PERSON> said his office had succeeded in forcing the services to improve the weapons before they are deployed. `` The list that did n't go into production because of our arguments, there were many, but they are sometimes hard to find,'' he said. For instance, some contractors have delayed testing in order not to fail, he said. They say, `` We are delaying because we do n't want to fail the test,'' he said. As an example, he cited the testing of cellular radios that were postponed for about four months.
