<HEAD>Female Veterans Often Feel Unentitled</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Female veterans often miss out on benefits for which they qualify because they have a low opinion of their service records, witnesses told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee Thursday. `` They do n't see themselves as veterans,'' said retired Rear Adm. <PERSON> Frances </PERSON> <PERSON> Shea-Buckley </PERSON>, chairwoman of the advisory committee on women veterans for the Department of Veterans Affairs. `` They feel that only men are veterans. They say things like ` I only served two years. I did n't go overseas.''' Women can get all the benefits available to male veterans as long as they have spent one year in service, said Dr. <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mather </PERSON>, chief of women's programs for the Department of Veterans Affairs. One estimate says women make up 4 percent of all veterans. Among those benefits are extensive health care opportunities, educational assistance and housing loans. Rep. <PERSON> Lane </PERSON> <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>, D-Ill., chairman of the Veterans Affairs subcommittee on oversight and investigations, called the hearing as a follow-up to the first hearing on the subject two years ago `` We want to learn what progress has been made during the last two years in realizing the equitable provision of benefits and services to women veterans,'' said <PERSON> Evans </PERSON>. <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Caldwell </PERSON>, a military nurse who is chairwoman of the advisory commission on women veterans in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>, told of a veterans hospital in her state is ill equipped to give women even basic service. <PERSON> Caldwell </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Lyons </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> had only men's pajamas, no personal sanitary supplies and no gynecological clinic for out-patients. She said by contrast, the <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION>, provides women those basic medical needs. `` Not all VA hospitals are created equal in terms of facilities, supplies or services provided veterans,'' said <PERSON> Caldwell </PERSON>. <PERSON> Mather </PERSON> said that in the last six or seven years the attitude of the government toward female veterans has improved, though `` it may not have filtered down to every level.'' <PERSON> Caldwell </PERSON> shared <PERSON> Shea-Buckley </PERSON>'s opinion about getting women to come forward as veterans. `` In particular, certain <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION> era women veterans speak of being ridiculed by family and friends upon their return to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Caldwell </PERSON> said. She said they do n't act proud of their service or use it to gain benefits rightfully theirs. `` When pressed for details, they often reply, ` I'd rather forget that part of my life,''' she said. She said World War II veterans are most vocal about their needs, primarily nursing care since they are now among the aging population. The 1980 Census, the first to ask women if they were veterans, counted 1.13 million women had served in the armed forces. That was 3.1 percent of the veteran population. Female veterans' now are believed to comprise about 4 percent of the veteran population, said <PERSON> Mather </PERSON>.
