<FIRST>u a AM-ExxonValdez     06-22 0647</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Exxon Valdez,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crippled Tanker To Be Moved Friday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VALDEZ, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Nearly three months after it caused the nation's worst oil spill, the damaged tanker <PERSON> Exxon </PERSON> <PERSON> Valdez </PERSON> will be towed out of Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON> on Friday for a $ 25 million repair job in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>, authorities said. The <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> said the 987-foot vessel will leave the shelter of <LOCATION> Outside </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> on the southwest side of Naked Island in the heart of the sound during the morning, weather permitting. The Exxon Valdez has been undergoing temporary repairs at Outside Bay since about two weeks after it ran aground at <LOCATION> Bligh </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Reef </LOCATION> on March 24, ripping its hull and spilling nearly 11 million gallons of crude oil drawn from wells on <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s North Slope. Eight of the vessel's 13 tanks were penetrated by the reef and divers reported finding rocks as large as small cars in the cargo hold. But the tanks have been cleaned to the point that small schools of herring and salmon have been reported living in them. The hull also has been steam-cleaned. Divers drilled numerous holes along many cracks in the hull and plated over them to keep the cracks from spreading. One crack was said to run through the hull until about midship. The cracks had to be immobilized with plates out of concern that rough seas could break the vessel in half. Several of the vessel's tanks remain unsealed, <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> said. Coast Guard and salvage officials said air pressure in the tanks would keep seawater at maneageable levels. The tanker will be towed by two tugs, and accompanied by a salvage vessel and a third tug. But <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> said the tanker's engines are in working order and will be be used at the skipper's discretion. Since the spill, oil has soiled more than 700 miles of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s southern coastline Some of the oil has flushed out of the sound and traveled with <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> currents some 400 miles to <LOCATION> Kodiak </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>. Workers have recovered more than 26,000 birds killed by the oil, although biologists say the figure probably represents 10 percent or less of the overall toll. Other casualties have included more than 50 eagles and nearly 800 sea otters. The spill forced closure of numerous herring and salmon fisheries and severely curtailed others. Exxon has more than 9,000 people, backed up by 800 boats and a small air force, working to clean up the spill. <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> said this week it already has spent more than $ 200 million on the job, and the state has billed <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> more than $ 12 million for oil-spill expenses. Under a procedure established two weeks after the spill, the state sends its bills to <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>, which pays most of the suppliers and contractors directly and reimburses the state for out-of-pocket costs, said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Nizich </PERSON>, administrative services director for Gov. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON>'s office. Batches of invoices have been sent almost daily to <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>. `` Some of them were pretty hefty in size,'' <PERSON> Nizich </PERSON> said. A <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> officer will be on board the <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valdez </ORGANIZATION> until it leaves Prince <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Sound </PERSON>, about 60 miles from <LOCATION> Naked </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION>, and again when the vessel nears <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION>, where the ship was built. <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> said seven Exxon officers and four salvage experts would be on board throughout the voyage, expected to take about 20 days, at about 6 mph. One worker was killed during the cleanup, and there have numerous injuries in boat and plane accidents as well as from falls on oil-slickened beaches. The former captain of the Exxon Valdez, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON>, has been charged with six criminal counts arising from the spill. Among other things, the state alleges he was drunk at the time. <PERSON> Hazelwood </PERSON> has pleaded innocent to all charges. Court officials say it is unlikely his trial will take place until fall or early winter.
