<SECOND>AM-Magnetic Train,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Urges U.S. Commitment To Magnetically Levitated Trains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> can regain the lead in developing magnetically levitated trains with a 300 mph potential, but if it does n't act soon <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> will dominate the field, according to a report released Thursday. `` Mag-lev'' will be an important transportation mode by the year 2000, and decisions made in the next five years will determine which country gets the patents and leads the industry, said an advisory committee to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION>. `` Because of the overseas competition evolving in this technology, <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s window of opportunity is already beginning to close,'' the committee wrote. Now is the chance for the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to leapfrog the competition by creating the second generation of mag-lev trains using superconducting electromagnets, according to the committee. It did not mean the new high-temperature superconductors, but rather the well-understood, extremely low temperature technology used over the past 10 years or so for medical imaging devices, particle accelerators and other devices in high-tech firms around the world. The advisory group prepared the study at the request of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Sen. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON>, second-ranking Democrat on the committee and sponsor of legislation authorizing the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> to develop such trains. The report recommends that the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government allocate $ 750 million over six years to develop, test and demonstrate several mag-lev prototypes. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> and <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Danby </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Brookhaven </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, co-developers of mag-lev trains, outlined the pluses at a news conference. Among them: they are faster than cars or conventional railroads; they consume less energy than automobiles or airplanes; they pollute less; they can run in any weather and they experience little wear. Mag-lev trains run on a cushion of air above a guideway, suspended by magnets on the train and in the guideway whose like poles repel each other. A moving magnetic field in the guideway attracts a magnet on the train of opposite polarity, pulling the train at high speed. Current magnets hold the train about three-eighths of an inch off the rails; superconducting models could offer higher stability with a six-inch elevation. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> pioneered mag-lev transportation in the 1960s and 1970s, but went only as far as building prototypes and scale models, said the report. The effort was abandoned in 1975 for lack of federal funds, `` but was picked up and carried on in a spirit of raging incrementalism by the Japanese.'' `` That <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> walked away from this effort more than a decade ago is demonstrative of the commercial technology lapses our country is prone to stumble into, characterized most visibly by the forfeiting of billion-dollar markets in consumer electronics and dynamic random access memory semiconductors _ two <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> inventions commercially exploited by <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>,'' the report said. `` We see many benefits. We do n't see any serious drawbacks,'' <PERSON> Powell </PERSON> said. At present, the Japanese are testing a full-scale 325 mph vehicle. <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> has tested a similar 256 mph system.
</TEXT>
