<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democrats and Republicans rushed to Old Glory's defense Thursday as the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> passed a resolution condemning the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision giving First Amendment protection to those who desecrate the American flag In addition to the resolution urging the high court to reconsider Wednesday's decision, a variety of bills aimed at circumventing the ruling were tossed into legislative hoppers. `` <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> has believed that the act of desecrating the flag is clearly not ` speech' as protected by the First Amendment,'' said the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> resolution, co-sponsored by Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>, and Minority Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, R-Kan. The resolution, which passed 97-3, voiced alarm that the ruling may invalidate federal law and statutes in 48 states prohibiting destruction of the flag. Sens. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, both Democrats, and <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hampshire </LOCATION>, a Republican, voted against the resolution. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> `` has the last word on the meaning of the Constitution'' and that the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> should n't go on record criticizing the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> for carrying out its duty. <PERSON> Humphrey </PERSON> said that while he did n't like anyone burning or defacing the flag, he asked, `` What defines desecration?'' `` This seems to me to be an exercise in silliness and a little bit of hypocrisy,'' he said. `` It strikes me as intellectually dishonest.'' The high court, in a 5-4 vote, threw out the conviction of <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> `` <PERSON> Joey </PERSON><PERSON> '' </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, who was sentenced to a year in jail and fined $ 2,000 for burning the flag in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. The court said the flag burning at a demonstration in <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION> during the 1984 Republican National Convention was a form of expression protected by the Constitution's guarantee of freedom of speech. The decision was greeted with virtually universal outrage on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. `` Shame on these judges,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Burton </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ind </LOCATION>. `` Shame on you, shame on you!.'' `` We must stand for <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. The flag, the flag. <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. For us!'' bellowed Sen. <PERSON> Strom </PERSON> <PERSON> Thurmond </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-S.C. </LOCATION> `` The First Amendment guarantees everyone the freedom to speak, but it guarantees no one an audience for his words,'' said <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, a former federal judge. `` I do not believe that Americans have to see the flag, that symbolizes their freedom to speak, devalued and cheapened in the cause of preserving that freedom.'' `` The act of flag burning is not meant to convey any political idea,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Dornan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Calif </LOCATION>., who was among those introducing legislation to amend the Constitution to prohibit flag-desecration `` It is an act that is solely meant to provoke and offend.'' `` With this decision, the court cloaks the most offensive behavior as political expression,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> <PERSON> Pickett </PERSON>, D-Va., who introduced a resolution aimed at nullifying the court decision Rep. 