<HEAD>Chemical Industry Now Supports Toxics Legislation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's chemical manufacturers said Thursday they have abandoned their previous opposition, and now support new legislation to control airborne toxic chemicals. `` We intend to be a constructive player in the legislative process,'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Forney </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Du </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pont </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> executive, told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> environment subcommittee on behalf of the <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Forney </PERSON> said the chemical industry's trade group previously believed new legislation was unnecessary, but has now concluded the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> `` can not adequately regulate air emissions under the existing law.'' But <PERSON> Forney </PERSON> and other industry witnesses clashed with Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON>, D-Calif., the subcommittee chairman, over the need for provisions designed to prevent accidental chemical releases <PERSON> Forney </PERSON> said `` a great deal has been done by industry'' to prevent accidents, and `` we do n't believe additional legislation is required.'' `` I find it difficult to understand that position,'' <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON> said, citing <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> figures showing there were more than 4,700 accidential releases between 1980 and 1987. The 120 most serious releases killed 145 people, injured more than 5,000, and caused nearly 250,000 to evacuate their homes, <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> V. </PERSON> <PERSON> Poje </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION> said it is essential that any legislation include provisions to deal with chemical accidents such as the disaster in <LOCATION> Bhopal </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> in 1984. In that case, more than 3,000 people died when the rupture of a storage tank unleased deadly methyl isocyanate. Industrial facilities and communities `` are unprepared to understand and respond to the consequences of chemical accidents,'' he said, testifying for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Coalition </ORGANIZATION>, representing environmental groups. One House bill, supported by <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON> and environmental groups, would require <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> to develop a list of substances most likely to endanger the public through accidental releases to the air and issue regulations to prevent such releases. The <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> has recently disclosed that some 2.7 billion pounds of toxic substances go into the air each year, but the agency only regulates only seven of more than 200 chemicals that are released. According to the agency, some 360 million pounds involve suspected carcinogens, contributing to between 1,500 and 3,000 fatal cancers each year. Chemical emissions also are factors in respiratory disease and birth defects. A number of legislative proposals, including a clean air package unveiled this month by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, would force industry to use the best available technology to reduce emissions. The proposals would regulate either the chemicals themselves or set limits for industrial categories such as steel mills or pulp and paper. Industry witnesses told the subcommittee, however, many of the solutions proposed so far would be too harsh and should be changed. `` Improvement can be made by adopting provisions ... for reasonable technology'' instead of the best available, said <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yosie </PERSON>, vice president for health and environment of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, the trade group for the oil industry. The controls, he said should be placed only on `` those sources found to be significant emitters of toxic air pollutants.''
