<HEAD>Witnesses Disagree on Permanent Airline Smoking Ban</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Several witnesses who object to smoking urged <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday to extend and expand a no-smoking policy on short airline flights, but the tobacco industry insisted that health research does n't justify a ban. More than two dozen witnesses submitted testimony at a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Public </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> aviation subcommittee hearing on several bills that would either make the temporary ban permanent or expand it to cover all flights. Smoking is outlawed on domestic flights of less than two hours, but the rule is to lapse in April 1990 unless <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> acts. Witnesses ranged from a flight attendant who said her health was ruined serving smoking passengers, to an indoor air expert who said there are worse health hazards _ including infectious disease _ in an airliner cabin than smoke. Opponents, including tobacco interests and some lawmakers, urged that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> await the results of a <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> study of the air aboard airliners before enacting any new law. The study is expected to be completed before the ban is lifted. `` Only a total ban on airline smoking will adequately protect the health and safety of airline passengers and flight crews,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Durbin </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ill </LOCATION>., who is sponsoring legislation that would give <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> a choice of making the ban permanent or expanding it to cover all commercial flights `` It is our job to esnure that those especially sensitive to cigarette smoke are free of having it foisted upon them in the confines of an airplane cabin,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Torricelli </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION> Reps. <PERSON> Lindsay </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, R-Ga., and <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> DeLay </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>, however, echoed the Tobacco industry's stand that no legislation should be passed before the airliner air quality study is completed `` I hope we will find a solution to this problem which will protect the rights of both those who choose to smoke and those who have decided not to do so,'' said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>. Representatives of several anti-smoking groups, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Respiratory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> and, the <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Flight </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Attendants </ORGANIZATION> called for a permanent ban of smoking on all flights, saying smoking poses a proven health hazard to nonsmoking passengers and crew as well as to smokers. Flight attendant <PERSON> Cathy </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilbert-Silva </PERSON> said working on flights where smoking was allowed severely affected her health. She complained of worsening sinus infections, bronchial problems, laryngitis, scratchy throat and blocked ears. `` A total ban will not cure me but I know I will not get worse and I can continue in the job I have grown to love without fear for my health,'' she said. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Whitley </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Tobacco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> said a permanent ban would unjustly abandon any effort to accommodate smokers. He said studies show that a nonsmoking passenger would have to make eight continuous New York-to-Tokyo roundtrip flights before being exposed to the nicotine equivalent of a single cigarette. <PERSON> Gray </PERSON> <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON>, president of a company that specializes in fighting indoor air pollution, <ORGANIZATION> ACVA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, said an airline passenger is more likely to get sick from bacteria, fungi and viruses floating in the poorly ventilated air tan from cigarette smoke. He said there is no scientific data to justify a smoking ban but took no position on the legislation. `` Ironically, there has been no evidence of excessive levels of carbon monoxide, airborne particulates or nicotine, all of which have been linked to tobacco smoke as a source,'' <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said. For 60 cents per passenger, ventilation can be increased to healthy levels on a <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> 747, <PERSON> Robinson </PERSON> said. He recommended that the committee pass legislation requiring improved ventilation and filtration of air on planes with regular inspections and monitoring of air quality levels.
