efense unit, would react in case of an attack from the Soviet bloc. The same day, <PERSON> Peri </PERSON> drove a military vehicle about 60 miles to a spot near the East German border. He abandoned the vehicle when it got stuck in a wooded area, walked to a border fence and climbed over it, carrying computer and discs. <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> said <PERSON> Peri </PERSON> `` wandered around in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> for about two hours,'' then went to a communist border guard tower and turned himself over to the East Germans, later handing over computer and discs to unidentified East German officials in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>. The prosecutor said analysis later showed the computer `` had been accessed and set up to print out material'' _ meaning the East Germans had copied the information. <PERSON> Graham </PERSON> then went into detail on exchanges between <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and East German officials after <PERSON> Peri </PERSON>'s abandoned vehicle was found on Feb. 24. He said the East Germans informed the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> on March 3 `` that they had released <PERSON> Peri </PERSON> to travel to a country of his choice,'' and that on the same day, the East Germans returned the computer and discs to <PERSON> Peri </PERSON>, who traveled by train to <LOCATION> Salzburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>. `` He stayed in one of the most expensive hotels in <LOCATION> Salzburg </LOCATION>,'' on the night of March 3, and the next day began traveling by train for his home unit in <LOCATION> Fulda </LOCATION>, where he was later arrested, the prosecutor said. <PERSON> Peri </PERSON> sat quietly during the session, occasionally whispering to his chief defense counsel, Maj. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stokes </PERSON>. His parents, <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> and <PERSON> Winnie </PERSON> <PERSON> Peri </PERSON>, and sister <PERSON> Desiree </PERSON>, from <LOCATION> Orange </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, were also present and sat listening quietly. The court martial proceedings are slated to continue Friday with testimony from <PERSON> Peri </PERSON>'s military associates and medical experts who have examined him.
