<HEAD>Final Filtration Rules Issued; Higher Bills in Sight</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS grafs 4-6 bgng: ``The new,'' with more detail on the
regulations.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 New regulations to protect the public from contaminated drinking water may prevent 90,000 cases of water-borne diseases every year but will mean higher water bills for millions of Americans, the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. The agency announced final regulations that will require nearly 10,000 providers of drinking water, serving an estimated 150 million people, to comply with strict filtration requirements to rid the water of disease-causing germs. The regulations, which apply to communities where drinking water comes from surface sources such as rivers and streams, are aimed at reducing the risk of illness from a variety of microscopic organisms such as viruses, bacteria and protozoa. The new regulations require that these public water systems use disinfectants of prescribed performance, and those not meeting certain strict purity standards must be treated by filtration. If not, states must devise another way to eliminate the germs, such as additional chemicals. Maximum concentrations are established for some microorganisms and treatment techniques are required for others. The rules also specify that treatment plant operators meet state qualifications and they set up new monitoring and reporting requirements. The agency has estimated that tens of thousands of people become ill yearly from such contamination. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> estimated the more stringent water purification procedures are likely to prevent annually about 90,000 illnesses, including diarrhea, nausea, vomiting and stomach upsets. `` These rules are a major step forward in providing maximum protection for our nation's drinking-water supplies,'' said <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Reilly </PERSON>. But <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> said the new requirements also will be expensive with expected initial capital costs at about $ 3 billion and operational costs of about $ 500 million a year. The agency said the additional costs are expected to be passed onto customers, but the increase in household water bills is likely to vary widely depending on the size of the public water system and whether the system already has some filtration equipment. According to <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> estimates, in rural areas where water systems serve fewer than 500 customers and where no filtration is now used, household water bills could increase from $ 30 to $ 50 a month. In urban areas with more customers to bear the cost, the increase is likely to be about $ 6 a month, perhaps much less if some filtration equipment already is being used. About one-third of the nearly 10,000 water systems subject to the tighter requirements currently have no filtration system, the agency said. Those systems serve more than 21 million people, including residents of major cities such as <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Newark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>. Some other cities not filtering their drinking water are <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Syracuse </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Utica </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Scranton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Wilkes-Barre </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Greenville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> S.C. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Reno </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sparks </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Nev. </LOCATION>; <LOCATION> Tacoma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>. Local authorities have four years in which to install new equipment, said <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryan </PERSON>
</TEXT>
