<HEAD>Rare Corporate Manslaughter Charge Over Ferry Sinking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A court issued manslaughter summonses Thursday for a shipping company, three of its former directors and four seamen over the 1987 <LOCATION> Zeebrugge </LOCATION> ferry disaster in which 193 people died. A corporate manslaughter conviction can carry an unlimited fine, while the seven men face a maximum sentence of life imprisonment. The decision to prosecute P and O European Ferries was believed by experts to be unprecedented. It capped more than two years of court and police proceedings, a public inquiry that blamed the ship owners, and an inquest that returned a verdict of unlawful killing. There was no immediate comment from the ferry company or the men summoned. The <ORGANIZATION> Herald </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Free </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprise </ORGANIZATION>, a car-and-passenger ferry, capsized outside the Belgian port of <LOCATION> Zeebrugge </LOCATION> in March 1987. Lawyers have disclosed that about two-thirds of the families affected by the disaster have accepted a compensation package from P and O, from $ 7,700 to the six-figure range, depending on the family's circumstances and the contribution the victim made to the family's income. Published reports have estimated the final payout will be at least $ 6 million and as much as $ 23 million. An unidentified family that lost its breadwinner father was granted $ 294,000 in a test case compensation settlement in the High Court in January 1988. Facing prosecution are the ship's captain, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewry </PERSON>; First Officer <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Sabel </PERSON>; Senior Master <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirby </PERSON>, and <PERSON> Boatswain </PERSON> <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON>. Also summoned were <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Develine </PERSON>, <PERSON> Wallace </PERSON> <PERSON> Ayres </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Alcindore </PERSON>, directors of owner <ORGANIZATION> Townsend </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Car </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ferries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, which is now called P and <ORGANIZATION> O </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ferries </ORGANIZATION>. The corporate manslaughter charge is against P and <ORGANIZATION> O </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ferries </ORGANIZATION>. The men summoned must appear before magistrates Aug. 1. The trial is expected to begin next year. `` It's a pretty untested part of the law,'' said a spokeswoman for the Crown Prosecution Service, which obtained the summonses at <ORGANIZATION> Bow </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Magistrates </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>. The spokeswoman, commenting on condition of anonymity, said that except for a couple of cases in the 1920s, the state had never brought a charge of this sort against a company. `` It's a complicated question because it is absolutely unprecedented for this sort of case to go ahead,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Zander </PERSON>, professor of law at the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Maurice </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Rohan </PERSON>, head of an association of families of the disaster victims, welcomed the move, as did the opposition <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s transport spokesman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Prescott </PERSON>. `` It makes clear to all directors of companies that they have corporate responsibility to see that the highest levels of safety pertain in their areas of operation and they do n't just blame the workers,'' he said. The ship with an estimated 543 people aboard capsized because its bow doors were open, letting in water that destabilized it, a public inquiry concluded. <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON>, who allegedly left the doors open, was directly blamed, while <PERSON> Lewry </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sabel </PERSON> were accused of serious negligence. Of <ORGANIZATION> Townsend </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Car </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ferries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, the inquiry report said: `` From top to bottom, the body corporate was affected by the disease of sloppiness,'' and guilt rested with `` all concerned in management.'' An inquest jury returned a verdict of unlawful killing, and police conducted a lengthy investigation. Last year, in an action brought by the families, a court ruled that companies could be prosecuted for manslaughter.
