<HEAD>EDS: LEADS throughout with details, background. CORRECTS that cease-fire
to begin at midnight Friday. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NTOTO WAKU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KINSHASA, Zaire (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> dos </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON> of Marxist <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and rebel leader <PERSON> Jonas </PERSON> <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> shook hands Thursday and agreed to end 14 years of civil war, reports said. The accord came at the end of an African summit on <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> attended by 14 African heads of state. It provides for a cease-fire in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> to start at midnight Friday -LRB- 7 p.m. Friday EDT -RRB-, according to Zairian officials quoted by the <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> news agency Agence France-Presse. The meeting between <PERSON> dos </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON> and <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> was their first since the civil war began in 1975. <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> heads the U.S.-backed <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> for the Total Independence of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, known as <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION>. The reconciliation follows a U.S.-brokered regional peace accord signed in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> in December under which <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> agreed to grant independence to <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> and halt aid to <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON>'s rebels in exchange for the withdrawal of 50,000 Cuban troops backing <PERSON> dos </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON>' government. <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> signed the accord. The rebels are not party to the agreement. Thursday's peace announcement was called the Declaration of <LOCATION> Gbadolite </LOCATION>, after the town in northern <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION> where the summit was held. It is the hometown of President <PERSON> Mobutu </PERSON> Sese Soko of <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION> and lies 700 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Kinshasa </L