GANIZATION>. That agreement broke a deadlock and brought <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s government to the conference table. <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> agreed in May he would not demand a role in any transitional government on condition democratic elections are held within two years. Major obstacles included <PERSON> dos </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON>' insistence on maintaining one-party rule while offering the rebels some positions in his administration. The government offered rebels an amnesty and clemency, but the guerrillas replied that the offer suggested their war was criminal and so was unacceptable. <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON> garners most of his support from the rural southern area toward <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> _ the <LOCATION> Ovimbundu </LOCATION> <LOCATION> tribe </LOCATION>, the biggest in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, and the Ovambo. <PERSON> Dos </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON>' power base is around northern <LOCATION> Luanda </LOCATION>, but his followers are more diverse, coming from several smaller tribes. <PERSON> Dos </PERSON> <PERSON> Santos </PERSON> arrived ready to reconcile. Before leaving <LOCATION> Luanda </LOCATION> earlier Thursday, he commuted death sentences of 50 rebels condemned for high treason and terrorism between 1981-87, <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>'s official <ORGANIZATION> ANGOP </ORGANIZATION> news agency reported. On Wednesday, it said, the government released 700 rebel prisoners who accepted an amnesty. <PERSON> Savimbi </PERSON>'s guerrillas, armed by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, have been fighting to share power with <LOCATION> Luanda </LOCATION>'s Cuban-backed government since Angolan independence. <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> continues to arm the rebels and may have encouraged the rebels to negotiate. <PERSON> Herman </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, assistant secretary of state for <LOCATION> African </LOCATION> affairs, said from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> on Thursday that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` helped develop'' the <LOCATION> Zaire </LOCATION> summit. `` We may have a breakthrough,'' <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> forecast earlier Thursday. <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> is twice the size of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, with 481,354 square miles, but has only 8 million people. Most of them live in tribal villages and rural areas. Nearly all the <LOCATION> Portuguese </LOCATION> fled in 1975, leaving <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> more than 90 percent illiterate and badly in need of capital and skilled workers. Oil fields in the Angolan enclave of <LOCATION> Cabinda </LOCATION> supply more than 90 percent of the nation's export earnings. <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> also has diamonds, minerals and rich agricultural land, but the civil war has seriously disrupted the economy.
