<HEAD>Plane Crashes in Andes with 60 Aboard. No Survivors</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with 60 on board, details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HUANCAYO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A plane carrying 60 people slammed into a mountain in the Andes, reportedly splitting in half, and all aboard were killed, the air force said Thursday. The aircraft, an air force plane, crashed near the town of <LOCATION> Tarma </LOCATION> 100 miles east of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION> Wednesday, according to a communique. Earlier Thursday, Gen. <PERSON> Edgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Sullca </PERSON> <PERSON> Flores </PERSON>, police chief of <LOCATION> Huancayo </LOCATION> city in the central highlands, said the plane was carrying 42 people, including crew and passengers. Peasants from <LOCATION> Uyubamba </LOCATION> village said they watched the aircraft break into two from the eastern mountain slopes, <PERSON> Flores </PERSON> said. The communique said 42 of the victims had been identified. An air force spokesman said no foreigners were among the passengers. The air force did not say how many of the dead were civilians and how many were military personnel. The communique did not indicate what might have caused the crash. The aircraft, a Canadian-made <ORGANIZATION> Buffalo </ORGANIZATION> bimotor cargo plane converted to passenger service, left the jungle town of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ramon </LOCATION>, 126 miles northeast of <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>. The air force provides passenger service on its planes to remote towns in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>'s eastern <LOCATION> Amazon </LOCATION> jungle because the routes are not profitable for civilian airlines. Also Wednesday, an Aeroperu jetliner made an emergency landing at <LOCATION> Lima </LOCATION>'s international airport on a flight from <LOCATION> Cuzco </LOCATION>. Airport officials said the landing gear on the plane, a DC-8, would not come down. The aircraft circled the airport for more than an hour, consuming its remaining fuel to reduce the chances of fire during the emergency landing. The aircraft finally was able to land without any of the 148 passengers suffering injuries. Aeroperu is a government-owned airline. Six civilian and military planes have crashed in <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> in the past two years. Critics blame most accidents on poor maintenance because of a shortage of spare parts. <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION> is suffering its worst recession in history, weighed down by annual inflation of more than 5,000 percent.
