<HEAD>Four Defendants Receive Maximum Sentences</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARILYNN WHEELER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OREGON CITY, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Four workers in a disciplinary program for ghetto children received maximum 20-year sentences Thursday for beating their leader's 8-year-old daughter to death. <ORGANIZATION> Ecclesia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Athletic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Eldridge </PERSON> <PERSON> Broussard </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, making his first appearance in court during the trial, pleaded unsuccessfully for the release of the four pending an appeal. <PERSON> Willie </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Chambers </PERSON>, 35, of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Diego </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brinson </PERSON>, 31, <PERSON> Frederick </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Doolittle </PERSON>, 28, and <PERSON> Constance </PERSON> <PERSON> Z. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, 38, all of <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>, were convicted of first-degree manslaughter May 12 in the death of <PERSON> Dayna </PERSON> <PERSON> Broussard </PERSON>. <PERSON> Dayna </PERSON> endured hundreds of blows for stealing food from another child Oct. 13, according to testimony. Several children forced to witness the discipline session testified that <PERSON> Dayna </PERSON> was slammed against a wall, kicked, tripped, slapped, dropped on the floor, shoved, bitten, spit upon and hung out a window. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, who beat five other Ecclesia children with an electrical cord, was convicted June 5 of five counts each of second-degree assault and first-degree criminal mistreatment. <LOCATION> Clackamas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Circuit Judge <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> sentenced <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> to 10 years in prison, to be served after the manslaughter sentence, on that conviction. She will be eligible for parole in seven years. Defense lawyers asked that their clients receive light sentences since none had criminal records. But prosecutor <PERSON> Alfred </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> French </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> urged the maximum penalty for all four. Chambers, who got the stiffest penalty of the four, will be eligible for parole in 10 years. The 50 or more blows dealt by Chambers were mainly to blame for the girl's death, <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> said. Chambers described <PERSON> Dayna </PERSON> during the trial as `` a strong-willed, strong-bodied world-class athlete,'' <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> recalled. `` But she was not yet a world-class athlete. She was an 8-year-old girl.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was convicted of striking and biting <PERSON> Dayna </PERSON>. `` It took more guts for <PERSON> Dayna </PERSON> <PERSON> Broussard </PERSON> to bite you in the leg than for a prisoner of war to spit in the face of her captors,'' <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> told her. <PERSON> Brinson </PERSON> and <PERSON> Doolittle </PERSON>, who held the girl down, will each have to serve 40 months before being eligible for parole. `` No human being could have participated without asking, ` Has n't this gone far enough?' <PERSON> Lowe </PERSON> said of the two. Defense attorney <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Thom </PERSON> said the sentences will be appealed. <PERSON> Broussard </PERSON>, who testified under a 1987 law that allows crime victims or their families to speak at sentencing, broke down once during his rambling, 20-minute testimony. `` I'm walking a tightrope,'' he explained to the court. `` When I do n't show any emotion, I'm inhuman,'' <PERSON> Broussard </PERSON> said. `` -LRB- When I do express my feelings -RRB-, people think I'm faking. I would like to assure you my daughter's loss is serious to me.'' He declined to comment after the sentencing. <PERSON> Broussard </PERSON>, 35, formed Ecclesia in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>' tough <LOCATION> Watts </LOCATION> area to steer ghetto children away from drugs and crime and toward rigorous athletic training. He criticized the news media Thursday for calling his organization a cult, and portraying him as `` a madman or someone who does n't have any sense.'' <PERSON> Broussard </PERSON> was in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> at the time of the beating at a farmhouse east of <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>. He has denied all along that <PERSON> Dayna </PERSON> was beaten, saying that children in the group were spanked as part of the group's strict disciplinary policy. Fifty-three children 6 weeks to 16 years old were taken into state protective custody after <PERSON> Dayna </PERSON>'s death. They are living with foster parents or with relatives.
