<HEAD>Solidarity Citizens Committee To Focus on Building Union</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RETRANMITTING a0803 to fix slug to distinguish from a0704, AM-Poland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Solidarity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, which ran the union's campaign for the new parliament, decided Thursday not to disband now that elections are over, patching a dispute that threated to split the opposition. Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> and the union's <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Executive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> advocated closing the local <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> so that activists nationwide could concentrate on rebuilding the Solidarity trade union itself. But activists strongly disagreed, and after a daylong debtate passed two vaguely worded resolutions that Solidarity national spokesman <PERSON> Janusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Onyszkiewicz </PERSON> said meant local groups could continue to exist for now. About 120 members of the national <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> _ set up in December by <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> to advise the union on political, social and economic issues _ gathered in a <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> auditorium for the debate. During the debate, <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> defended a weekend resolution by the union's <ORGANIZATION> Executive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to concentrate efforts on rebuilding the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc's first independent trade union, which regained legal status April 17. Union organizing took a back seat during the election campaign. But the final resolution thanked the local Citizens Committees, which helped Solidarity to its overwhelming election victory, and said they should help prepare for free municipal elections, a Solidarity goal. The executive's resolution to dissolve the local committees `` should not be treated as something that should be implemented immediately,'' <PERSON> Onyszkiewicz </PERSON> said. `` Today's resolution ... says one should approach their transformation with flexibility,'' he said. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> is of the opinion that the main task at the present moment is expanding and strengthening the Solidarity trade union and Farmers Solidarity as guarantors of democratic reforms in our country,'' it said. A 14-member commission was appointed to present proposals on the future of the national <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> by Sept. 10. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> appeared concerned the continued existence of the committees would drain strength from rebuilding the union. `` Today if we get divided into two ... we weaken the most important stream and the most important stream today is the broad stream of working people,'' he said. A top adviser to <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> who opposed disbanding the committees tried to downplay conflict. `` First of all we want to say in the current situation that we maintain unity, that we are able to maintain it and that there is no conflict between the <ORGANIZATION> Citizens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> and the bodies of the union,'' said <PERSON> Bronislaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Geremek </PERSON>. The weekend decision was greeted with anger from members of the local committees, flush with their electoral triumph, which saw Solidarity win 99 of of 100 seats in the freely contested <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> in June 4 and June 18 elections. Solidarity also won all seats available to it in the lower house, the Sejm. Critics said the decision was to prevent the committees in each of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s 49 provinces from becoming parallel, possibly rival organizations to Solidarity. The dispute reflected contradictions within Solidarity over whether it is ultimately a trade union or a political movement and whether it will be led by workers or intellectuals. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> has said Solidarity should be mainly a union, with politics eventually shifted to newly emerging political groups. But Solidarity nevertheless has a broad following among non-workers _ students, intellectuals and professionals _ who are more interested in pressing communist authorities for democratic political changes.
</TEXT>
