<HEAD>Senate Approves Natural Gas Bill</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Thursday night approved a compromise bill to remove the remaining wellhead price controls from natural gas. The <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> compromise was cleared in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> by a voice vote. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> must take final action on the bill before it can be sent to President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who is expected to sign it. The legislation is designed to remove all federal price controls on natural gas by Jan. 1, 1993. It is not expected to affect retail prices much because most gas under controls already is selling below the official ceilings. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s action came two days after <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> negotiators agreed that gas from wells drilled after the date of enactment of the bil would be deregulated on May 15, 1991. All other gas not already decontrolled would be freed from the federal ceilings when sales contracts are renegotiated or Jan. 1, 1993, whichever comes first. About two-thirds of the nation's natural gas was freed from controls in 1978.
