<HEAD>Leader Defends China's Version Of Crackdown, Criticizes Hungarian
Reform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A leader of <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, one of the most rigid in the Soviet bloc, on Thursday defended <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s official version of the crackdown on pro-democracy activists <PERSON> Joachim </PERSON> <PERSON> Herrmann </PERSON>, a member of the party's policy-making Politburo, also denounced democratic reform in <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION> and backed the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Wall. <PERSON> Herrmann </PERSON>, who also serves as secretary of the party's <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, made his comments in a Politburo report he read to a <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> meeting on foreign policy. Speaking about the violent suppression of student demonstrators in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Herrmann </PERSON> said <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> has published all official Chinese statements with the purpose of denying `` Western horror stories'' and to present `` objective information.'' Chinese witnesses and Western intelligence sources say the death toll in the June 3-4 crackdown may have been as high as 3,000. The Chinese government's most recent report says 100 soldiers and 100 civilians died. Most East Germans are able to watch West German television. <PERSON> Herrmann </PERSON>, whose speech was distributed by the government-run news agency <ORGANIZATION> ADN </ORGANIZATION>, said the `` peaceful student demonstrations'' in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> were intended to be used for a `` counter-revolutionary overthrow of people's power in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>.'' The Politburo makes all key decisions in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and its report expresses the views of the country's aging leaders, led by <PERSON> Erich </PERSON> <PERSON> Honecker </P