<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Americans have learned to use debt like never before, but it does n't necessarily follow that they are creating an economic problem in doing so. That assumption _ that consumer debt is dangerously high _ is often made after a casual glance at lending figures that, among other things, show the debt-to-income ratio at sky-high levels compared to a few years ago. A decade ago, for example, analysts worried when the ratio reached 15.5, meaning that consumer debt was 15.5 percent of disposable income. When it topped 16 percent a few years later they warned that a recession was due. True to the forecast, the economy fell into the brief recession of 1980, and then into a much deeper recession that lasted from July 1981 to November 1982. That brought the ratio back under 15. Now, and for the past several years, the ratio is back over 15 _ and 16 and 17 and 18, numbers that had never been seen before and which were n't even foreseen a decade ago. Theories abound: Lenders have lowered their standards, deregulation has made lenders more aggressive in seeking customers, prices have risen faster than many incomes, and stable employment has created a sense of security. Some critics believe that the sense of security from stable jobs is a false one. Credit evaluation systems, they point out, rarely deal explicitly with the question of how long employment might last. They judge by the past, not future. Other observers, however, suggest the explanation is in the credit figures themselves rather than in consumer behavior. What seems to be a problem of too much borrowing, they say, may be statistical rather than economic. Here are some numbers to digest: _ Revolving credit accounts for about 30 percent of consumer installment credit, rising from $ 14 billion in 1975 to $ 185 billion now, a gain of 1,200 percent _ Total installment credit grew from $ 160 billion in 1975 to $ 666 billion over the same period _ Much of this credit is in the form of money owed to retailers But a growing amount of it is in bank credit card balances. In 10 years, the latter have risen from less than 50 percent of revolving credit to almost two-thirds. However, the story told by these figures, provided by economist <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunkelberg </PERSON>, is not what it appears to be. <PERSON> Dunkelberg </PERSON>, dean of <ORGANIZATION> Temple </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>, calls attention to a fact often overlooked, that more than half these bank balances _ 25 percent for retail cards _ are repaid each month at no interest. In effect, these balances _ which keep the ratios at record high levels _ are not `` debt'' in the minds of consumers, but convenient substitutes for the use of cash and checks in making transactions. <PERSON> Dunkelberg </PERSON> estimates, conservatively he says, that $ 75 billion of these cash and check substitute balances are not debt in the traditional sense. Remove them, he says, and the debt-to-income ratio drops all the way down to 16.5. While that percentage is nearly three points lower than the latest official figures, it still appears high. In fact, it is about as high as the rate that prevailed just before the 1981-1982 recession. Still, <PERSON> Dunkelberg </PERSON> suggests, the ratio might not have the same significance now as it had back then. Several lending and borrowing changes tend to put a new and different interpretation on the figures. Important among these changes is a sharp rise in the share of consumer credit accounted for by consumers in the top 20 percent of the income tables, many of whom have sufficient assets to support debt. The behavior of these upper-income folks may have changed, <PERSON> Dunkelberg </PERSON> suggests, because of such things as tax-deductible, second mortgage lines of credit and the proliferation of credit cards. As he analyzes the scene, the high debt-to-income ratio may not be evidence of individuals taking on greater risk as much as it is a sign that more people are using debt, for convenience or other reasons.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thursday, June 22</NOTE>
</DOC>
