<FIRST>a a AM-ReligionToday Adv23   06-22 0817</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Religion Today, Adv 23,0846</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv23</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Fri AMs,June 23, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Sexual Harassment Troubles Churches As Women Clergy Increase</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Laserphoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Shocked at its extent, churches are grappling with a newly recognized problem in their own domain _ sexual harassment of women, particularly female clergy. Concern about it has risen as increasing numbers of women have entered the ordained ministry, traditionally a profession of males and largely limited to them until modern times. The trouble, however, has surfaced among lay women as well as clergywomen. It has turned up in `` every setting of the church,'' declared the board of directors of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Christ </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Coordinating </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Women </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> in </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION>, after reviewing reports about it. One of the center's research projects found that of 138 women clergy surveyed, 45 percent of them said they had been sexually harassed in the workplace, that is, in church precincts. `` It's a startling figure,'' said <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Breitling </PERSON> of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION>, the center's executive director. `` The harassment was not identified by type, but no matter how you define it, that's an inordinately high number. `` We were shocked.'' However, there has been little or no awareness of the problem until recently, she said, but it now is drawing increased attention in major Protestant denominations, most of which now ordain women. `` It was very, very hidden and people did not talk about it, but now they're beginning to talk about it in a straightforward way, and seek ways to deal with it,'' she said in a telephone interview. Especially in church, `` you expect to be treated with respect and dignity,'' she said. For church colleagues `` to intimidate, take advantage, harass or molest is just unconscionable. `` Unfortunately, those kind of things are happening. Harassment is occuring even in the church. The church needs to speak to that problem in its own life, just as it speaks to things in the culture at large.'' Among lay women, the center's survey found 20 percent of them reported incidents of sexual harassment within the church, less than half the proportion of women clergy doing so. The 1.7-million-member <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> through its antecedant Congregationalism -LRB- merged in 1957 with the <ORGANIZATION> Evangelical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reformed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- pioneered women's ordination, beginning in the l850's. Sixteen percent of the denomination's 10,000 clergy are women. Other Protestant bodies, including Presbyterians, Lutherans, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodists </ORGANIZATION>, Episcopalians and others, have begun ordaining women only since the 1950's. More than 20,000 women now are among <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> clergy. Sexual harassment has aroused concern in several denominations. The Presbyterian Church -LRB- <LOCATION> USA </LOCATION> -RRB- last week called for development of a church-wide policy on sexual misbehavior in the church household. In most denominations, `` all of us are very much concerned about the issue,'' said <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Dubois </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ky. </LOCATION>, Presbyterian specialist on women in church employment. A special study about it is under way in the Northeast. `` It's no respecter of denominations,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Breitling </PERSON> said. `` It's a very common experience. It's also one we've avoided dealing with. But the issue is coming to the fore in most every denomination.'' The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> at its l986 governing conference said sexual harassment has been documented in congregations, agencies, seminaries and other institutions. One limited survey found one in eight <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodist </ORGANIZATION> women reported being sexually harassed in church environs. The denomination called for grievance procedures for victims and penalties for offenders. It also launched a denomination-wide study on the extent of church sexual harassment. The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>'s women's center proposes a resolution for the denomination's General Synod June 29-July 4, saying women volunteers, seminarians, pastors and lay employees report `` varied experiences of sexual harassment.'' That is a `` disappointing fact in an institution that is based on values of equality and respect for all persons,'' the measure says. It calls for gathering of more data and developing guidelines about the matter. The resolution identifies two types of sexual harassment, one being the `` imposition of unwelcome sexual activity, suggestion or behavior in a relationship of unequal power.'' That refers to such situations as between pastor and associate minister or intern, or between clergywomen and members of the church board of trustees when superiors manipulate women into demoralizing affairs. A second type of harassment cited is the creation of a `` hostile, intimidating atmosphere in the workplace'' that offends or disturbs women personnel, even if there is `` no direct damage to victims.'' `` Even if it's seemingly harmless inuendo, it can be offensive and create an unpleasant work situation,'' Ms. <PERSON> Breitling </PERSON> said. `` There are a lot of variations and complex relationship questions.'' While open, friendly hugs or pats between mutually respecting associates are not considered in the harassment category, she said objectionable activity generally is distinguishable by victims. As one woman put it, `` I've been hugged, and I've been ` groped' and I know the difference.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, June 23</NOTE>
