<HEAD>$adv26</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday June 26, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>NASA Will Use Jet To Simulate Shuttle Landings On A Flat Tire</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> plans to help crews prepare for flat tires and other problems landing the space shuttle by having an astronaut fly an armor-plated aircraft to test shuttle landing gear. During next year's tests, the Convair CV-990 jet will touch down on its own landing gear at 225 mph, then lower shuttle landing gear mounted between its main tires, said <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lovato </PERSON> at <ORGANIZATION> Edwards </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Base </ORGANIZATION>. `` We intend to do a whole series of tests and use different pressures in the shuttle tire, taking the pressure down to where we actually destroy the tire,'' <PERSON> Lovato </PERSON> said. Because the Convair's landing gear will support the plane, there is no danger to veteran shuttle astronaut <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Fullerton </PERSON>, who will fly it, she added The test landings will be conducted on paved and dry lakebed runways at <LOCATION> Edwards </LOCATION>, on paved runways at Kennedy Space Center, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, and on unpaved landing strips at White Sands Space Harbor, N.M. The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement that the tests `` will give engineers information on what to expect should an orbiter experience a flat tire or other anomalies on landing, and will provide data to help in developing crew procedures for various landing conditions and situations.'' The agency required all space shuttles to land at Edwards since April 1985, when Discovery blew a tire and sustained brake damage landing on a paved runway at Kennedy Space Center. The shuttle swerved down the runway, but was never out of control and the astronauts emerged safely. Landing gear and brakes have been modified, and <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> continues to test them during shuttle landings at <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>. To prepare the CV-990 for the 1990 test landings, `` we'll armor plate the belly of the airplane so that if there's debris kicked up, it wo n't damage the bottom of the aircraft,'' <PERSON> Lovato </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> will test brakes and nose gear steering, along with the main and nose landing gear, wheel and tire assemblies.
</TEXT>
