<SECOND>PM-GATT-World Trade,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Rejects Criticism of Trade Policy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLARE NULLIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official has rejected criticism from negotiators in world trade talks that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy undermined efforts to liberalize international trade. Delegates at a special meeting of the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade condemned provisions in the 1988 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade act which call for penalties against countries deemed to be especially protectionist. <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunkel </PERSON>, director-general of the 96-nation organization, issued an appeal Wednesday that governments should not take action outside <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION>'s international trade rules as unilateral measures had been tried before and failed, the spokesman said. Deputy <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Trade Representative <PERSON> Rufus </PERSON> <PERSON> Yerxa </PERSON> told the special closed session of the <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> council that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` would not apologize for actions taken in trying to pursue its trade objectives,'' and said the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration was committed to the current four-year round of global trade-freeing talks, according to a partial text of his speech released to journalists. But <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> ambassador <PERSON> Tran </PERSON> <PERSON> Van-Thinh </PERSON> warned in the closed meeting of the possible `` sinking of the <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> because of an error of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> judgment,'' a <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said. Last month the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> administration singled out <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> for priority action under the so-called 301 section of its trade act because of alleged serious violations against fair trade. The three countries face 100 percent tariffs on selected exports to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> if they do not remove the offending barriers to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goods within 18 months. <PERSON> Yerxa </PERSON> told the meeting Wednesday that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> had taken no action under the new procedure other than `` to identify trade liberalizing priorities'' in areas which are `` significant barriers to world trade.'' Arguing that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> was `` remarkably open'' in the face of a huge trade deficit, he said that 60 percent of all Third World exports of manufactured goods go to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, twice as many as the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> and five times as many as <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> received. <LOCATION> Brazilian </LOCATION> ambassador <PERSON> Rubens </PERSON> <PERSON> Ricupero </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> action `` undermines and puts in jeopardy the whole <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Round </LOCATION>,'' and `` has already wasted and ruined the precious capital of goodwill'' built up during the talks. Indian representative <PERSON> Bal </PERSON> <PERSON> Krishan </PERSON> <PERSON> Zutshi </PERSON> said the implementation of the 301 provisions would `` emasculate the multilateral trading system.'' Japanese ambassador <PERSON> Joshio </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatano </PERSON> cited <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> disregard of the system within the <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> for settling trade disputes. `` To be judge, jury and executioner at the same time is not acceptable,'' he told the meeting. Copies of the texts from the Brazilian, Japanese and Indian were made available to journalists. The <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said that <PERSON> Dunkel </PERSON> told the meeting that <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> had been established in 1948 after `` unilateralism and bilateralism had been tried and failed.'' <PERSON> Dunkel </PERSON> told the meeting if the drafters of the founding agreement were still alive, `` they would have asked in despair, do world economic relations have to go through the same cycle again? Can the present generation of trade policy makers not learn from the experiences of a previous one?'' the spokesman said.
