<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Heller </PERSON>, citing financial hardships in living on his $ 82,500-a-year government salary, says he will resign as one of the seven members of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. An expert in international economics, <PERSON> Heller </PERSON> said Wednesday he would return to <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> to become an executive vice president of <ORGANIZATION> Visa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION>, the giant credit card company. In a meeting with reporters, he refused to disclose his exact salary at <ORGANIZATION> Visa </ORGANIZATION>, saying only that it would be a `` pretty sizable'' increase that would represent a multiple of his government pay. <PERSON> Heller </PERSON> specifically cited <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' rejection earlier this year of a proposed federal pay raise as one factor in his decision to leave. Under the proposal, which would have boosted congressional salaries as well as those of top officials, the pay of a <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> governor would have risen to $ 125,000. His resignation will give President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> his first opportunity to appoint someone to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>. The other six members, including Chairman <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Greenspan </PERSON>, were appointed by former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. Economists said it was unlikely <PERSON> Heller </PERSON>'s surprise departure would affect policy at the central bank. <PERSON> Heller </PERSON> generally espoused supply-side monetary views emphasizing economic growth, appearing at times to be at odds with the tough anti-inflation leanings of former Chairman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Volcker </PERSON>