<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> attorney says the carrier's move to end its contract with striking pilots and cut wages is a matter of economics, but the pilots union says it reflects management's anti-labor attitude `` The albatross around <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s neck is not labor costs, but an inept and rapacious management,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pilots </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement late Wednesday. Eastern on Wednesday asked the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bankruptcy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to terminate the contract its pilots had been working under before the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union in March led a massive work stoppage that crippled the airline. The Miami-based carrier also is seeking approval for a permanent increase in the number of hours a pilot may work each month and about $ 50 million in temporary wage and benefit concessions. `` This is not a union-busting tactic,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>. `` This is an economic problem.'' Eastern officials said the new conditions are supported by pilots who have continued to fly during the strike and are similar to cuts taken by management and other non-union employees during the 3-month-old strike. The pilots union said <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s actions came as no surprise. <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>. Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> `` is following basically the same pattern of harsh treatment for workers that he established when he took <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> into bankruptcy and abrogated its labor contracts there in 1983,'' <ORGANIZATION> ALPA </ORGANIZATION>'s statement said <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> abrogated union contracts with employees of <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>, like <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> a <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary, after he put <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> into bankruptcy protection. The carrier, based in <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, is now non-union. But the pilots union said Wednesday it expects <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> to have a `` much more difficult time'' doing the same with <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> because <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> tightened the bankruptcy laws after the Continental episode to make it harder for companies to cancel contracts through bankruptcy reorganization. Now a company must show it is negotiating in good faith. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> sought termination of the pilots' contract, which expired a year ago, in order to move ahead with rebuilding plans because the union had balked at negotiating a new contract. Eastern had about 3,600 pilots before the strike, but plans to rebuild into a smaller carrier with about 1,700 pilots. Under Section 1113 of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Bankruptcy Code, the court has 14 to 21 days to schedule a hearing and 30 days to rule on <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s request Eastern is seeking to cut the pilots' pay by 10 percent for six months, 5 percent for the next six months and to delay vacations until next year. Wage and pension-plan concessions would be restored by half on Jan. 31, 1990, and in full by August 1990. The airline also is asking for permanent work rule changes. The airline wants to be able to schedule pilots to fly 68 hours a month in 1990 and 60 hours a month thereafter, compared with the pre-strike 46 hours. Federal regulations allow a pilot to fly an average of 85 hours a month, with a maximum of 100 hours. The Machinists went on strike March 4 after federal mediation failed. The pilots' contract is still open to negotiation and normally would have to go through federal mediation, but <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said the airline can seek to end the contract because the company is in Chapter 11.
