<HEAD>Director's Defeat May Not Signal End of UAW Dissident Movement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Convention to convene at 3 p.m. EDT. PMs lead unlikely.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The strongest <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> dissident movement in 40 years has lost a seat on the union's executive board, but the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION>'s leadership may be hearing more from the New Directions group <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> of <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> was defeated for re-election Wednesday as director of <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Region </ORGANIZATION> 5 in eight south-central states, losing to <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyse </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> area. <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> and New Directions have criticized <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> for allegedly stifling dissent within the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> and losing sight of the 1 million-member union's roots by making to cooperative labor agreements with automakers. <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> and members of his <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caucus </ORGANIZATION> have denied the charges. But the New Directions effort has gained widespread rank-and-file support and is the most serious challenge to the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION>'s leadership since the mid-1940s, when <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Reuther </PERSON> was solidifying control of the then-fledgling union After the regional director election, one <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Directions </ORGANIZATION> member asked <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> to set aside the entire vote and hold another election within two months. That brought catcalls and mild obscenities from <PERSON> Wyse </PERSON> supporters. <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> ruled the motion out of order. On his way out of the caucus, <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Reuther </PERSON>, brother of <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Reuther </PERSON> and a backer of <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON>'s efforts, said a similar motion could be brought before the convention today. <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> had little to say immediately after the loss, other than that he had not decided about whether he would take the election challenge to court. <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON> was chosen director of Region 5 in a federally supervised election Sept. 1, 1988, after he challenged an earlier election in court. He lost that contest by an extremely narrow margin. <PERSON> Wyse </PERSON>, appointed by <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> as an assistant director in Region 5 three years ago, said after his election that union members `` saw through the New Directions movement. They saw they had questions but no answers. `` I think it's the beginning of the end for the New Directions movement,'' he said. <PERSON> Wyse </PERSON> said he would try to reconcile the two camps in his huge region. But, he added: `` It will take a while. There are some scars out there that need to be healed.'' That was evident in the packed hotel room where the caucus was held. Both sides wore jackets with their candidates' names on the back _ <PERSON> Tucker </PERSON>'s forces in blue and <PERSON> Wyse </PERSON>'s in white. Earlier Wednesday, the <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caucus </ORGANIZATION>'s slate of top union officers was elected to three-year terms without opposition. <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> won his third term as the union's president. Incumbent Secretary-Treasurer <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Casstevens </PERSON> was elected to a full term after succeeding the late <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Majerus </PERSON>, who died Jan. 14, 1988. Delegates also elected four vice presidents _ two incumbents and two to succeed the retiring <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Ephlin </PERSON> and <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> will assign responsibilities to his new vice presidents. It's expected that <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Yokich </PERSON> will move from the union's <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to head the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, succeeding <PERSON> Ephlin </PERSON>; newly elected vice president <PERSON> Ernie </PERSON> <PERSON> Lofton </PERSON> will succeed <PERSON> Yokich </PERSON>; and <PERSON> Stan </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON>, also elected as vice president Wednesday, will follow <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> as director of the <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. Vice President <PERSON> Odessa </PERSON> <PERSON> Kommer </PERSON>, the union's most senior vice president having been elected first in 1974, probably will keep many of her responsibilities, including oversight of the union's relations with a number of automotive supplier companies
