<HEAD>Paramount, Time Trade Punches in Buyout Battle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has gone to court to block <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s proposed $ 14 billion buyout of <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc </ORGANIZATION>. But a cable operator that is 82 percent-owned by <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> said <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> is running into opposition from local officials over its own plans to acquire the operator's cable franchises in connection with a hostile $ 10.7 billion bid for Time. Meanwhile, <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> asked the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> to investigate Time's bid for <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> on the ground that the companies may have violated exchange rules. The exchange said it would comply with the request. Those were among the developments Wednesday in what is shaping up as a fiercely contested takeover battle that could produce one of the world's largest communications companies no matter who wins. In composite trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> rose $ 4.75 a share to $ 157.25 on Wednesday after losing $ 19 in the previous three sessions. <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> fell $ 1 a share to $ 58.50 while <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> lost 12 -LCB- cents a share to $ 59.25. Paramount filed a 49-page amendment to an earlier suit in <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chancery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday in which it said Time acted improperly in rejecting <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s buyout offer and launching its own takeover bid for <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>. The complaint said the offer for <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> `` amounts to a multibillion dollar abuse of Time's stockholders for the purpose of protecting the secure and prosperous future of Time and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> management.'' Paramount also asked that the court nullify results of the upcoming election of four Time board members. Time's chairman and chief executive, <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Munro </PERSON>, and its president, <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, are nominees. Paramount said the pending election is a sham because no opposing candidates have been nominated. In response to the amended complaint, <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement that <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s allegations were without merit. Time said it would `` respond to the complaint in the proper forum _ <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chancery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> _ and demonstrate clearly its position and the merits of its case.'' In its amendment to the suit, <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> also claimed that a stock swap recently completed between Time and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> violated <ORGANIZATION> NYSE </ORGANIZATION> rules that require shareholder approval for such a transaction. If the <ORGANIZATION> Big </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> finds that Time or <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> had violated its rules, it could bar the merged company from trading its shares on the exchange. A hearing on <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s suit is set for July 11. Paramount, an entertainment and publishing concern, launched a $ 175 a share tender offer for <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION>'s stock on June 6, only 2 -LCB- weeks before Time and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> shareholders originally were to vote on a merger of the companies. Time, a leading magazine and book publisher and cable programmer and operator, rejected <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s offer Friday, saying it was inadequate and highly conditional and that securing regulatory approvals for cable system transfers alone would take a year or more. Time also said it had revised its merger agreement with <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> to provide a $ 70-a-share buyout of the movie, record and cable concern. While shareholder approval was needed for the original merger, <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION>'s shareholders are not being asked to vote on the acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION>'s stock. Meanwhile, the cable operator <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday local opposition is growing to <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s plans for acquiring cable franchises associated with Time. <ORGANIZATION> ATC </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, has said <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s acquisition of Time is illegal because the change in control would place <ORGANIZATION> ATC </ORGANIZATION> in violation of many of its cable franchise agreements. It said officials from the states of <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> and 16 cities including <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION> have complained to federal officials that <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION>'s takeover plan abrogates the local right of prior approval for cable franchise ownership in their areas. <ORGANIZATION> ATC </ORGANIZATION> also said that Paramount has indicated in a court filing in <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION> that it wo n't meet the July 5 deadline set in its tender offer for Time. Asked for a response, <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> said it intends to extend the expiration date of its tender offer until after the <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> court decision. Paramount also said it expects to get cable franchise approval `` where required by state and local law in an orderly and expeditious way.'' In its amended complaint in the <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> court, <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> argues that <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION>'s management `` launched a massive campaign to block the Paramount offer'' before <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION>'s board made its public statement on the merits of the offer. The complaint said that before the board acted, <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> wrote to at least 22 state attorneys general, urging them to oppose any action by Paramount to get quick approval of its offer. Paramount said Time failed in moving the date of its annual meeting to June 30 from June 23 to adjust the May 1 record date for eligibility to vote, even though the company acknowledged that a large number of shares have since changed hands. It also noted the meeting will not deal with any aspect of the <ORGANIZATION> Time-Warner </ORGANIZATION> merger plan but only election of directors, who are unopposed. `` The board's action make one thing clear: Time is being run solely for the benefit of its management,'' the suit said.
