<HEAD>Dollar Plunges, Stocks Slide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar plunged against the Japanese yen today, while the <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>'s main index fell slightly. The dollar closed at 141.40 yen, down 3.55 yen from Wednesday's close of 144.95 yen It opened at 141.75 yen, its high for the day, and fell as low as 140.35 yen. It was the dollar's lowest close since 140.65 yen on June 5. It had climbed to 151.30 a week ago. The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues lost 20.31 points, or 0.06 percent, ending at 33,324.97. The index, a 111.81-point gainer the previous day, inched up in early trading today, then turned downward. <PERSON> Kenji </PERSON> <PERSON> Ishizuka </PERSON>, a dealer with <ORGANIZATION> Daiwa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, said the market lost energy and became directionless after its early gains. `` Following last week's large losses, the market's energy has not come back yet,'' he said. Affected by large swings in the dollar-yen exchange rate, the <ORGANIZATION> Nikkei </ORGANIZATION> lost more than 1,100 points last week. Most investors retreated to the sidelines in the afternoon session, making trading thin, <PERSON> Ishizuka </PERSON> said. Volume traded on the first section was estimated at 550 million shares, down from Wednesday's 600 million. On the foreign exchange market, traders said expectations for a higher dollar had disappeared after its sharp downswing in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> overnight, triggered by reports of new government efforts to hold it below 140 yen. <PERSON> Masafumi </PERSON> <PERSON> Koyama </PERSON>, an analyst with the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo </ORGANIZATION>, said any rumors or remarks suggesting a lower dollar could be a strong dollar-selling incentive now. `` A majority of Japanese investors sold the dollar, trying to see how far they could push it down to reach an appropriate dollar-yen rate,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Japan </ORGANIZATION> reportedly sold dollars to help push the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency down, but neither the amount nor the intervention itself had been confirmed, <PERSON> Koyama </PERSON> said. `` The market took the central bank action as showing its intention to eventually push the dollar below the 140 yen mark,'' he said. <PERSON> Koyama </PERSON> said it still was too early to determine the market trend. `` That's why many investors have been avoiding major moves, and just making position adjustments,'' he added.
