<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As automakers adopt inflatable air bags as a means of meeting tighter requirements for safety restraints, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> says it will install driver's - side air bags on all its About 1 million <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> cars will have the devices in the coming model year, the No. 3 automaker said Wednesday. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> said driver's - side air bags will be standard on 15 of its 1990 car lines, or about <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> said it will install them on nine major lines, an expected 1 million cars. `` Part of it is meeting the passive restraint requirements,'' <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON> said, adding that company surveys show safety is a top concern among customers. In addition to air bags, <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> is equipping 17 of its U.S.-built 1990 models with rear-seat lap and shoulder belts rather than just lap belts. The automaker also will offer antilock braking systems on 26 of its more than 30 car and truck lines in 1990, he said. Starting in 1990, federal regulations require front-seat passive restraints in cars, comprising either manual safety belts supplemented by driver's - side air bags or passive belt systems, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> spokeswoman <PERSON> Toni </PERSON> Passive restraints do n't require an action such as buckling a seat belt. Passive belt systems are partly anchored to the car door so the belt wraps around the occupant when the door is closed. By 1993, air bag protection or passive belts will be required for front seat passengers as well as drivers, <PERSON> Simonetti </PERSON> said. Passenger-side air bags are in the works but are harder to design, she and <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON> said. `` The driver is in a fixed position, plus you have a natural home for the air bag in the steering wheel assembly,'' <PERSON> Dunn </PERSON> said. `` On the passenger side you have to engineer it to travel a greater distance, and you do n't know what position the passenger might be in.''
