<HEAD>Anti-Takeover Plan Enacted at Disney</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Walt </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has adopted a `` poison pill'' anti-takeover defense but says it does not know of any prospective bids for the company. The plan adopted by <ORGANIZATION> Disney </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors and announced Wednesday would entitle present stockholders to buy new stock at half price in the event of a hostile takeover attempt. Such plans dilute the holdings of a potential buyer, making a buyout without management consent prohibitively expensive. The plan is similar to those adopted at many <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> corporations in recent years, and has been under consideration at Disney for several months, said spokesman <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Deegan </PERSON>. `` It was not as a result of anything that has happened in the last several weeks,'' <PERSON> Deegan </PERSON> said. He was referring to the three-way buyout battle among <ORGANIZATION> Paramount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Time </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Warner </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, and to a trend toward consolidation of media giants. `` While we are not aware of any effort to acquire control of the company, the stockholder rights plan represents a sound and reasonable means of safeguarding the interests of all stockholders,'' <PERSON> Disney </PERSON> said in a news release.
