<HEAD>Pizza Chain Says No Drivers Under 18</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Domino's <ORGANIZATION> Pizza </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, the subject of criticism for a series of fatal traffic accidents involving its delivery drivers, has told its stores to fire or reassign drivers who are under the age of 18, a spokesman said Thursday. Domino's spokesman <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Hingst </PERSON> said federal law prohibited the comapny from hiring drivers younger than 18, but in some cases people hired for other tasks have ended up delivering pizzas. Company-owned stores were being told that employees under 18 who drive should be fired or given other jobs, <PERSON> Hingst </PERSON> said. The move will affect about 300 employees at Domino's company-owned stores, about one-third of the Domino's 5,000 stores nationally, he said. The remaining two-thirds of the stores are franchises, which were being urged to make the same move, <PERSON> Hingst </PERSON> said. The company's directive led to confusion at a <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, Domino's store that gave pink slips to all its under-18 employees on Wednesday. Those under 18 who do n't drive were rehired later that day, the company stated. `` There was some miscommunication on our part,'' <PERSON> Hingst </PERSON> said. Domino's has acknowledged 20 fatal accidents in the last year involving its drivers, but denies the company's 29-year-old promise to deliver pizza within 30 minutes of a telephone order encourages employees' reckless driving. A 17-year-old Domino's driver, <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Colson </PERSON>, was killed earlier this month when his small pickup truck skidded on a rain-slicked <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> road and hit a utility pole. His mother has claimed he was speeding and that Domino's guarantee was `` an invitation to break the law. Domino's has stated it knows of 20 fatalities involving Domino's drivers, pedestrians and others last year, but that accidents were bound to happen with such a large fleet, believed to be about 75,000 to 80,000 drivers <PERSON> Hingst </PERSON> said the directive on drivers under 18 was `` a reminder to follow the guidelines.''
