<HEAD>Senate Defeats GOP Child Care Plan</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Combines pvs files; lead with vote on Democratic leadership
plan expected within 20 minutes</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> today defeated a White House-backed child-care plan offered by Republicans as an alternative to a broader program sponsored by the chamber's <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> leadership. The <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> plan, defeated on a 56-44 vote, relied almost exclusively on tax credits, an approach Democrats said would not address the need for more child-care openings and improved quality of services. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> then immediately took up the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> leadership plan, which combines direct subsidies to help parents and states pay for child care with a tax-relief package similar to that proposed by the Republicans. The leadership plan was expected to win approval but, under an agreement between the parties, would still be subject to amendments. A final vote was not expected until Friday. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Maine </LOCATION>, said President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had refused to discuss a compromise on child care, forcing the partisan showdown. `` We've expressed an interest in talking to the White House all along,'' <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> told reporters before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> convened. `` The president and his aides have adamantly refused.'' Today's votes came a week after the start of debate dominated by floor speeches by co-authors of the revised Act for Better Child Care, Sens. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>, D-Conn., and <PERSON> Orrin </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Utah </LOCATION>, defending it against <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> attack The Dodd-Hatch bill would authorize $ 1.75 billion for fiscal 1990 to help parents and states pay for child care. Seventy percent of the money would help parents pay for child care, while the remaining 30 percent would be available to the states for programs designed to improve the availability and quality of care. The revised <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> bill, in the form of an amendment offered by <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, includes two tax changes. One would provide up to a $ 500 credit to low-income families to pay for children's health insurance. The other would make the existing dependent care tax credit refundable to low-income families, some of whom otherwise do not benefit from the provision because they have no federal tax liability to which to apply the credit. In promoting their alternative, <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> senators have argued that the <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> bill's subsidy provisions would result in state bureaucracies that would limit parental choice in child care, a position <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON> and <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> have vigorously contested. `` We have a decidedly different approach to what is a real problem,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Coats </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ind </LOCATION>. `` The word ` choice' is the critical distinction.'' Sen. <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, R-Calif., said the <LOCATION> Dodd-Hatch </LOCATION> plan would `` give to government the decision as to what kind of child care shall be provided. The GOP package would also make the dependent care credit refundable. Its other major provision would expand the existing Earned Income Tax Credit to provide addition tax relief to low-income families with children under age 5. <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, calling that inadequate, said Wednesday the expanded credit would provide $ 750 to a poor family with two eligible children while child care for the two would cost about $ 6,000 a year. Also, he said, using the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> tax credits alone likely will not solve child-care problems because parents would not be required to spend the money on child care. Democrats have also attacked the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> plan for cutting off eligibility for the expanded credits at age 4, saying children twice that age and more need child care. The Dodd-Hatch bill allows payments for children up to age 13.
</TEXT>
