<HEAD>Bass Makes Offer to Integrated Resources, Source Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> investor <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Bass </PERSON> has talked with <ORGANIZATION> Integrated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> about investing in the financially troubled real estate and insurance concern in exchange for a controlling stake, a source said Thursday. Integrated is meeting with several interested parties, including <PERSON> Bass </PERSON>, about receiving a large capital infusion after the company last week announced plans to refinance $ 955 million in short-term debt, the source, who asked not be identified, said. The Wall Street Journal reported Thursday that a Bass-led group could be willing to pump as much as $ 200 million into Integrated conditional on Integrated stock and bond holders accepting a restructuring. Integrated had announced it would put up almost all of its $ 7.8 billion in assets and sharply cut back operations after defaulting on oustanding bonds and commercial paper because of a cash shortage. The Bass group would emerge with much of the equity while the company's common stock would be diluted, the Journal said. Bondholders would have the security of of a new investor. An Integrated spokesman, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Caouette </PERSON>, declined to comment on the newspaper report. After a delayed opening on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, Integrated was up 75 cents a share at $ 4.75 in mid-afternoon trading. The company's stock has plunged from $ 15 last week and $ 40 in 1986. Bass, whose widespread holdings include the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Howell </PERSON> and various media, cable television and real estate properties, is believed to be interested in Integrated's network of financial consultants who sell a wide variety of investments ranging from insurance to real estate The New York-based concern has 35 subsidiaries and 750,000 investor accounts. The Journal said <PERSON> Bass </PERSON> believes he would be able to calm the concerns of <ORGANIZATION> Integrated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION>' bankers long enough to allow the company to develop its financial products. Bass does not think the company's real estate problems are so great, and he also believes the company's newer products like insurance and leveraged buyout fund investments are sound, the paper reported. Under its proposed restructuring, Integrated would replace $ 955 million in short-term debt with secured borrowings. The company also said it would cut back its operations substantially. The company, which has $ 1.1 billion in capital, also said it would concentrate on its core businesses of money management and mutual funds, variable insurance products and limited partnerships. Its debt to be restructured includes outstanding short-term bank debt, domestic and European commercial paper and notes outstanding under loan-sale programs. About 50 banks are providing short-term loans to Integrated and the company said it has about 50 to 75 holders of commercial paper and notes under loan-sale programs.
