<HEAD>Former Trader Pleads Innocent In Securities Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VERA HALLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former Wall Street trader <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mulheren </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> pleaded innocent Thursday to charges he assisted the securities fraud schemes of <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>, the jailed stock speculator he is accused of plotting to kill. <PERSON> Mulheren </PERSON>, 39, of <LOCATION> Rumson </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, was arraigned before a federal magistrate in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> on a 42-count indictment handed up last week. <PERSON> Mulheren </PERSON> was charged with manipulating the price of <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> common stock at <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>'s request and arranging a series of sham stock transactions to help <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON> companies evade taxes and circumvent securities laws. Last month, <PERSON> Mulheren </PERSON> pleaded innocent in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> to state weapons possession charges in connection with an alleged plot on <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>'s life. <PERSON> Mulheren </PERSON> was arrested in February 1988 near his home with a loaded semiautomatic rifle that local authorities alleged he planned to use against <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>. He previously had been charged in federal court with threatening a witness stemming from the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> case and was freed on $ 20 million bond. Federal officials have never identified the alleged target, but <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION> police have said it was <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>. Prosecutors said the federal charge of threatening a witness would be dropped in favor of the state weapons possession charges. At a bail hearing on the securities case, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Miriam </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldman </PERSON> <PERSON> Cedarbaum </PERSON> denied defense attorney <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Puccio </PERSON>'s request to reduce his bond <PERSON> Puccio </PERSON> argued that <PERSON> Mulheren </PERSON> poses no danger to the community and that the bond was unreasonably high. But because the defense had not shown the bond caused <PERSON> Mulheren </PERSON> hardship, <PERSON> Cedarbaum </PERSON> said: `` I am not persuaded that I should reduce the bail that is in place today.'' <PERSON> Mulheren </PERSON> was charged with conspiracy, securities fraud, mail fraud and keeping fraudulent records. If convicted, he faces a maximum five years in prison and $ 250,000 in fines on each count. <PERSON> Mulheren </PERSON> was a general partner and chief trader at <ORGANIZATION> Jamie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION>, a now-defunct <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> investment and arbitrage firm. Also arraigned with <PERSON> Mulheren </PERSON> Thursday was <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> DeStefano </PERSON>, 32, a former trader at <PERSON> Jamie </PERSON>. He was named on three counts of conspiracy, mail fraud and fraudulent record keeping. <PERSON> DeStefano </PERSON> also pleaded innocent and was released on $ 125,000 bond. <PERSON> Boesky </PERSON>, whose guilty plea led to a series of Wall Street investigations, is serving a three-year sentence at a minimum security prison in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. He also paid $ 100 million in fines and restitution to settle civil insider trading charges in late 1986.
