Hanson </PERSON> `` to impress upon him the true worth of Gold Fields,'' an indication he might seek a sweetened bid. Gold Fields shares had fallen after a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> court in April refused to lift an injunction blocking on antitrust grounds the takeover attempt by <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION>, which is controlled by <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s powerful Oppenheimer mining family. <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION> had argued it would sell Gold Fields' stakes in <ORGANIZATION> Newmont </ORGANIZATION> and a number of other major mining operations if its takeover succeeded, but the court sided with government concerns that the acquisition of Gold Fields sizable holdings could lessen competition in gold and strategic metals markets. <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION> had received acceptances of its offer from about 25 percent of Gold Fields' shareholders which, combined with the 29.9 percent it already owned, would have given <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION> control of Gold Fields. `` Unlike <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> is a serious company and any approach from it has to be carefully considered,'' said <PERSON> Agnew </PERSON>. `` However, <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON>'s opening offer completely fails to reflect the value of Gold Fields. It would benefit <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON>'s shareholders but it does not sufficiently benefit ours.'' <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION> Chief Executive <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwardes </PERSON> said his company viewed the sale of its Gold Fields shares to <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> as `` a very satisfactory outcome.'' <ORGANIZATION> Minorco </ORGANIZATION> would receive 915.2 million pounds, $ 1.43 billion, from the sale of its 64 million shares. <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> is involved in tobacco, bricks, electricals, cement, tools and other basic industries and made pretax profits last year of $ 1.37 billion. In t