<HEAD>Oil Executive Blasts Bush Proposal on Non-Gasoline Cars</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 4th graf to CORRECT million to billion. Also moved on general
news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A representative of the major oil companies on Thursday attacked President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s clean-air proposal involving methanol-powered cars, saying it could add to public health risks without significantly improving air quality. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> DiBona </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, told a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> panel the oil industry was unhappy with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal for requiring the use of cars powered by methanol to reduce certain smog-causing pollutants. `` Methanol fuel use is unlikely to result in significant air quality improvements, raises serious public health concerns because of methanol's high toxicity, and will not enhance national energy security significantly,'' <PERSON> DiBona </PERSON> said. The oil industry produces about 110 billion gallons of gasoline a year. It currently does not have the capacity to produce large quantities of alternative fuels. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said his proposals, announced June 12 as part of a broad package of measures aimed at making the air cleaner, would combat smog in urban areas by reducing emissions of carbon monoxide, while also limiting toxic pollutants such as benzene. It would require that 500,000 alternative-fuel cars be built by 1995. <PERSON> DiBona </PERSON> told a subcommittee of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Banking, <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Urban </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> that consumers will pay more per mile for methanol than gasoline, will need to fill up more frequently because methanol burns less efficiently, and may have more problems starting their cars in cold weather because methanol needs more heat to start burning. `` Under a methanol mandate, consumers would have to bear these costs and yet not receive a significant overall improvement in air quality,'' <PERSON> DiBona </PERSON> said. <PERSON> DiBona </PERSON> also said limited domestic supplies of natural gas _ the cheapest source for methanol _ meant <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal could undermine national security. This is because the extra supplies of natural gas would come, at least in part, from the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>, thus adding to American dependence on an unstable region, he said. <PERSON> DiBona </PERSON> also criticized <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposals for reducing gasoline's volatility, or its ability to evaporate into the atmosphere, and for requiring gasoline pump controls aimed at reducing the amount of vapors escaping into the air
</TEXT>
