<HEAD>Inland, USW Reach Accord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steelworkers </ORGANIZATION> union said it reached a tentative four-year contract settlement Thursday with <ORGANIZATION> Inland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> that raises wages in each of the first three years, improves pensions and avoids any worker concessions. `` We're going to recommend it, and it does meet all the goals our members helped formulate. I think they'll accept it,'' said <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Parton </PERSON>, director of <ORGANIZATION> USW </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> 31 and chief negotiator with the nation's fourth-largest steel producer. Inland originally wanted concessions, including the right to schedule workers for a 12-hour work day, <PERSON> Parton </PERSON> said. The company also wanted the employees to help pay medical insurance premiums. Both demands were withdrawn by company negotiators. Incentive pay will be increased in the fourth year, and the agreement also improves pension benefits and resolves differences over the status of maintenance jobs, he said. Inland's workers gave no wage concessions in the 1986 negotiations, so there was no restoration of past sacrifices. The talks began March 7, earliest among four major producers who shared July 31 contract expirations. By a self-imposed settlement deadline of March 31, Inland still was demanding concessions and had offered no wage increase, <PERSON> Parton </PERSON> said. `` We had n't had a raise in about eight years, when inflation was 22 percent. The company made a big buck. Management got raises. They deserve raises, but so do we,'' <PERSON> Parton </PERSON> said. By late May `` we still could n't convince our counterparts that our members were entitled to share in those profits,'' he said. `` We started preparing for a strike.'' The 12,000 <ORGANIZATION> USW </ORGANIZATION> members at Inland were hearing late in the bargaining that a sticking point remained over wage increases in the first year, and their fellow union members at <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> this week surprised negotiators by rejecting a 50-month offer in part because it offered less money up front than workers accepted from <ORGANIZATION> Bethlehem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The Inland settlement came around 4 a.m. in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>, where the company is based.
