<HEAD>Eastern Pilot Flew with Broken Foot, Paper Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal investigators are looking into a charge that an <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> pilot with a broken foot and two newly hired co-pilots flew into a difficult South American airport, a newspaper reported Thursday. Eastern union sources said the captain, <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Neville </PERSON>, suffered a broken foot in a car accident June 15 on his way to the airport in <LOCATION> Asuncion </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Paraguay </LOCATION>. Despite the injury, <PERSON> Neville </PERSON> continued flying even though a broken foot could make him unqualified for duty, the sources told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, for an article published Thursday. One stop on the flight was in <LOCATION> La </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Paz </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>, an airport <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s operations manual designates as one at which only the captain can make takeoffs and landings. The airport is in the mountains, and nearby terrain rises 8,000 feet above the airport. Flying an airliner with such an injury is dangerous because foot pedals help steer the plane and heavy pressure is required in some wind conditions or if an engine fails, the union sources said. Eastern officials said the claim was an effort by its striking unions to hurt the airline by raising doubts about its safety. `` This type of manufactured, alleged incident is typical of the safety-related scare tactics that -LRB- the pilots union -RRB- is using at this point,'' <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Robin </PERSON> <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> said <PERSON> Neville </PERSON> did n't feel he had been incapacitated after the auto accident. After returning to <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, the captain was checked out by <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s medical department and his private physician and was cleared to continue flying with a hairline fracture in his foot, <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> said. `` This is not the type of thing you would even put a cast on,'' <PERSON> Matell </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Neville </PERSON>, a resident of <PERSON> Davie </PERSON>, near <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, has an unlisted phone number and could not be reached for comment. `` The -LRB- pilots union -RRB- called it to our attention last weekend, and we're looking into it,'' said <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Barker </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>. The medical report is being sent to the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> but has not yet arrived, <PERSON> Barker </PERSON> said. Besides the captain, the cockpit crew reportedly included two recent graduates of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s pilot training program. Pilots union spokesman <PERSON> Hank </PERSON> <PERSON> Weber </PERSON> called <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Paz </PERSON> `` the most dangerous'' airport in Eastern's system because of the mountains. He also said Eastern has scaled back training aimed at helping new pilots handle <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> flights because of its need to train them quickly. Eastern suffered a fatal crash into a <LOCATION> Bolivian </LOCATION> mountainside five years ago. The union has charged that the company, moving ahead with a rebuilding plan relying mainly on newly hired pilots, is risking safety by using so many inexperienced pilots.
