<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Phoenix </LOCATION> announced Thursday it will add $ 181 million to its loan-loss reserves and expects a $ 90 million loss in the second quarter as a result. <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arizona </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Utah </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bancorporation </ORGANIZATION> are chief subsidiaries. <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> attributed the action to a deterioration in <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>'s real estate market with no immediate sign of recovery. `` Given that current market conditions make the estimation process difficult, we believe we have taken a conservative view in determining the amount to be added to our reserves,'' <PERSON> Simmons </PERSON> said. Banks take such steps to protect themselves against the possibility that loans wo n't be repaid. The weak property market in the economically depressed <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> has raised the risk of mortgage defaults. <ORGANIZATION> Valley </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> stressed that the corporation's core earnings and financial base remain strong. It projected that a substantial amount of the second quarter loss should be regained by the end of the 1989.
